<HEADLINE>Specialists prepare inhospitable  ground for an army 60,000-strong Americans join Nato peace force</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>PATRICK BROGAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975060993</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE first substantial contingent of American troops will arrive in Bosnia
tomorrow. President Clinton gave the order last night to activate the first
part of the peace plan, and some 700 American communications and logistics
specialists will be sent immediately to Tuzla.
A small number of specialists are already there. They have been examining the
airport to recommend what improvements it needs to cope with 20,000 soldiers.
The full deployment of American and allied troops will begin after the treaty
is finally signed in Paris on December 14, at a ceremony that President Clinton
hopes to attend.
In a press conference in Madrid today, the president said: ``I have authorised
the Secretary of Defence to order the deployment of the preliminary troops to
Bosnia, as I said I would as soon as I was convinced that the military plan was
appropriate.''
He also said that he was not deterred by the defiance of General Ratko Mladic,
who has rejected the peace deal signed in Ohio last month and said it would
have to be reworked.
``No, I don't think the treaty is in trouble and, no, I don't think it should
be renegotiated,'' said Mr Clinton, who is depending on President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia to bring the Bosnian Serbs into line.
The arriving troops' first duty will be to prepare bases and depots for those
who will follow. There is no accommodation for 60,000 allied troops anywhere in
Bosnia, and winter is imminent. Engineers will need to build up the airports in
a hurry, construct barracks and warehouses, and bring in the huge mass of
equipment that a modern army requires.
They last did it in the Gulf in 1990-91. The differences are that the Gulf was
further from base and the operation on a far larger scale.
However, the weather was much better and the allies landing in Saudi Arabia
were sure of their welcome. They are not at all sure in Bosnia.
The allies all have the authority to defend themselves with whatever force is
appropriate. American television and newspapers are full of stories of Islamic
mujahideen fighters from Afghanistan, Iran, and Egypt who have gone to Bosnia
to fight for the faith and who distrust the allies as much as they do the Serbs
and Croats.
The British, too, have encountered mujahideen forces. One of the next tasks for
the diplomats will be to persuade the Bosnian Government to disarm them and
send them packing.
On the home front, Republican leaders have now fallen into line behind the
president. Senator Bob Dole, Republican leader in the Senate, after a period of
hesitation has come out unequivocally in support. He follows the old-fashioned
line that it is Congress's duty to support the commander-in-chief.
He hopes to attain that position himself, of course, in a year's time, but
seems to be motivated by genuine principle. His stand has silenced critics in
the Senate - except for the egregious Senator Phil Gramm, who is also running
for president - and even in the House. The speaker, Newt Gingrich, has been
notably and uncharacteristically moderate on the issue.
q Mr Clinton ended his European tour by meeting Spanish Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez in Madrid yesterday to sign a wide range of joint aims including
committment of support to the Middle East peace process, development of East
European nations, and the non-proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</TEXT>
