<HEADLINE>Management skills attacked in CBI report</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHRIS STONE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975060994</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POOR management skills are often at the root of the problems of many small and
medium sized enterprises (SMEs), inhibiting their growth, according to a new
report from the Confederation of British Industry.
A key weakness identified in the report is the lack of rigorous evaluation of
the different types of support available to SMEs, especially in terms of help
from the Government.
The report, entitled Managing to Grow, says that Business Links, the
one-stop-shop advice centres for small businesses, should play an essential
role in a Government drive to enhance SME management development.
It calls for a number of measures to ensure that Business Links fulfil their
full potential. These include ensuring an adequate level of long-term funding,
the delivery of all Government SME services through Business Links making sure
it represents a true one-stop-shop, the need for large firms, banks, and
accountancy firms to encourage their clients and suppliers to use the service,
and promoting and effectively evaluating the performance of Business Links.
The report recognises that there will only be a limited number of personal
business advisers available through Business Links and proposes the
establishment of a national network of business mentors.
Meanwhile, another report out today claims that more than a quarter of
Britain's 1.2 million limited companies are loss-making while two-thirds of
those are high-risk debtors, potentially unable to fulfill their credit
commitments to suppliers.
The report says that, as a result, many businesses find they are running up bad
debts and jeopardising their own financial stability by supplying goods and
services to customers who are unlikely to pay for them.
ICC, one of the UK's leading providers of company and industry data which
carried out the research, says the findings have grave implications for many
British companies.
</TEXT>
