<HEADLINE>Driving force behind firm's bid to get into black</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975060996</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CHANGE has never scared Bill Kane. He has thrived on it from the day he decided
after two years as a young trainee with a Glasgow firm of chartered accountants
and three failed attempts at the taxation exam that his future lay elsewhere.
Now, at 37, he is steering Edinburgh-based paint manufacturers and
wall-covering distributors Craig and Rose, suppliers of paint to the Forth
Bridge, through its most intensive period of change since being established in
1829.
Brought into the company in June as commercial director on a contract that was
initially to last only to the end of this year, Mr Kane was promoted at the end
of October to managing director with a remit to supervise its return to
financial health after being in the red since 1991.
He was brought up in the village of Ferniegair, near Hamilton, and studied
business and accountancy at Bell College. After two years in chartered
accountancy, he spent a year in the internal audit section of the Glasgow
electrical and engineering group James Scott, of Finnieston. In 1984, he joined
the Hertz car rental organisation, working from London on financial and
operation audits throughout Europe.
His next stop was something completely different. In 1991, he was recruited as
finance manager and company secretary of Light and Sound Design, which rented
equipment to rock concert organisers in the UK and the United States, and had
become part of Christian Salvesen.
He became managing director three years later and sold the business on for
Salvesen in May this year, which freed him to join Craig and Rose.
The drive to bring the company out of the red began before Mr Kane arrived. It
had already been decided to close down its loss making depot at Dartford, near
London, a move which has made the major contribution to reducing the workforce
to 70 from an average of 110 last year.
Cost-saving measures have included the shedding of the company's own fleet of
vans and farming out distribution.
Administration and stock control, handled manually until now, is being
computerised. Steps are also in the pipeline to improve sales, particularly in
the north of England, where the company may open a depot, and from the Glasgow
depot in Lawmoor Road, which is likely to be re-sited as the existing premises
are covered by a compulsory purchase order because of the M74 extension.
Mr Kane is particularly proud of the recent refurbishing of the company's Leith
Walk showroom, which he sees not only as an essential step to improve the image
conveyed to customers but as a way of boosting staff morale.
</TEXT>
