<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Cuts in Britain's aid budget</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061000</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AS representatives in Scotland of major overseas aid agencies, we are dismayed
that the issue of aid cuts has now come so far down the agenda of public
interest that it was not even mentioned in your paper.
In the Budget an aid cut of 5.4% (6.7% in real terms) was imposed which will be
a real blow for some of the world's poorest people. Compared with plans
announced in last year's Budget, aid in 1996/97 will be cut by #124m in cash
terms - from #2278m to #2154m.
The money being cut would be enough to fund the combined programmes in Africa
of six of the largest UK aid agencies, but the money the Treasury will save
will only be worth an extra 16 pence a week off the income-tax bill of someone
on average earnings.
This level of cut does not reflect public opinion. A recent Harris opinion poll
which told people that the Government spends only 31p in every #100 of national
wealth on overseas aid, found that 79% of respondents thought that this amount
should stay the same or be increased while only 10% favoured cuts.
The aid cuts will severely damage some of the best parts of Britain's aid
programme for the sake of a few pence in the average pay packet.
Eildon Dyer, Christian Aid; Peter Chirnside, Tearfund; John Dornan, SCIAF;
Marie Hearle, Oxfam; Don Harrison, Save The Children; 759a Argyle Street,
Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000008</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000008</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Innovators who built on their vision</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lucy Lockhart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061001</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TURNING vision into reality is the phrase which architects and planning
consultants, Holmes Partnership, consider summarises succinctly what they are
all about.
Currently they are celebrating the manifestation of their own vision: a
prestigious yet good value building at 89 Minerva Street, for their Glasgow
practice, custom-built to their own design. It was officially opened last week
by Malcolm Campbell, president of the Glasgow Chamber of Commerce.
``There are many reasons why we moved from our old offices in Kelvingrove
Street,'' said managing partner Robin Th'ng. ``Most of our clients and
colleagues are in the West End of Glasgow. We wanted to be around this area
rather than in the city centre. We have car parking, and it is very accessible
from the motorway, both from Edinburgh - where we also have an office - and the
city.
``We have been able to design, develop and build exactly what we want. How we
work is how we create, so that's very important.''
The two-storey rectangularly shaped building has been kept to the rear of the
site, with car parking to the front. The simple design has been given added
interest by the glazed front wall having been set at a slight angle, while the
oversailing roof's aerofoil eaves detail - echoed in the smaller roof over the
entrance lobby - forms a skyline the dynamics of which become more striking the
closer visitors get to the front door.
At ground level, wide glass doors lead into a pale, elegantly appointed
reception foyer and exhibition area where generous use has been made of natural
timber. On either side are two meeting rooms, while to the rear are the
administration area, storerooms, kitchen and toilets.
The exhibition space, in addition to displaying the practice's projects, ``will
be used,'' Dr Th'ng explains, ``to exhibit interesting things that are going
on. When it comes to Glasgow's Door Open day each year, we will be open to the
public and, for example, we will sponsor students, and enable them to show
their work as part of our philosophy, and as a contribution to the community.''
The first-floor level is an entirely open-plan office studio with a wall of
windows to the west and rooflights to the rear, combining to make an
exceptionally bright workplace.
An electronic trade and reference library coupled with other CAD/IT systems
have reduced the necessity for hard copy storage and shelving.
The seven partners at Holmes would like to think, says Robin Th'ng: ``that we
were the trendsetters in our business rather than trend followers. We are
innovators, and we like to think that we are the leaders in our field in
Scotland.
``In our use of technology too, we are creators. There is not a single drawing
board in our offices. I can't think of another practice in Scotland which can
claim that. We are full on CAD and fully into all sorts of IT in terms of using
PCs to communicate throughout our offices with our colleagues and our clients.
``What is important is that we are still very creative in our design approach.
We have that creativity together with the technology. We are also very
conscious of issues, such as environmentally friendly buildings, of which much
has been preached, but little done.
``Our own building we are proud of, we describe it as very environmentally
friendly. This is illustrated by the fact that the building's performance
attains the standard ``very good'' when calculated using the BRE Environmental
Assessment method. The building is very easy also for wheelchair users or
disabled people, being entirely level from the car park and throughout the
ground floor.''
The Holmes Partnership's two practices are run as one unit, partners in the
West also work on projects in the East and vice-versa. ``Ours is a very
dynamic, exciting partnership,'' enthuses Dr Th'ng. ``It is a great advantage
to be able to do what you want to do, enjoy it and also get a reward. We have
been fortunate to have kept busy throughout the recession, despite the
construction industry having suffered badly.
``Our new building is a reflection of all that, it is making a statement, and
it is our own little contribution towards Glasgow's 1999 City of Architecture
and Design.''
Robin Th'ng has been the managing partner of both the Glasgow and Edinburgh
offices for nine years. He said: ``As a practice we are very focussed in what
we want to do. The areas in which we specialise are urban design, urban
renewal, planning work, commercial work, educational projects and residential
projects.
``Our clients often come to us and say: ``We have a vision,'' and indeed they
do. We have to make that into a reality - that is fundamentally our role.''
Among some of the high profile examples of the work of The Holmes Partnership
is the distinctive office building at 100 Bothwell Street, Glasgow, designed
for a London developer; the Inland Revenue and Customs and Excise Building on
Dundee's Riverfront; the newly-completed #2.5m refurbishment of the Bank of
Scotland's flagship branch in the West of Scotland at the corner of Glasgow's
Queen Street and Ingram Street; the new #12.5m Royal Mail centre opposite the
M8 Interchange on the Edinburgh City by-pass; and the recently-completed
refurbishment of the University of Glasgow's large sports and recreation
building.
Again for the university, Holmes' mixed skills are demonstrated well by two
projects: a Victorian listed terrace of some 11 units which is being converted
to a department of computing science. Every room and wall has been opened in
order to create one single building, while retaining the original facade and a
number of outstanding features.
A recent project is the addition of a 12th floor and new roof to the lofty
tower which is the university library. Work for housing associations;
restoration, including the on-going restoring of Laurieston House in Carlton
Place, Glasgow, for a Government organisation; public housing and private
clients; projects for health boards, often in the planning and development of
redundant hospital sites; and work for local enterprise companies, district or
regional councils, are all part of Holmes' project portfolio.
The seven widely experienced partners in the Holmes Partnership are: Robin
Th'ng, BArch, PhD, FRIAS, RIBA, FIMgt, ACIArb. Charles Strong, BArch, FRIAS,
RIBA. Harold Phillips, BArch, FRIAS, RIBA, MSAI. Neil Maxwell, BSc, BArch,
ARIAS, RIBA. Allan Martin, BArch, ARIAS, RIBA. Douglas Fraser, BArch, ARIAS,
RIBA. Brian Henderson, DIPArch, ARIAS, RIBA.
</TEXT>
