<DOCNO>GH951204-000009</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000009</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Yacht owners launch wave of protest against CalMac</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061002</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CALEDONIAN MacBrayne is at the centre of a storm over the speed of its car and
passenger vessels entering and leaving west coast harbours.
It is claimed that bow waves from the ferry operator's ships are causing damage
to yachts and that it is only a matter of time before someone is seriously
injured.
Two vessels - the Lord of the Isles and the Isle of Mull, both of which operate
the Oban to Mull service - are the target of complaints from private boat
owners. Yachtsmen say the speed of the ferries as they enter and leave Oban
harbour is excessive and is causing huge bow waves that have:
q Caused more than #1000 of damage to two yachts tied alongside each other;
q Torn the deck mountings off a 30ft motor cruiser tied to a pontoon; and
q Almost washed 12 people off a pontoon as they waited for an island ferry.
Despite mounting complaints to HM Coastguard, pier masters and the police, and
letters to the company, boat owners say Caledonian MacBrayne skippers are
refusing to slow down.
Private boats using pontoons in Rothesay harbour on the Isle of Bute have also
experienced severe wave motion as the Wemyss Bay ferry approaches.
Retired Merchant Navy officer Alex Clark, from Tain, in Ross and Cromarty, says
CalMac are a ``law unto themselves'' when it comes to the high seas.
He said: ``We know that ferry captains have timetables to keep, but so has the
70,000-ton QE2, but when she came into the Cromarty Firth recently there was
hardly a ripple.
``This battle with CalMac at Oban has been going on for years but it is getting
worse, but it will only be time before someone is seriously injured.''
In one incident at Oban Yacht Club, a member's dog was catapulted from the
boat's wheelhouse into the sea when the wash from the ferry struck. Paint tins
were spilled over the yacht's decks. The dog was saved.
Yachtsmen were amazed, however, when, earlier this year the Queen arrived in
Oban aboard Britannia. The CalMac ferry entered the harbour area without a wave
in sight, according to locals.
Caledonian MacBrayne is unrepentant, saying that its Oban-Mull ferries each
displace about 3000 tons of water and this has to go somewhere, according to
Captain Sandy Ferguson, a former captain on the Oban-Mull route, now marine
superintendent for CalMac.
He said: ``I was master of the Isle of Mull vessel for the past four years, and
I know what it's all about. Our ferries slow right down on their approach to
Oban, and by the time they get to the entrance they are doing five knots at the
most and decelerating.
``We are responsible people and all our masters approach every harbour at a
prudent speed, but unfortunately there will always be a certain amount of wash
from a ferry.
``We get yachtsmen complaining almost on a weekly basis that CalMac ferries
have damaged their boats. This is particularly frequent at Oban. But we do not
accept any claims whatsoever and we will fight every case put to us.
``The last person who took us to court two years ago withdrew on the courtroom
steps, as he could not prove we caused the damage to his boat. He had to pay
our legal costs.''
The Royal Highland Yacht Club, based at Oban, has written to Caledonian
MacBrayne, raising the concerns of its members and other yachtsmen sailing on
the west coast.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000010</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000010</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>A Bonnie day as Charlie stands his ground again</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061003</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE world's first statue of Bonnie Prince Charlie on horseback was unveiled in
the centre of Derby yesterday - after a battle against public apathy.
The statue was commissioned to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the retreat
of The Young Pretender from the city, the most southerly point the Jacobites
reached in the ill-fated 1745 uprising.
After an inital slow start to an appeal, the #100,000 cost has been met
entirely by public subscription, mainly from the chairman of Derby County
Football Club, Mr Lionel Pickering.
The statue has been placed outside Derby Cathedral, where the prince went to a
thanksgiving service when he arrived in the city.
It was occupied by the prince and his army of 5000 Scottish and English troops
for two nights and three days before a fateful decision to turn back
effectively ended the Jacobite cause.
The bronze statue on a stone plinth was a joint effort between Bristol-based
sculptor Anthony Stones and bronze worker Rungwe Kingdon.
Twelve pipers and members of the Charles Edward Stuart Society dressed in
period costume stood in ceremony as it was unveiled by Lady Scarsdale, whose
husband's ancestors played host to the prince when he arrived in Derby 250
years ago.
Lady Scarsdale said: ``Our family is proud of its association with the
Jacobites and I'm sure the statue will become enormously popular as the Bonnie
Prince Charlie story is known throughout the world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000011</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000011</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Labour contrast</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061004</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
COUNCILLOR Cathie Craigie's second attempt to pour cold water over me (Letters,
November 24) very effectively endorses my case.
The Labour Party was never off the media demanding action for the speedy
implementation of the Nolan Report which demanded the full disclosure of
Parliamentary allowances and income associated with the MPs' salaries.
It has been as silent as the grave in pressing for a similar inquiry in local
government - indeed no date has been published for such an inquiry. With good
reason!
In April 1992 the Secretary of State cut the proportion of special
responsibility allowance from 25% to 10% because there was clear evidence that
the Labour councils would not give a fair proportion of the allocated sum to
minority parties.
To quote one example, North Lanarkshire Council, on which Councillor Craigie
also serves, has 69 councillors being paid #6000 a year basic allowance, a
total of #414,000. Twenty-nine Labour councillors, including Councillor
Craigie, in addition share special responsibility allowances of #254,000.
The sole responsibility allowance paid to the minority is one ``Leader's
allowance'' of #4800.
The special responsibility allowances amount to 62.5% of the council's basic
allowances.
The minority parties who represeent well over 30% of the electorate receive
just over 1% of the basic allowances.
This of course takes no account of the very generous expenses and perks which I
have previously pointed out. These more than double Councillor Craigie's basic
and special responsibility allowances in 1994/95 as leader of Cumbernauld and
Kilsyth District Council.
Councillor Margaret Murray,
29 Binniehill Road,
Cumbernauld
</TEXT>
