<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Statue plea gets a crisp response</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>LACHIE KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061005</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A YOUNG sculptor's plan to move the statue of the Duke of Wellington from
Glasgow`s Royal Exchange Square and replace it with a 40ft statue of a potato
snack is a non-starter - because it would cost too much.
Artist Derek Beggs is believed to have made a planning application to Glasgow
District Council suggesting the Iron Duke be moved to another site to make way
for his crispy snack because the duke is a target for merrymakers who
continually place a traffic cone on his head.
But last night his idea was knocked firmly on the head by Mr Julian Spalding,
the city's director of museums. He said: ``For a start, it would be a massive
building operation to move the duke and would cost far too much, well into six
figures.''
He admitted he would like to see the statue moved from the front of the Gallery
of Modern Art, which opens next February, and added: ``There is certainly
competition to put a cone on his head and I would like to find a way of
stopping this.''
A spokesman for the city council said last night that he could neither confirm
nor deny that Mr Beggs had made a planning application.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000013</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000013</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Trade standholders pleased with the number of visitors and quality of enquiries Successful DairyScot secures future</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Robert Ross, Farming Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061006</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT was an eventful week last week, with three days at Earls Court for the new
Smithfield FarmTech show - and then straight off the plane at Edinburgh to
visit DairyScot at Ingliston.
They were two contrasting events, and if you were asked to put money on which
one would survive it would be DairyScot. That is not to criticise the
Smithfield event but simply a comment on the fact that DairyScot had a lively
buzz to it while FarmTech was more laid back.
Space had a lot to do with it, of course. At Earls Court the show was spread
over a four-acre site and attracted 11,500 visitors over three days. It was
confined to one hall, never felt crowded and, at times, looked sparse compared
with the bustle of the traditional Smithfield Show which takes over the whole
exhibition centre on several floors.
The DairyScot attendance was 3200 in one day and trade standholders were
pleased with the numbers of visitors and the quality of enquiries. Management
committee chairman Alex Brown was able to announce that the event's future had
been secured for the next four years. The Bank of Scotland has agreed to repeat
its sponsorship next year and Mr Brown was confident that the bank would want
to remain on board beyond that.
The Smithfield organisers say that they exceeded their attendance target of
10,000 - at #8 a head - and although it is too early for firm decisions to be
made, the indications are that the exercise will be repeated in 1997.
The reason why there has to be a ``big'' and a ``small'' Smithfield is that the
machinery manufacturers and distributors have decided to make their
participation biennial. This suits their plan to concentrate on a European
circuit of leading events. The consensus view was that they had rather shot
themselves in the foot this year. The arable sector has generally enjoyed good
returns, and good orders would have been ripe for the picking at a traditional
Smithfield.
The absence may actually have done farmers a favour. The message at the show
from one farm business consultant was that the conventional wheeze of buying
expensive machinery as a way of diverting cash away from the tax man is of
doubtful wisdom.
Simon Mountjoy, of Leicester, said that his advice to clients was ``pay the
tax''. He sees the tax regime as benign and profits as historically high in
real terms.
On capital expenditure of #30,000 for a new tractor the first year write-down
allowance would be 25%, giving a total tax saving of #3000 at the higher tax
rate of 40% - only 10% of the capital sum spent. The message, he said, is to
have the right machine in the right place at the right time and not to confuse
effective planning and utilisation of labour and machinery with taxation.
Effective planning, he suggested, would increase profits and actually
exacerbate the tax situation. But he added, drily, that anyone not paying tax
should seriously consider whether they have long-term viability.
Simon's partner, Ian Youdan, reported that farmers were not ready sellers of
land at the moment - although the same could not be said of the financial
institutions. They were seeing price levels as an opportunity to get out of an
investment medium with which they had become increasingly uncomfortable. His
experience is that agricultural investment requires a level of intensive
management which many institutions feel unable to deliver when their own
management facilities are being slimmed down dramatically.
Finally, as Charlie Allan is not reporting on the après-show high jinks at
Smithfield, I can lift just a corner of the veil which is, quite properly,
drawn over the activities of the Scottish press corps.
There is a traditional Sunday night visit to a Chinese restaurant. It fell to
one of our more responsible colleagues to organise the transport and, after
commandeering two taxis, he proceeded to give the most detailed directions he
could muster: ``The Mayflower - it's a Chinese restaurant.'' Full credit to the
London cabby, he got us to the right one.
Once there we found the waiter more anxious about establishing our need for
drink rather than food. His efforts were misdirected, as the need for liquid
refreshment had been attended to - as he might have observed. Eventually one of
our number conceded: ``OK, bring us four bottles of your best white wine.''
``Are you sure sir? Our best wine is #28 a bottle.''
``Oh very well, then - four bottles of house white.''
A compromise, yes. But accomplished with panache.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
