<DOCNO>GH951204-000014</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000014</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chairman stresses need for expansion Amec deal `is vital to future of Kvaerner'</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDREW WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061007</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
KVAERNER chairman Erik Tonseth has made it very clear that the acquisition of
Amec, for which the company has bid a contested #1 a share, is crucial to the
Norwegian shipbuilding and engineering group's long-term future.
Last week, he expressed disappointment that he had not been able to restart
discussions with Amec's Sir Alan Cockshaw after the initial meeting on November
23. That was after the dawn raid made on the advice of advisers SBC Warburg
when Kvaerner raised its stake of several months' standing from 2% to 12%.
Perhaps more important than the benefits from the takeover, Amec would provide
Kvaerner with a British passport. Mr Tonseth regards that as essential for
international expansion, particularly in Asia, where the UK has diplomatic and
financial clout which Norway conspicuously lacks.
He is still upset that Amec's brief flirtation with Alfred McAlpine valued
Amec's shares at just 70p or so, compared with the 100p that he paid. The Amec
feelers were almost immediately rejected by McAlpine which is now seeking to
beef up its board through the reported recruitment of Rolls-Royce chief
executive Sir Terence Harrison as chairman to succeed Sir John Milne.
Kvaerner has argued there is strong industrial logic in putting the two
together. It is a world leader in sub-sea structures whereas Amec has a
powerful position in rig topsides. More importantly, it has the construction
and contracting skills necessary to complete major turnkey projects for both
fuelled and hydro-electric power stations.
Co-operation at present extends to a joint venture bid for a major US contract
where Kvaerner would provide the equipment and Amec would be in overall charge
of construction.
Mr Tonseth, 49, joined Kvaerner seven years ago after it became clear he would
not get the top job at Norsk Hydro. He has been known as Norway's only rugby
player but he said he was trying to forget that, particularly as the match was
in Sweden.
If the bid does succeed, an increasing proportion of Kvaerner's international
business will come to Britain. Mr Tonseth added that the Sea Launch floating
platform project should be finalised within the next three weeks. That
envisages a platform costing over #60m to be built at Kvaerner's Govan shipyard
to provide a base for satellite launch rockets in the Pacific.
The finance is in place but there are still difficulties with the US
authorities over the relationship between Boeing and the Russian and Ukrainian
rocket companies.
This is a revolutionary development and Mr Tonseth said that it would be very
good for Scottish industry.
In a letter to Amec shareholders, Kvaerner stressed the offer was final and
would not be increased unless a rival bidder emerged. It said: ``Your board has
talked about the `true value of Amec's potential' but has not provided any
facts in support. In considering whether to accept our offer, you should
contrast the certainty of our 100p per share in cash now with the uncertain
future value of Amec's shares.
``The difficulty of assessing that future has already been reflected in Alfred
McAlpine's speedy rejection of your board's offer to acquire the company and
that offer itself indicates that your board considers the Amec should not
continue on its own in its present form.''
Kvaerner has steadily increased its stake in Amec following its hostile bid
last week by buying shares in the market and now speaks for 18.1%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
