<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Deli with recipe for success grows into catering empire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<FLAG>feature inside business</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061008</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CATERER Liz McAreavey has come a long way since she opened Le Bistro takeaway
delicatessen in Edinburgh's West End eight years ago. Today she runs a rapidly
expanding outside catering empire.
Earlier this year, Le Bistro Caterers fed more than 7000 visitors to the Tall
Ships Race and it was the Le Bistro which ensured construction workers building
the new Scottish Office did not go hungry.
``The takeaway deli is a very small part of our business,'' said managing
director Ms McAreavey, ``but people still perceive us as a takeaway deli and it
is a perception which we are trying to overcome.''
Le Bistro Caterers is planning to expand into commercial contract catering. ``I
believe that this is an area which is ripe for expansion we are talking to
several companies,'' she said.
The expansion has meant the company is now looking for larger premises, despite
the fact that it only moved into its present premises at Bonnington Mill
Business Centre a few months ago.
``I thought we would be settled their for at least 18 months but we have
outgrown it already,'' said Ms McAreavey.
Le Bistro can find itself providing food for a dozen different functions in a
single day, and this requires a great deal of organisation. ``Until 18 months
ago, you could have found me behind the till at our takeaway but I now realise
that this is not the best use of my time, and that I cannot do everything
myself,'' she said.
Le Bistro Caterers is often used by the Scottish Office to cater for functions
in the Great Hall of Edinburgh Castle and Ms McAreavey admits the guest lists
often frightens her. ``I often get nervous when I see who we will be serving,
so I try not to bother looking.''
To ensure VIP guests are not disappointed with the food, Le Bistro Caterers has
hired top chefs James Davie and Marcus Lane.
Mr Davie was head chef at Prestonfield House Hotel and also worked on the QE2
while Mr Lane has worked at Gleneagles, the Ritz, and the Savoy.
``We try to make sure that our food matches venues such as the Signet Library
and the Great Hall but, whatever we are preparing, whether it be bacon and eggs
for construction workers or a delicacy for a visiting politician, we try to
ensure that it is top quality,'' said Ms McAreavey.
</TEXT>
