<HEADLINE>Meeting scheduled as secret hospital visits to talk to dying patients are disclosed Princess's role on Major agenda</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061011</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE future public role of the Princess of Wales is widely expected to be
discussed at a meeting on Tuesday between the Queen and John Major.
The meeting comes less than a week after the princess sat down with Buckingham
Palace courtiers to put forward her own ideas on her future in the wake of her
dramatic Panorama interview.
It also follows a poll showing that seven out of 10 people support her wish to
be ``queen of hearts'', and the disclosure that she is making late-night visits
to sick and dying hospital patients.
Tuesday's meeting is the traditional routine weekly briefing in which the Prime
Minister visits the Queen at Buckingham Palace.
Both Downing Street and the Palace were yesterday sticking to the rule that no
comment is made about discussions between the Prime Minister and members of the
royal family.
But one Sunday newspaper reported that a new role for the princess was to be
discussed at the meeting. It said there was ``growing nervousness'' among some
Ministers about the possibility of giving her any formal ambassadorial role.
Buckingham Palace confirmed that a meeting was held last week between the
34-year-old princess and senior figures in the Queen's household, although a
spokesman would not give details.
The talks had not taken place in an atmosphere of confrontation, and were
``perfectly amicable'', he said. Further meetings were likely.
This was in line with the palace's announcement after the BBC Panorama
interview that ``we would be talking to the princess again about helping her to
define her future role, and asking in what way we could continue to help her'',
he said.
One paper reported that the princess made a series of demands - for a new image
for the monarchy and for her crowd-pulling potential to be recognised ``and not
derided from within Buckingham Palace''.
Meanwhile, the princess was spotted outside a London hospital in the early
hours of one morning, and explained how she loved helping patients come to
terms with their suffering and loneliness, said the News of the World.
She said of the sick and dying people she visits: ``Some will live and some
won't. But they all need to be loved while they are here.''
Dressed in her baseball cap and jeans, she said she wore a disguise and visited
at night to avoid attention and problems for the hospitals.
``There are hundreds of patients who are there without their own loved ones and
they need a human presence.
``I hold their hands, talk to them, tell them that everyone is on their side,
whatever helps.''
The NOP survey for the Sunday Times showed that, since her Panorama interview,
the princess had attracted more public sympathy.
Two weeks ago only 27% of people had sympathy for her, but the figure has risen
now to 39%.
The Prince of Wales's sympathy rating has dropped, from 10% to 8%. Another 21%
have equal support for the estranged couple while 32% - down from 40% - say
neither has their vote.
Only 36% want the princess to be queen but 50% do not, while 14% don't know.
The poll of 1035 voters was taken on Thursday and Friday.
.q.The Duchess of York has struck up a friendship with a gypsy artist and is
mounting an exhibition of his paintings. She met Paul Gaisford while holidaying
in Spain with her husband and children and became a great fan of his work.
Now she is hoping to win the black-haired 54-year-old a wider audience by
organising a display at Kensington Palace and a top London gallery.
The duchess was on holiday with the duke and their daughters in Seville near
where Mr Gaisford had been giving painting classes.
She was immediately impressed by his oil-paintings of gypsy wagons, flamenco
dancers and men with dogs.
Explaining her passion for his work, she said: ``You can't talk about Paul's
work in generalised terms as it is so diversified. But I like his use of light
and his sense of magic. I see huge depth and inspiration.''
The duchess, who has been taking art appreciation classes with a leading London
art dealer for five years, said of her hobby: ``I'm learning brushstrokes. My
grandmother paints rather nicely and it is from her side that I am a little bit
creative. I certainly have a very vivid imagination.''
The artist has been described as ``a bit of a rough diamond'' by some, and by
the duchess's aides as ``a non-verbal personality''.
His friendship with the duchess has spurred him to great activity, painting 76
works in three months in preparation for the show, which can be seen at the Roy
Miles Gallery, in London's Bruton Street, from December 14 to 16.
The artist will donate part of the proceeds of the display to Children in
Crisis, a charity which the duchess set up in 1993.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
