<HEADLINE>The facts about Catholicism</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061013</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE fact that John MacLeod has got his facts wrong time and time again in the
past never really seems to discourage him (November 28).
There is no tradition in Roman Catholicism of the Pope or the Church being
infallible in everything and anything. There does exist a Doctrine of Papal
Infallibility, which applies only to certain pronouncements on faith or morals,
but this has been invoked only once, in 1950, by Pope Pius XII.
The Catholic Church rightly views the sacrament of marriage as holy and
indissoluble but, in Scotland at least, understands that for many reasons two
people may find it impossible to continue living together as man and wife, and
not necessarily because of the ``fault'' of one partner.
It does deny them certain (but not all) other sacraments, but this does not
extend to excommunication.
As for annulments, these can be notoriously difficult to obtain - Henry VIII of
England is one example - and the process can take up to 10 years or more.
Hardly an alternative to a ``quickie'' divorce.
Things might be better if in future John Macleod kept his writings confined to
topics closer to his own Free Church tradition, rather than using them to voice
his own personal religious prejudices. All your readers, Catholic and
non-Catholic alike, would say ``amen'' to that!
Dr Paolo Capanni,
25 Norfolk Crescent,
Bishopbriggs, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000021</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000021</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unjust to Ferguson</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061014</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
I FIND that instances of manifest injustice in Scotland are more and more
difficult to bear. People seem to be sent to prison far too often for far too
long. We have the highest prison population in Europe.
I write because it is our MP, Menzies Campbell QC, who appears to be associated
with the latest injustice, which concerns the footballer Duncan Ferguson.
On November 8 a three-man appeals tribunal, chaired by North-east Fife MP
Menzies Campbell, decided against the appeal by Mr Ferguson for his 12-match
football ban to run concurrently with his prison sentence.
Mr Ferguson has thus been punished three times for the same offence of
head-butting while playing for Rangers. He has been sent to prison. He has been
banned from playing football by virtue of his imprisonment. And he has been
banned by the SFA after his release from prison on November 22.
The effect of the appeal tribunal decision is that Mr Ferguson will not play
football until January 22, 1996. Mr Ferguson would have otherwise been able to
resume football on November 25, if concurrent punishments had been allowed for
the same offence by the tribunal.
In my view, leaving aside the selective prosecution of Mr Ferguson, and other
curious anomalies, it was a pity that Mr Ferguson was not allowed to do
community service - as Eric Cantona did for a worse assault - for his crime,
instead of receiving a prison sentence.
One worthy national newspaper concluded that our MP's tribunal was ``silly and
vindictive'' and that Scotland ``certainly does not need any lessons in the law
from Nigeria''.
I despair that so-called Liberals still seem to think that harsh punishments
are a ``good thing''. Harsh punishments did not work when another Liberal
administration executed leaders of the Easter Rising in Dublin in 1916. Harsh
punishments have not worked anywhere else. They have brought forth hatred,
embitterment, a feeling of revenge, and an ``intifada''.
It is mercy, magnanimity, gentleness, love and offering people a better way
which heals and which binds people together in unity, harmony, and obedience.
Dr David Reid,
Step Rock House,
The Scores,
St Andrews.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
