<HEADLINE>French gamble Strikes surprise government</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061017</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE political imperatives were clear and the required measures simple and
defensible: that is what the French government thought when it unveiled a
package of tough reforms designed to remove the welfare system's deficit and to
meet the Maastricht criteria for economic and monetary reform. It was a gamble
in a country which has long cherished both its public sector and a
comprehensive welfare system of some generosity; and it is a gamble which the
government of Mr Alain Juppe may yet live to regret.
The rapid spread of strikes and unrest on the streets appears to have taken the
government by surprise. It seems likely that the authorities will attempt to
provide alternative transport, whether in buses or lorries, in an attempt to
circumvent the latest round of strikes planned for today. The reform package is
deeply unpopular in France. French unions are not particularly strong but
opinion polls indicate widespread support for the strikers and suggest that at
least two-thirds of French adults have no confidence in Mr Juppe's ability to
resolve the argument. His case has not been helped by President Chirac, thought
to be enthusiastically in favour of reform, who adroitly removed himself over
the weekend to an obscure conference in Africa. Nor has the beleaguered Mr
Juppe been able to say much for himself in recent days. His hope must be that
the general public will tire of the chaos and unrest, but he cannot be sure of
this. Nor has he an avenue of escape, for the government's credibility on the
foreign exchanges depends on its ability to see the reforms through and to cut
the deficit. These are hard times for the French government, but they are
self-inflicted in the sense that a more gentle approach might have brought
incremental reforms with less political danger.
</TEXT>
