<HEADLINE>Hope after Clinton Need for hopeful persistence</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE></BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Leader</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061018</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANY peace process, but particularly the Northern Ireland peace process, needs a
lightness of spirit and warmth occasionally to break through the grey tones of
which it seems predominantly constituted. The public aspects of President
Clinton's visit provided that warmth and they were in their way quite as
important as the serious behind-scenes pressure and diplomacy which the
Washington administration has applied to all concerned. There has been carping
at President Clinton but his recent involvement has been creative, even
although it was not always so in the past, and there are hopes that he and
those around him who deal with Northern Ireland now have a clearer
understanding of the realities which apply there.
Nevertheless, the festival atmosphere has gone and if the peace is to be
maintained there must be a forward progress, however painful and however slow.
The invitations to the preparatory talks have gone out and the international
commission headed by Mr George Mitchell must begin its task soon if it is to
report by the middle of January. Although the involvement of Washington has
clearly given some of the participants the confidence to continue it is obvious
that the problem of weapons will not go away.
Mr Major remains convinced that proper negotiations with Sinn Fein will not
begin until the IRA has at least made a start at divesting itself of weapons
and he is right in maintaining this position. In that respect Mr Gerry Adams's
assertion yesterday that any twin-track process is useless if it contains
preconditions is notably unhelpful. If he is prejudging what will happen over
the next few weeks he is making a serious mistake. Nor does the Ulster Unionist
leader, Mr David Trimble, have good news to report. He tried to persuade
loyalist paramilitaries to make the first move on disarmament but has been
rebuffed, thereby enabling the loyalists to show themselves to be as
wrong-headed as the IRA. The grey shadows are back but it is not time for
despair. The second peaceful Christmas is almost upon us and one of the
messages it will bring is the need for hopeful persistence, and the ultimate
triumph of light over dark.
</TEXT>
