<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Business needs an independent Scotland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061020</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHAT Government would be best for business in Scotland? Not this one. A
first-class Scottish industry is being destroyed right now by the impotence,
compounded by the indifference, of the Scottish Office.
Fergus Ewing wrote to you (November 17) that once again, as in 1989 and in
1993, the market for farmed salmon is flooded with Norwegian production. He
said the Norwegians have 50,000 tons for which there is no market.
Only three weeks later I hear from Norway that the new estimate of surplus
production is over 100,000 tons.
For four years the Scottish Office has refused pleas from Scottish farmers to
establish producer organisations to control the number of smolts put to sea in
Norway, Scotland, Ireland, and the Faroes, according to the EU Common Fisheries
Policy. All the other countries want such producer organisations.
Now that in the absence of such a scheme the market has collapsed yet again you
might suppose that embarrassed Scottish Office Ministers would rush in to help.
Some hope. Just as in 1993 it is the Irish (whose industry is one-fifth the
size of the Scottish) who are fighting for emergency measures in Brussels. Just
as in 1993 the British Government is sitting on its hands.
Why? One reason is Scottish Office impotence, because all relations with the EU
on such matters are handled by London through the Ministry of Agriculture and
Fisheries.
MAFF in turn has to do what it is told by the Treasury, which of course has
much more important things to worry about than the collapse of salmon farms 500
miles from London.
The second reason is Scottish Office indifference. There isn't the slightest
chance of the Tories winning a seat at the next election anywhere near a salmon
farm.
Business needs a Government in Scotland - a real Government of course: a
devolved assembly as proposed would have no more clout in Brussels or with the
Norwegians than does Mr Forsyth.
David McCarthy,
Parks of Aldie,
Kinross.
</TEXT>
