<HEADLINE>University's infertility scheme under inquiry</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061021</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCHEME to help childless couples, set up 10 years ago by a private hospital
in Glasgow in association with Glasgow University and an NHS hospital, is under
investigation after allegations of financial irregularities.
The Herald understands that the inquiry is not linked to the infertility
scheme's acquisition of donors but concerns working practices and contracts.
Professor Ian Greer, head of the university's Obstetrics and Gynaecology
Department, is leading the investigation, which has been under way for several
months.
It is understood to be linked to the assisted conception service provided by
the university in association with Glasgow Royal Infirmary and the Glasgow
Nuffield private hospital.
The service was established by the Nuffield in 1985 to treat infertile couples
with the help of cash donations made to the university.
Patients who come for IVF (in vitro fertilisation) treatment in Glasgow with
their own donor are referred to the Nuffield - which collaborates with GRI and
Glasgow University in the city's IVF programme - to have it done privately.
To have it done on the NHS entails waiting in the queue for an anonymous donor
to become available.
The Obstetrics and Gynaecology Department under investigation has a staff of 15
academics and several other lower-grade members. A separate Department of
Obstetrics and Gynaecology within the university is linked with the Western
Infirmary.
A university spokesman declined to discuss details of the inquiry yesterday. He
said no-one had been suspended at this stage. He was not aware of any
suggestion that the police might become involved.
A spokesman for the GRI said he believed the investigation was ``purely an
internal university matter'' and had no bearing on services carried out by the
hospital. A spokeswoman for the Nuffield said she was confident there were no
irregularities involving the hospital.
</TEXT>
