<HEADLINE>There's still time to jam</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Rob Robertson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>24</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph Map</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061022</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NEWSVIEW: The new M8 extension spells good news for badgers, but what about
motorists?
THE long-awaited M8 extension on the west side of Edinburgh, designed to end
the traffic chaos and tailbacks          at the notorious Newbridge roundabout,
officially opens in seven days' time.
It is hoped that the new link will improve things for drivers coming from the
west of Scotland, who will be able to bypass the roundabout on their way to the
capital.
Already the extension is being hailed as a major boost to motorists, and, would
you believe, badgers. A special ``animal motorway'' has been created under part
of the road to make it easier for the badgers, who live in woods on either
side, to cross.
Fencing on both sides of the motorway will lead the badgers down to a tunnel,
which will take them safely to the other side.
However, the growing number of critics of the new road plan believe it will
only be the badgers who will be able to travel up and down the motorway more
quickly than they used to.
They believe drivers coming from the west will still be stuck in traffic jams,
albeit not at the Newbridge roundabout but at a different place on the new road.
Leading critics of the #40m road plan, who include a senior lecturer in
transport economy and a major east coast amenity group, believe the extension
will make no difference to the massive traffic problems on the west side of
Edinburgh.
Even the AA and the RAC do not seem convinced that the new road will completely
end the traffic chaos.
The new Claylands to Edinburgh city bypass road starts at the west end at the
spur off the existing M8 at Claylands Farm just before the Newbridge roundabout
and will connect the M8 direct to the Edinburgh city bypass at Hermiston. It is
designed to cut traffic coming both to and from Edinburgh on the west side of
the city.
The road is designed to provide relief to both the Newbridge roundabout and to
help traffic flow on connecting roads to the M9 and the A8.
Critics question just how successful the new road extension will be, and do not
accept Scottish Office claims that it will bring to an end the massive
tailbacks on the roads coming into Edinburgh.
At present, the congested A8 from Newbridge to the Gogar roundabout past
Edinburgh Airport carries an average of 58,000 vehicles a day.
The Scottish Office said that the new M8 extension will allow traffic to bypass
that area and the amount of traffic using that road will drop by nearly half to
29,000 vehicles a day.
Despite the supposed benefits of the extension road, experts and
environmentalists still have major concerns.
``The Scottish Office is simply buying time by opening the M8 extension,'' said
David Begg, lecturer in transport economy at Napier University.
``Give it two years and the tailbacks of traffic from the west trying to get
into Edinburgh will be back to the same levels. They are simply moving the
traffic problem from the Newbridge roundabout to the city bypass.
``I do not think this new road will make any great difference in journey times
between Edinburgh and Glasgow city centre.
``Although we fully accept there will be a cut in traffic on the way into
Edinburgh initially, the road traffic problem will slowly build up and will
just be shifted further along to where the new M8 extension meets the Edinburgh
city bypass, causing just as long tailbacks,'' said Mr Begg, who is also
chairman of Lothian Regional Council's transportation committee.
Supporters of the road extension disagree and say it will bring to an end the
years of frustration felt by the millions of people who have endured the
traffic jams in and around the dreaded Newbridge roundabout.
As well as the new extension connecting the M8 straight to the Edinburgh city
bypass, there will be roads off the new motorway to help break up the traffic
log-jams. It is estimated that 33,000 vehicles will use the extension alone
each day.
Despite the optimism, Mr Begg said there are still fundamental problems with
the road plan.
``The Scottish Office are driving people from Glasgow city boundary to the
Edinburgh city boundary. Once they get there, the problems begin.
``In Edinburgh the problems of getting into the city centre will be huge. When
drivers from the west hit the city bypass they will have the option of either
turning left - back towards the Gogar roundabout at the Gyle, going through the
bottle-neck that is Corstorphine High Street or turning right on the city
by-pass and going into town through Sighthill.''
One point even critics accept is that the big construction contract to build
the road has been handled efficiently and well.
Scottish Office chiefs are said to be delighted that contractors Balfour
Beattie managed to get the road extension ready for opening ten weeks early and
built with no overuns and within budget.
Around 200 men worked on the 92-week contract, moving two million cubic metres
of soil and clay. The work included building four new bridges, three extensions
to existing bridges and five new main carriageways. Four thousand tonnes of
concrete was used in the construction.
During the work a newt colony was found at Goldenacre pond, near the motorway,
and a conservation area set up for them. A 3500-year-old bronze age burial site
near Ratho was found, which was excavated and documented before construction
work began.
The road may have been built on time, but the extension itself has certainly
been a long-time coming. It was first discussed in the early 1960s, due to
complaints by motorists who were even then unhappy at road delays.
It took until 1985 for the first extension plan to be drawn up, and only in
February 1992, after a public inquiry, was the project given the go-ahead. In
the interim, traffic signals were installed at Newbridge in an attempt to
spread the travel problems out and to make journey times more predictable.
Mr Terry Levinthal, secretary of the Cockburn Association, an amenity and
environmental group, said there was currently a tremendous sea change of
opinion against road building in Scotland.
He said: ``If this road was at the planning stage now, there would be
tremendous opposition to it. People are realising building more roads is not
the answer to cutting congestion.
``I am more and more concerned there will be no decrease in traffic on the M8.
It will just push more and more cars on to the city bypass, and very soon the
bypass will be so congested that it will be full of traffic jams and will
become one big parking lot.''
Mr Levinthal accused the Scottish Office of keeping the public in the dark over
how effective the road will be in cutting traffic.
``What the Scottish Office is not telling us is just how much new road
extensions like this one cut traffic,'' said Mr Levinthal.
``The old M8 may well be ten times busier in a few years' time if the extension
had not been built. However, the question to be asked is whether it is worth
building a new #40m road if you just manage to cut that figure marginally. The
more roads you build, the more cars come along to use them.
``The Secretary of State has put his plans for a second Forth Road Bridge on
ice, so no traffic would be going to that from the M8.
``Because of that and other factors the extension is just yet another road
being built which is not part of an overall road strategy.''
Motoring groups also have their concerns over the road's possible long-term
effectiveness in cutting traffic.
Sue Nicholson, of the RAC, said: ``The extension will make a difference to the
horrific traffic problems to the west of Edinburgh.
``However, we believe the extension is not the complete answer and feel it
should be linked up to other measures which we believe the new Edinburgh City
Council want to look at, like park and ride projects and an improvement in
public transport.''
Neil Gregg, the AA's environmental officer in Scotland, said he was pleased
that the new extension would split traffic up coming towards Edinburgh and make
it easier to get to the city bypass. However, he said there was a worry that
the Gogar roundabout rather than the Newbridge roundabout would become the
focus for traffic difficulties.
Despite the criticism of the new road, the Scottish Office is still adamant
that the new extension, which will be opened by Scottish Office minister Lord
James Douglas-Hamilton next Monday, will be a great boost for drivers.
Only time will tell if its prediction of less traffic congestion and quicker
journey times between Glasgow and Edinburgh will come true, or whether it is
only the badgers who will have cause for celebration over the new road.
</TEXT>
