<HEADLINE>Jodie Foster in Net death threat</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>foreign digest</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061023</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jodie Foster in
Net death threat
LOS ANGELES: Actress Jodie Foster has been targeted with death threats and
other explicit messages on the Internet, Hollywood trade newspaper Daily
Variety reports today. The FBI has been asked to investigate threats against
the Oscar-winning star after the messages detailed explicit plans for attacking
and murdering her and also described imaginary sexual encounters.
In March 1981, crazed fan John Hinckley tried to impress Foster by carrying out
an assassination attempt on President Ronald Reagan.
Rutskoi to run
MOSCOW: Alexander Rutskoi, leader of the bloody 1993 revolt against President
Boris Yeltsin, has announced that he will run for president of Russia next
year. Former vice-president Rutskoi, 48, tried to overthrow Yeltsin in a coup
bid brutally crushed when the president sent in tanks. Rutskoi was jailed but
later freed under an amnesty. Yeltsin, still recovering from a heart attack,
has not yet said if he will run again.
Twins apart
TEL AVIV: Israeli doctors successfully separated Siamese twins yesterday, hours
after the girls were born joined at the intestine. ``They are in excellent
condition,'' said a spokesman. It was only the sixth such recorded case as most
Siamese twins are joined at the chest.
Anglers on ice
MOSCOW: Helicopters and icebreakers were searching yesterday for six Russian
anglers who have been adrift on an icefloe for four days. They were reported
missing by two other fishermen who made it back to land after the ice broke
away into the large inland sea of Lake Onega, 570 miles north of Moscow.
Poll ban urged
CAIRO: Opposition parties in Egypt, angry because they did not win any seats in
the first round of parliamentary elections, are considering a boycott of
Wednesday's second round to decide the remaining 70% of the seats.
King `resting'
DUBAI: Saudi Arabia's royal court said yesterday that King Fahd had been
advised to rest, but that his health was no cause for alarm. Concern over the
73-year-old monarch arose when the court said he had been admitted to hospital
for checks.
Cashing in
LILLE: Bruno Calonne, a 36-year-old bank cashier, says    he will go to work
today just like any other day, although he has just won a record    F69m
(#9.3m) in the French national lottery. Calonne, married with two daughters,
said he would pay his debts, travel, and share the winnings with his
tightly-knit family in the northern town of Hazebrouck.
Briton wins
CAPRI: British novelist A.S Byatt has won the #1500 Curzio Malaparte prize, one
of Italy's top literary awards, for her contribution to literature.
</TEXT>
