<HEADLINE>Thursday spells triumph or disaster for Galileo Jupiter probe's moment of truth</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061024</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SIX-YEAR journey to one of the strangest places in the solar system ends this
week in a 75-minute suicide flight to the heart of the planet Jupiter.
Astronomers and scientists around the world are waiting with bated breath the
arrival of the unmanned Galileo spacecraft at the massive planet after a 300
million-mile journey dogged by problems.
Among them is a British professor who hopes the #1000m mission will feed back
benefits for the humble weather forecast on earth.
On Thursday, a probe launched from the craft in July is due to become the first
man-made object to plunge into the turbulent atmosphere of Jupiter.
As it plummets towards certain destruction in conditions of intense heat and
pressure, its mother ship will take up orbit around Jupiter, ready to transmit
masses of information about the little-understood fifth planet.
Galileo mission director Dr Neil Ausman describes Thursday as the ``day of
truth'', when Nasa will know whether its investment in the 20-year project has
paid dividends.
He said: ``If it doesn't work, it will be devastating. If it does, we will be
walking around six feet off the ground.''
Atmospheric physicist Professor Fred Taylor, of Oxford University, is the head
of the only British scientific team to have equipment on board Galileo.
He said: ``This is a very exciting time for us. I have been working on this
project since 1976, so it has been a very long wait.
``There is a lot about Jupiter that we do not understand, and Galileo will
provide us with the first hard physical data so we can start pinning down
exactly how the planet's atmospheric systems work.''
Among the mysteries which Professor Taylor hopes to solve are the causes of
Jupiter's distinctive giant red spot and the bands of colour on the surface of
its atmosphere.
He hopes to discover whether Jupiter's incredible winds - known to reach speeds
of more than 300mph - are matched by equally terrifying storms and lightning.
He believes that the remarkable Jovian weather he learns about from Galileo
will improve our understanding of weather on earth.
``Jupiter has a very strange atmosphere by Earth terms, but we are interested
in comparisons with Earth. The interesting thing about Jupiter is that it is so
much larger than Earth, so it may have similar weather patterns but on a much
bigger scale, with some weather systems as big as the earth itself,'' said the
professor.
``New knowledge like this always translates into practical applications
eventually, but we don't know what we are going to find out, so it's difficult
to predict how.
``But we would expect the effect of our new information to diffuse out
gradually to places like the Met Office and the weather forecasts.''
Professor Taylor's experiments have been hit by the failure of Galileo's main
communications antenna to function, which has impaired the spacecraft's ability
to transmit its discoveries to earth.
He said: ``We will only get about a tenth of the data we were expecting, but
that is not as bad as it sounds, as there will still be an enormous amount to
work with, so we are not too despondent.''
The probe will enter Jupiter's atmosphere at 110,000mph, but will be slowed to
1000mph within minutes by the dense gases. The friction of entry will raise the
temperature on its surface to 28,000C, more than twice the heat of the sun.
It will have an estimated 75 minutes to send information back to Galileo for
transmission to earth before being destroyed by Jupiter's hostile atmosphere.
Professor Taylor said: ``It is a toss-up whether it gets crushed or baked
first. We expect it to survive up to about 20 times the atmospheric pressure of
earth, but by that time the heat might have destroyed it.''
As the probe is vaporized, the Galileo mother ship will settle into an orbit
round Jupiter, recording data from a distance for around two years.
Galileo's arrival will be a triumph over massive adversity by the Nasa team at
Pasadena, California.
The craft was to have taken just 30 months to reach Jupiter after launching on
one of the earliest Space Shuttle flights in 1982.
Delays in the Shuttle programme put the launch back to 1986, when the
Challenger disaster sent the whole project back to the drawing board.
Galileo was redesigned with a smaller motor, and eventually launched in 1989 on
a spiral route, orbiting the sun twice and using the planets' gravitational
forces to power its flight.
After two decades of intense effort and technological achievement against the
odds, for the scientists at Nasa, Thursday will be one of the most nail-biting
white-knuckle rides of all time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000032</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000032</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Bid to lift housing up the political league</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061025</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
HOUSING is the number one issue MPs face from their constituents, but it is not
given the political attention it deserves, it was claimed yesterday.
The Scottish Federation of Housing Associations will today try to alter that
situation.
The federation, representing the country's 200 housing associations and
co-operatives which manage nearly 80,000 homes, will launch a major campaign
aimed at getting housing on to the political agenda alongside ``popular''
issues such as health, education and crime.
As part of it, politicians and prospective candidates in the next General
Election are to be given a non-party political housing manifesto.
Mr David Orr, federation director, said political debate tended to centre on
issues such as health and education.
``Housing is every bit as important,'' he said. ``After all, poor housing
affects children's education and people's health generally.
``We will be campaigning hard with all the political parties to get them to
take housing matters seriously.''
The manifesto drawn up by the federation calls for the housing association
budget to be doubled to allow a minimum of 10,000 new homes a year.
It maintains housing and social work departments, health boards and the private
sector will need to continue to offer housing associations free land to tackle
homelessness.
The manifesto also says a capital subsidy system is needed to ensure affordable
rented housing is available to those who need it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000033</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000033</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>From a double act legend to singular acclaim</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061026</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JIMMY JEWEL, the comic with the unmistakeable battered look of a downtrodden
bloodhound, died yesterday on the eve of his 83rd birthday.
He was one of a small group of music hall artists who made the successful
transition to straight acting late in life. He was half of a legendary double
act with his cousin Ben Warriss, a kind of British Abbott and Costello. They
achieved nationwide celebrity status on stage and radio.
Then, approaching the age of 60, he gravitated towards acting and received wide
acclaim for his performances in West End plays such as The Comedians and Death
of a Salesman.
Jewel was hailed as one of the best character actors in the business and worked
through his 70s in the theatre and on television, saying he would only stop
when he became an embarrassment to himself or other people.
He saw no barrier between comedy and acting, and pointed to the success of
American vaudeville stars like James Cagney and Red Buttons who moved to the
screen.
But for TV viewers he will be best remembered as the lecherous, boozy character
partnering Hylda Baker in the long-running 1970s TV series Nearest and Dearest.
It ran for 65 episodes and was a huge audience-puller.
Yet, unknown to fans, it was a disaster off the set, with Baker even trying to
have Jewel, her ``Dearest'' partner, replaced by another actor.
Like Max Wall, in whose footsteps he followed from comedy to acting, he had the
advantage of having been born and reared in showbusiness.
Born James Arthur Thomas Jewel Marsh in Sheffield on December 4, 1912, he had
three distinct careers in his lifetime - first as part of the family troupe,
second with Ben Warriss in the double act and finally as a distinguished actor.
It is no exaggeration to say he came up the hard way with more than his fair
share of broken limbs, black eyes and other assorted injuries acquired through
the physical side of showbusiness.
He claimed that he never wanted to be a performer. His great joy was stage
managing his father and the hard physical labour involved in loading sets on to
horse drays and into railway trucks as the family toured the music halls.
But at the age of 14 he did a sketch called The Tripe Supper and enjoyed the
audience's laughter so much that he set out on his career as a comic.
Shortly before his father died, he teamed up in 1934 with Warriss, who had been
born in the same Sheffield bed just months earlier. Their mothers were sisters.
The partnership came about through chance - at the time Jimmy told stories
ending with an impersonation of Maurice Chevalier, while Ben sang Eddie Cantor
songs and was a successful ``top-hat-and-tails'' performer.
They found themselves on the same bill in Newcastle upon Tyne and when one of
the turns - a double act - failed to appear, they decided to go on as second
act and ``see what kind of a go we could make of it'', as Jimmy later said.
The Jewel and Warriss team was born and stayed together for 32 years.
They topped the bill at The Palladium, had six Royal Command performances and
during the 1950s were able to make #2500 a week. They were the Morecambe and
Wise of their generation.
But this showbusiness marriage was dissolved in 1966 when the two comics
decided to go their separate ways as the music halls disappeared.
Jimmy Jewel's career went into the doldrums and he genuinely believed his life
on the stage was over.
But around 1970, Frank Muir, then head of comedy at the BBC, asked him to do a
Variety Playhouse script called Spanner in the Works. It was the turning point.
Overnight, the ageing comic became an actor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
