<DOCNO>GH951204-000034</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000034</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Contact lenses disease alert</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061027</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILLIONS of contact lens wearers could be at risk from a rare eye disease
because they use inadequate cleaning solutions, says a report.
More and more people are suffering from an ailment caused by a microscopic
organism which eats away at the eye, according to BBC1's consumer programme,
Watchdog, tonight. Eye experts believe that problems may arise because two out
of three lens-cleaning solutions are not powerful enough.
An eye surgeon told the programme that the number of people suffering from the
disease - acanthamoeba keratitis - had quadrupled since 1990 and he was now
seeing about 40 sufferers a year.
Staff at the Moorfields eye hospital in London told the programme that only one
third of cleansing solutions contained hydrogen peroxide, the chemical most
effective in killing the organism. ``We're seeing a dramatic increase,'' said
John Dart, consultant opthalmologist at Moorfields.
``It is a very unpleasant condition. The disease lasts for many months, if not
years. About one in 10 patients lose their sight.''
``I'm concerned that most of the solutions are neither effective against
acanthamoeba or against bacteria.''
</TEXT>
