<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000036</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000036</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The missing Gaelic link</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Paul Welsh</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061029</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paul Welsh considers moves to provide nursery education for Gaelic-speakers
FËILTE Chlànn, a Gaelic welcome to children, could be heard with increasingly
regularity in Glasgow if a campaign just launched is ultimately successful.
Parent power is being mobilised in the city to establish two Gaelic-speaking
nursery schools for four to five-year-olds by next August.
``This is the vital link missing in Gaelic education for children in Glasgow,''
says campaign spokesperson, Katherine Gillies, treasurer of Croileagan Partick,
a Gaelic playgroup in the city's West End.
``We want to give Gaelic-speaking children the same opportunities that English
speakers already have,'' she continues, ``but as things stand we are losing a
lot of children because of the lack of a suitable nursery. Glasgow's Gaelic
language base is definitely being negatively affected by this.''
Although Strathclyde contains a substantial number of Pàrant in Paisde (parent
and toddler) playgroups and three Bùnsgoil (Gaelic medium primary schools),
there are no Sgoil Aràich, or pre-school nurseries, for four to five-year-olds
in the region. After playgroup, working parents have no option but to place
children in English-speaking nurseries, and often feel they cannot take the
children away from their friends when it is time to enrol in primary school.
The campaign organisers believe a bridge for this age-group is essential, if
this damaging trend is to be curbed.
``The demand for the nurseries is mushrooming,'' says Gillies. ``The emphasis
would be on education rather than play, helping the children to develop a
pre-school foundation in letter and number recognition.''
At present, the campaign is ``more of a feasibility study'', as the organisers
compile a register of names and contact numbers for children recently born to
five years of age who may use the nursery, and prefered locations for the new
full-time resource. ``We want to show there is demand for the nursery, not just
this year, but for the next five years to come,'' explains Gillies.
A recent census by the Gaelic Council suggests there is a 7000-strong
Gaelic-speaking community within a two-mile radius of Partick Burgh Halls and,
according to Gillies, there is ``a general consensus'' that one nursery should
be established close-by in the West End, serving the north side of Glasgow.
Steering communities on both sides of the river will ultimately determine the
best location for each nursery, however, and much of the impetus in the early
stages of the campaign is coming from non Gaelic-speaking and English nationals.
``In the sixties, speaking two languages was thought of as a hindrance to your
education,'' says Gillies. ``Many parents who want their children to learn
Gaelic now, come from Gaelic backgrounds but lost the language during that
period. Some of them are very annoyed about it now, but west coasters are
really pretty reticent by nature. The English will get up there and shout,
whereas Scots are definitely more modest.''
After compiling the register, the second stage of the campaign is an
application to Glasgow City Authority, the new unitary body which replaces the
Glasgow District Council and Strathclyde region on April 1 next year. The
organisers want both nurseries to be local authority run, rather than private
concerns, and are also aware of specific EU grants available to help sustain
lesser-spoken languages.
Since the early eighties, Strathclyde region has given a strong commitment to
the language, and Gillies thinks this will continue. The new campaign is
reminiscent of the push for Gaelic primary education in the city which resulted
in the establishment of the Sir John Maxwell School in 1984, the only Gaelic
primary that falls within the boundary of the new authority. Councillor Malcolm
Green, GCA Education Convener in waiting, is positive about the campaign.
``This is a campaign to maximise interest among parents, rather than against
the council,'' Green says. ``A nursery for four to five-year-olds fits
logically with the provision we are already making for Gaelic education, but it
is up to the parents themselves to determine numbers and suitable locations.''
``In principle,'' he continues, ``there is no minimum number for a successful
application, but I would expect somewhere between 12 and 20 children would
secure the nurseries. We would try to minimise start-up costs by freeing space
in existing primary schools, for instance, and also help minimise the distance
children would have to travel.''
If the voucher scheme proposed by the Government, guaranteeing #1100 worth of
nursery education for four-year-olds, is eventually implemented, Green would
like the new city authority to collect any vouchers spent on Gaelic nursery
education in Glasgow.
A public meeting this evening at Glasgow Caledonian University, run by
Comhairle Nan Sgoiltean Araich (CNSA), the Gaelic Pre-School Council, will
focus on Gaelic nursery provision in the city.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000037</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000037</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lighter load</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061030</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AT first glance, James Tolmie's letter (November 29) paints a distressing
scenario of hard-pressed staff from the procurator-fiscal's office finding
themselves even more overworked, busily scrutinising video tapes of football
matches, searching carefully for heinous misdemeanours perpetrated during play.
But fear not! Those canny lads at the fiscal's office have already found a way
to lighten their load. By restricting themselves to watching only one of the
potential 20 matches played, and then by focusing on only one set of players,
their onerous burden is much reduced.
David McLintock,
74 Ralston Path,
Crookston, Glasgow.
</TEXT>
