<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000038</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000038</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>MP urges lottery impact probe</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061031</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Government was yesterday urged to set up an independent, high-powered
commission to examine the impact of the National Lottery on charity work
overseas.
Mr George Foulkes, Shadow Overseas Aid Minister, claimed that the Lottery could
be depriving Third World countries of badly-needed donations.
``We are already facing a 7.5% cut in the overseas aid budget. On top of that,
the social effects of the Lottery are having a much greater impact than
forecast both at home and overseas.''
He said the reduced amounts people are now giving to charity because of the
Lottery were hitting those organisations doing vital work in the poorest and
most deprived regions of the world.
``The impact of this, plus the cutbacks in official aid, could be having a
calamitous effect on those already in dire straits in these countries.
``It is time, a year and a bit on from the inception of the National Lottery,
that its impact and its effects right across the globe should be reviewed in a
very dispassionate and penetrating way.''
Mr Foulkes said he would be asking National Heritage Secretary Virginia
Bottomley to order such an inquiry ``as a matter of the utmost urgency''.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000039</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000039</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Northern managers are better at losing their jobs</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061032</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A NORTH-SOUTH divide has opened up among Britain's redundant executives, a
survey out today suggests.
Freshly-redundant high fliers in the northern half of Britain get more support
from their wives and are more likely to talk to them openly about their plight.
They are also more likely to have working wives - and more likely to find that
their problems bring them closer together.
Southerners are more likely to react to redundancy by cutting household
expenses - and their partners are more willing to consider moving abroad to a
new job.
But throughout Britain the stigma that once attached to redundancy has
vanished, financial strains have eased with the growing number of two-income
households - and families are becoming more willing to look further afield for
work.
The most common reflection from the newly-redundant executive is: ``I wish I
had spent more time with my family.''
And wives are far more willing to move to help their redundant husband find a
job than the husbands of redundant women executives.
The survey, published today by career consultants Drake Beam Morrin, is based
on responses from 171 executives, most of them men.
The firm attributed the North-South divide to the industrial heritage of the
North - and the shock waves that job losses sent through the white-collar South.
``I think the North has had more of a history of job losses over the years, and
it is something that most households will have experience of,'' said managing
director Peter Trigg.
``But in the South the professional classes were really hard hit in the
recession, while, for generations before, they had not been people who lost
their jobs. This could explain the different attitudes.''
The typical executive in the survey was in his late 40s or early 50s, married
with children, and earning between #30,000 and #45,000 before losing his job.
Just over a third - 34% - had a non-working partner, well down on the 42% in a
previous survey in 1994, and in the previous month most of them - 85% - had no
financial difficulties.
Nearly 30% believed they could spend up to a year searching for a job before
hitting financial problems, while nearly a quarter could afford to job-hunt for
up to two years.
But 13% reckoned they had only six months to find a job before encountering
serious financial problems.
Ninety-seven per cent of couples in the North had ``openly'' discussed their
plight together compared with 89% in the South.
Northern husbands or wives were more likely actively to help redundant partners
find work, and the overall proportion of partners prepared to do this was well
up on last year.
The main concern of all the executives was the fear of long-term unemployment,
while partners were more worried about their inability to plan for the future.
Forty-five per cent of all couples thought redundancy had drawn them together -
but less so in the South than in the North.
If finding a job meant a move overseas, 41% of southern wives would be prepared
to follow their husbands - but only 21% of northern wives.
But overall, three-quarters of all partners were willing to move elsewhere
within the UK - compared with just 51% in 1994.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000040</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000040</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE> Profiting from milk quality</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>COLLEGE COMMENT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061033</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MILK quality now attracts substantial premiums for those producers able to sell
milk with a high butterfat and, more importantly, a high protein level. The
converse is also true - milk of low-quality now attracts penalties which can
make a considerable difference to a farmer's income from milk sales.
The various milk buyers operate different payment systems for quality. It is
important to study these pricing arrangements to see the effect they will have
on income.
Penalty deductions will become more evident in many situations. The instinctive
reaction to receiving deductions in a milk cheque is to try to improve milk
quality, but this may not be the most profitable option.
Although premiums are paid for high butterfat, it is not always desirable to
increase butterfat. This is because of the effect it can have on the milk quota
situation if the butterfat trigger operates.
Increasing butterfat will result in production being adjusted upwards without
any compensatory payment. It may actually pay a farmer to reduce butterfat
despite being penalised for poorer quality.
More emphasis is being placed on protein in an effort to encourage higher
levels in milk. Dietary changes are the only way to effect an immediate
improvement in protein levels. This means ensuring that the type and level of
protein in the diet are adequate.
This has to be coupled with sufficient energy of the right type in the ration
to encourage the correct fermentation in the rumen. In the longer term,
improvements in protein percentage can be made through breeding and attention
to the overall herd management.
With dietary manipulation to improve milk quality, the over-riding factor has
to be - does it pay and produce a ration capable of maintaining cow health and
fertility?
More than ever, milk costing is an important tool in monitoring the overall
profit levels from the herd.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000041</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000041</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears for Briton on missing plane</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061034</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Valletta
NO TRACE has been found of a small aircraft which went missing over the
Mediterranean this morning with six people including one Briton on board.
The hunt was launched shortly after 5am when the single-engine Piper aircraft
operated by Excelair Services Ltd failed to arrive in Malta on a two-hour
flight from the island of Jerba, off Tunisia.
Maltese police named the missing Briton as Michael Williams. It is not known
which part of the UK he is from.
Jets from the Maltese air force, two Excelair planes, and helicopters from an
Italian base on the island scoured the sea south-west of Malta for almost 12
hours but found no sign of the aircraft. The search was called off at nightfall.
Spokesmen for the Maltese Police and Directorate of Civil Aviation said there
were no clues to what had happened to the plane which was reported missing
after it failed to make contact with the Maltese control tower.
No distress signal was received from the aircraft, which left Tunisia before
dawn and was due to take two hours to reach Malta.
The police spokesman said the hunt would resume tomorrow.
The other passengers are Irishman Desmond Goomer, Gorny Tadeuse from Poland,
and Phillip Farrugia and Matthew Aquilinia, both from Malta.
The plane was piloted by Maltese Carmel Bartolo, a director of Sun Aviation Ltd
which owns the aircraft.
A Foreign Office spokesman confirmed that Mr Williams was missing and said that
UK missions in Malta and Tunisia were investigating his disappearance.
q.Four people were hurt when an Indian Airlines aircraft with more than 100
people on board overshot the runway at an airport near New Delhi.-Reuter/AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000042</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000042</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Man held over Nickell killing</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061035</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
POLICE investigating the murder of Rachel Nickell have arrested a 31-year-old
man.
Scotland Yard said that he had been arrested at a south London police station
after voluntarily surrendering himself on November 22.
They would not confirm he is John Gallagher, a former barman, who had returned
from New Zealand.
A spokesman said: ``We can confirm that a 31-year-old man attended voluntarily
at a police station on November 22 with his solicitor. He was formally arrested
in connection with the death of Rachel Nickell and bailed while further
inquiries continue.''
Gallagher, originally from Roehampton estate, near Wimbledon Common, south
London, where Rachel was killed, had emigrated to New Zealand where he shared a
home with his girlfriend in Hastings, on the North Island.
Scotland Yard officers flew out to interview him after a new witness came
forward in the case.
Rachel, a 23-year-old former model, was stabbed 49 times as she walked on
Wimbledon Common with her two-year-old son Alex in July 1992.
In 1993, Colin Stagg, also from the Roehampton estate, was charged with her
murder. Police had set up a major operation to lure Stagg into confessing, but
he was acquitted after the trial judge at the Old Bailey last year attacked the
police tactics.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000043</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000043</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>France brings home outspoken general</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061036</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
FRENCH Defence Minister Charles Millon said tonight he had ordered the
commander of UN forces in Sarajevo to return to Paris after he criticised the
Bosnia peace accord, saying France should have rejected it.
Millon said in a television interview: ``I have asked General (Jean-Rene)
Bachelet to return to Paris. I will be meeting him tomorrow. It is quite
obvious the French Government cannot accept any sort of criticism of the Dayton
plan.''
He did not make clear whether Bachelet would be replaced, or whether he would
be allowed to complete his tour of duty in Sarajevo, which has six months to
run.
Bachelet apologised yesterday for remarks published in the French press which
he said had not been not intended for publication.
He was quoted on Friday as saying the accord would drive panicky Bosnian Serbs
to flee the Bosnian capital, burning their homes as they left.
He said US negotiator Richard Holbrooke had cynically pushed through a hasty
peace accord in Dayton, Ohio, to promote President Bill Clinton's re-election
campaign.
Millon said France had clearly accepted the Dayton plan, due to be signed in
Paris on December 14, and would be sending 7500 men on the ground to help
enforce it.
However he said the French Government was concerned that ``the balance between
the communities should be respected''.
President Jacques Chirac wrote to President Clinton last week calling for
guarantees for the Bosnian Serbs, who fear they will be overrun in Sarajevo
once their militia is disarmed and disbanded in the Bosnian capital within 45
days of signing the peace deal.
Bachelet said the accord would lead to more ``ethnic cleansing'' and drive
Serbs to flee Sarajevo by the thousands, burning their homes as they left.
``We would then see terrible television pictures of French soldiers directing
traffic while houses burned,'' he said. ``If the operation fails, we, the
French, will be held responsible.''
The Defence Ministry disowned Bachelet's remarks on Friday night but senior
defence officials made clear there were serious differences with Washington
about the implementation of the Bosnian peace accord.
Beyond the issue of the Sarajevo Serbs, France is also concerned at the US
intention to rearm the Muslim-led Bosnian government army, and at Washington's
insistence on withdrawing a Nato-commanded international peace force after one
year, fearing it could lead to a new outbreak of bloodshed.
Bachelet criticised his own government for accepting last month's peace
agreement, saying: ``General de Gaulle would without doubt have slammed the
door in Dayton''.
Bachelet's barb about De Gaulle was an implicit rebuke to President Jacques
Chirac, who considers himself the political heir of the late general and
president of France.
On a related issue, Millon said Chirac had warned Serbian President Slobodan
Milosevic of the consequences if two French pilots shot down by the Bosnian
Serbs were not released in the next few days.
He said France would otherwise ``take measures which the Serbs would have cause
to regret''. He did not spell them out but said the Serbs knew they needed the
co-operation of the international community to implement the Bosnia peace
accord.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000044</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000044</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>no headline present</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061037</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN MY letter published on December 1, under the heading Irish pogroms only in
North, a phrase has been omitted from the tenth paragraph which leaves the
paragraph meaningless when taken with the folllowing paragraph.
The paragraphs contrast the situation in the 26 Counties as compared to the six
Counties. In the first of these paragraphs I originally wrote: ``Proportional
representation was included in the 1922 Constitution to protect the rights of
the small Protestant population of the 26 Counties.''
As you can see this significantly alters the sense of the two paragraphs.
In addition, where I refer to the decline in the relative Protestant population
in the South, my original text suggests it might be worth looking at the
long-term effects of the First World War on the Anglo-Irish population. I do
not, as in the published form, offer it as a hard and fast explanation, or as a
sole explanation.
Hugh McLoughlin,
24 Russell Street,
Mossend, Bellshill.
</TEXT>
