<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000045</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000045</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Center Parcs to shine for S&amp;N</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061038</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A QUITE heavy reporting week kicks off this morning with Scottish &amp; Newcastle's
half-timer, with arch rival Bass reporting its full year fortunes on Wednesday.
S&amp;N's main point of interest will be progress on the Courage acquisition, which
turned it into Britain's biggest brewer and how much the restructuring will
cost.
Playing a big part in the profits increase during the six months to November 1
will be the hot summer and a good contribution from the Center Parcs holiday
operations. The concensus profits expectation is #162m compared with last
time's #145m.
Strong performances from hotels and pubs should have offset poorer trading from
Bass's bingo operations. The National Lottery will have hit its bingo, perhaps
by as much as 15% in the second half. For the full year to the end of Septmber,
pre-tax profits should have risen from #555m to about #590m, while the dividend
could improve by 1.4p to 22.5p.
Tomorrow sees electronics and engineering group Siebe with its interim. Broker
UBS suggests it will have made a pre-tax profit of #147m compared with #119m.
Shareholders are likely to see their interim dividend rise from 4.03p to 4.45p.
Control systems are thought to have been the main driving force behind the
group's improved fortunes.
Wednesday is graced by Robert Wiseman's Dairies, which has 5% of the overall UK
milk market. Progress reports on the rapid expansion through acquisition are
probably more important than the bare figures which should see the pre-tax
profit rise from #2.9m to about #4m.
Carlton Communications should have benefited from good advertising growth and
also from its video activities sufficiently to have pushed profits for the year
to September ahead from #190m to #250m, with the dividend being hoisted from
20.7p to 23.5p.
Engineering giant GEC is expected to show six month profits ahead by about 9%
to #413m on Thursday, but the dividend by just 5% to 3.1p. Attention will focus
on the problems at Marconi, the integration of VSEL and further news about the
re-shaping of the board.
Great Universal Stores' interim is thought likely to show little change apart
from a marginal improvement from #225m to perhaps #230m.
An uplift from #23.5m to anything between #28.5m and #36m is expected from
Racal.
Pubs group Greenalls will see analysts concentrate on news of its integration
of Boddingtons. They are looking for pre-tax profit for the year to September
rising from #74.8m to about #100m.
</TEXT>
