<DOCID>GH951204-000046</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tragedy of parents who give life, and death</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph </GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061039</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY thought they were just an ordinary couple with a baby, says Liz. That was
seven years ago, before they discovered that their infant son was one in a
million. When he was four weeks old, they discovered an unexplained lump in his
tummy and tests at the Royal Hospital for Sick Children in Glasgow had the
doctors baffled. After a couple of weeks in anxious consultation with genetic
specialists in London, Christopher tested positive for chronic granulomatous
disorder, CGD.
It is a genetic abnormality in which the white blood cells are unable to
produce the superoxide necessary for breaking down invading bacteria. As a
result, people with the condition are extremely susceptible to infections which
would be minor to other people and can quickly suffer serious complications
such as pneumonia, skin complaints which won't heal, bone infections, and
life-threatening abscesses on the heart, liver and lungs. Unfortunately
Christopher was severely affected by it and although given drug therapy, he
died at just six weeks old from an abscess on his liver.
His parents, devastated at his death, also had to cope with the completely
unexpected knowledge that they were carriers of a genetic disorder. Liz was
found to be a carrier of the type of CGD which is transmitted from mother to
son, although it does not affect her own health at all. Fewer than 100 people
in the UK have CGD, although one in 200,000 is a carrier.
It was first pinpointed in 1958 as an abnormality of the white cells which
means that when activated by bacteria they fail to produce a ``respiratory
burst'' which is important for making hydrogen peroxide which combines to make
a superoxide which is vital in killing bacteria.
We all depend on our genes for our very existence, but never give them a
moment's thought unless the secret code breaks down. Genes are succinctly
described by Dr Linda Lashford, a researcher into gene therapy for CGD in
Manchester, as ``the complement of instructions to guide normal growth and
function''. She regards the complex science of gene therapy as repairing that
list of instructions to enable the cell to function normally again.
Research into genetic disorders has moved ahead at such a fast pace in the past
few years that even from the time Christopher was diagnosed, there have been
enormous advances. Although by the nature of the deficiency, it must have
affected previous generations, it is likely that childhood illnesses and deaths
would have been attributed to other causes.
``In my great grandmother's generation infant deaths were much more common and
there is really no means of tracing the pattern of transmission in the
family,'' Liz said. As soon as the nature of the problem was diagnosed, other
family members who could be affected were tested. In her generation, from a
total of nine girl cousins, four are carriers including Liz and her sister.
Happily, Liz and Stephen now have two healthy little daughters, after what
their mother describes as two very long pregnancies during which they waited on
tenterhooks to find out whether they would have another affected son. It occurs
in one in two sons born to carriers and there is a one-in-two risk of daughters
being a carrier.
Only in the rarer cases of both parents being carriers (usually in marriages
within the extended family) are girls affected. The prospect of their daughters
having boys with CGD is something they may have to face in the future, but
Stephen is optimistic that by that time gene therapy will have advanced to the
point where the genetic damage can be corrected.
His hope is borne out by Professor Anthony Segal at University College, London,
the main centre for research into CGD in the UK. ``It is one of the disorders
which could be particularly amenable to gene therapy,'' said Professor Segal,
who predicts that successful treatment could be between five and 10 years away.
``CGD is the ideal case for treatment by gene therapy. It is a prototype
disease where the white blood cells can be aspirated from the bone marrow,
treated, cultured, and then tested to see if the defect has been corrected
before being put back into patients.''
Although patients have to be on long-term antibiotic treatment, it is not
necessarily fatal. The work in Professor Segal's laboratory, which has already
included some gene therapy trials, although none as yet has been successful, is
funded by the Medical Research Council, the Wellcome Trust and the small but
determined CGD Trust run by families of affected children, will also open the
way to gene therapy for other genetic disorders. ``We need support,'' added
Professor Segal.
Everyone from toddlers to grandparents can help raise funds for their work by
wearing jeans, preferably in unexpected places such as city offices, law
courts, schools, hospitals and on commuter trains and business class in
aeroplanes on March 1 next year. The CGD Trust has dubbed it Jeans for Genes
Day: a worldwide one-day sponsorship exercise to raise money for research into
gene replacement therapy for genetic disorders.
Proceeds from the UK appeal will be shared equally between four charities. They
are the Chronic Granulomatous Disorder Research Trust; the Primary
Immunodeficiency Association, whose 2000 members are deficient in certain
antibodies leaving them susceptible to specific infections, but in severe cases
suffer severe combined immune deficiency syndrome, dubbed Baby in the Bubble
syndrome from cases where children have had to be isolated in a sterile
environment; the Society for Mucopolysaccharide Diseases, a distressing group
of rare metabolic diseases, whose sufferers lack an enzyme to break down used
materials in the body. Growth is usually restricted and they can cause
progressive mental as well as physical handicap and even death in childhood.
The fourth beneficiary will be the new gene therapy centre to be based at the
Institute of Child Health, the research arm of the Great Ormond Street
Children's Hospital in London, where the first gene therapy trial was carried
out in 1993.
n It is hoped that schools and businesses will support the Jeans for Genes Day
on March 1, 1996. More information from the appeal director, telephone 01725
517 977.
Losing a child is devastating enough for any couple, but the trauma is even
worse if it is revealed that they were responsible for the death.
Jennifer Cunningham talks to just such a couple
</TEXT>
</DOC>
