<HEADLINE>Dr Jane Davie and the pill</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061040</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
n IN The Herald on October 27 we published an article headlined ``The Pill
scare'' in which we interviewed Dr Jane Davie, the Senior Clinical Medical
Officer with the Edinburgh Family Planning Services and Well Woman Clinic,
about the problems that had been caused after an official warning was issued
over use of the pill. In the context of that article we quoted Dr Davie as
stating that she accepted that the CSM had over-reacted and also that she felt
that the piecemeal information from the CSM had been very badly mismanaged. We
also made reference to ``time bombs'' and ``crises''. We have been asked by Dr
Davie to point out that she did not use these exact words in the interview and
also that the article did not correctly reflect her views on the safety of
second and third-generation pills. We have specifically been asked to mention
that Dr Davie did not make any direct criticism of the CSM in the course of the
interview. We are glad to set the record straight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
