<DOCNO>GH951204-000048</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000048</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Fears over `mass production' of TV puppies</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WILLIAM TINNING</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061041</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FEARS were expressed yesterday that the success of the BBC Scotland television
drama series Hamish Macbeth has led to a growth in unscrupulous dog dealers
using sub-standard stock to cash in on it.
The warning follows confirmation by the Scottish Kennel Club that dog breeders
have been receiving almost 100 inquiries daily about the availability of West
Highland white terrier puppies similar to the one given to PC Hamish Macbeth as
a present in the series.
Concern has been expressed that Westies and other popular breeds of dogs are
being churned out at puppy farms in certain areas of the country to meet
increasing public demand.
However, bodies such as the Scottish Kennel Club, the National Canine Defence
League, and the SSPCA, have a major task in identifying unscrupulous puppy
breeders and are looking to the Government to assist them.
The Scottish Kennel Club is opposed to the ``indiscriminate breeding'' on puppy
farms and says many of the puppies are bred from poor quality stock which is
not screened for hereditary diseases.
Mr Peter Mann, the club's vice-president, told The Herald yesterday: ``We do
not recommend that people use pet shops or dealers who are associated with
puppy farms. Anyone buying a puppy should use a KC registered dog breeder and
insist on seeing the mother of the litter.''
Mrs Aileen Hamilton, manager of the Dalkeith Pet Hotel and Grooming Centre,
said: ``A lot of these dogs coming in to be trimmed are of such poor quality
they are hardly recognisable as the breed they are supposed to be.''
She said te puppy farms used sub-standard conditions to ``mass produce'' the
puppies.
``Poor quality dogs which normally would not be used for breeding are being
used to meet the high demands of the public. While the practice is not illegal
I believe it is immoral.''
Mrs Hamilton, who breeds about three or four litters of Westies each year,
added: ``Puppy farms are breeding disasters and unsuspecting people are buying
them.''
Ms Anna Fox, of the Scottish Kennel Club, believes the demand for Westies,
which cost about #300 each, is unlikely to fade given that a new series of
Macbeth is to be shown in the new year.
</TEXT>
