<DOCNO>GH951204-000050</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000050</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>GEC loses #90m radar contract</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061043</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ELECTRONICS and defence giant GEC suffered a serious blow yesterday after the
Philippines government scrapped a massive radar deal designed to cover the
country's entire civil and military needs.
Details of the cancellation of the contract, worth nearly #90m to GEC-Marconi,
were widely reported in the Sunday newspapers in Manila.
Speaking from the capital, a spokesman for GEC-Marconi, a major GEC subsidiary
whose interests span torpedos to radars and which has a plant in Donibristle,
Fife, said: ``If true, we are naturally bitterly disappointed, but we have not
been informed.
``We need to consider our position and at the moment it would be inappropriate
to comment further.''
The spokesman described the contract as ``very big indeed''. It was won in the
face of ferocious competition against other European and worldwide electronics
and defence contractors.
GEC-Marconi, which has an annual turnover of #2500m and generates a third of
GEC's profits, has a signed contract with the Philippines government for the
radar deal, which was designed to provide a dual civil and military radar
system to cover the entire country.
The spokesman described the radar as a ``Rolls-Royce system'' and one which
would have been self-financing over a period of time.
President Fidel Ramos of the Philippines is understood to have abandoned the
contract following increasing pressure from Senator John Osmena who, it is
alleged, claimed the deal was overpriced. A direct beneficiary of the
cancellation is thought to be the French electronics giant Thomson CSF.
The group is expected to report half-year pre-tax profits which the City
believes will reach #412m for the six months to the end of September, compared
with #378m in the corresponding period last year.
Cancellation of the contract comes at a particularly sensitive time for GEC,
one of the UK's biggest exporters, following a major boardroom row last month
which resulted in a senior director being removed from the board.
Richard Reynolds, chairman of the group's telecommunications subsidiary GPT,
made his annoyance quite clear over the way in which GEC was looking for a
successor to Lord Weinstock, the 71-year-old managing director who is to step
down next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000051</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000051</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Harry Conroy meets a Prestwick canoeist and factory owner with a golden ambition Rapid expansion for hi-tech paddles</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>inside business</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061044</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PADDLE maker Alistair Wilson's ambition is to ensure that the winner of the
canoeing gold medal in next year's Olympic Games in Atlanta crosses the finish
line with the help of Lendal Products equipment.
At this year's World Canoeing Championships in Nottingham, every individual
medal winner used a Lendal paddle.
Lendal Products has been making paddles in its Prestwick workshop since 1972
when Mr Wilson and his wife, Marianne, founded the company but it is only
recently that new techniques have revolutionised the business and brought mass
production within reach of what had been a craft industry.
``In the past when paddles were made of wood, it would take five days for the
entire process to be completed but now we use thermal plastic and the entire
process can be completed in 10 minutes,'' said Mr Wilson.
``We now have the potential to make as many tubes for paddles as we want. In
the past, we would perhaps be able to make 30 tubes every day. Now we can make
one every two               minutes.''
Despite the introduction of machine processes, each paddle is still a highly
technical object and is made to very high standards.
``We have a responsibility to ensure that our products can withstand the
tremendous strain a paddle is under when it is being thrust through the
water,'' said Mr Wilson. ``If a canoeist is five miles offshore and his paddle
breaks, he is not going to be very pleased. One broken paddle can put someone's
life in danger.''
He speaks from a personal knowledge of the sport as both he and Marianne
represented Britain in the Tokyo Olympics. Mr Wilson still canoes across the
eight miles of sea which separates Ailsa Craig from the Ayrshire coast.
Lendal Products introduced the thermal moulded plastic blades last year with
the help of a regional enterprise grant after its accountants, BDO Stoy
Hayward, put together a business plan. Lendal uses its own design and
production system and expects to increase its workforce of seven to keep up
with demand.
Orders are now coming in from Japan, South Africa, Australia, Hong Kong, and
the United States.
``We recently supplied between 400 and 500 blades to the US and have the
potential to grow as big as we want,'' said Mr Wilson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000052</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000052</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Major takes the rhubarb for baffling obfuscation</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061045</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JOHN MAJOR's good deed and a Scottish law firm's transfer deed have been
selected for awards by anti-gobbledegook campaigners.
The Plain Language Commission has given the Prime Minister its Golden Rhubarb
Trophy for the most baffling Government document of 1995 - an 11,000-word
booklet on the Northern Ireland peace process.
Picking up the Bronze Rhubarb Trophy is Edinburgh legal firm Tods Murray WS for
archaic language in a deed of transfer.
It struggles its way through more than 200 words with the help of two sets of
brackets, two ``herebys'', a ``thereof'', a ``hereinafter'', and just one comma.
These two, along with Silver Rhubarb Trophy winner NatWest Bank for ``the worst
gobbledegook in a `simple guide' to mortgages'', receive vacuum-packed sticks
of the fruit.
Mr Martin Cutts, director of the Stockport-based research firm, described
Frameworks For The Future, outlining the peace settlement proposals, as
``rambling, repetitive, jargon-filled, and incomprehensible to its target
audience''.
One sentence runs to 121 words compared to the commission's recommendation of
15 or 20-word sentences for a complex subject.
``Mr Major's foreword declares three times that everyone should read the
booklet and voice their opinions but it's brimming with terms like `cognizant
of either option and open to its democratic realisation', `embrace the totality
of relationships', and `quantum of public expenditure'.
``Belfast people who queued for a copy were so annoyed they nominated it for
the accolade.''
Meanwhile, Mr David Anderson of Tods Murray said the transfer deed had been
used in the same form for 20 years and had provoked no complaints.
He added: ``We agree wholeheartedly that all consumer contracts should be in
plain, intelligible language. However, that does not mean that it is either
necessary or desirable that they should be in colloquial language.
``In our view it is perfectly clear and understandable.''
The contents of the deed include - We ....... do hereby assign and transfer to
the said person or persons (if more than one person equally between them and to
the survivor of them) (who and whose successors and assignees are hereinafter
referred to as ``the transferee'') the Holiday Certificate for Weekly Period
Number 00 of Highland Lodge of the Loch Rannoch Highland Club, by virtue of
which Holiday Certificate we as the holders thereof are entitled to occupy the
said unit which is more particularly described in the said Holiday Certificate
for the said period in each year all in terms of and with and under the
conditions specified in the Constitution of the said club including the
obligation to pay all management charges due by the holders of the said Holiday
Certificate ..... in witness whereof these presents are executed at .....''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000053</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000053</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rugby star found dead</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061046</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A RUGBY club was in mourning yesterday after one of its top players was found
dead.
Mr George Dickson, 31, was due to play in a National League match for Borders
club St Boswell's on Saturday.
But after he failed to keep an appointment in the morning, friends called at
his home and found his body.
A post-mortem examination will be carried out today.
Club secretary David Elliot said: ``We are all devastated. George was one of
the most popular guys in the team. He had been a member of the club since he
was at primary school and had played for our first team for many seasons.''
Mr Elliot added: ``He missed two months of this season after breaking his
collar-bone in one of the first matches. But he returned to action a couple of
weeks ago and seemed delighted to be back in the fray.''
Mr Dickson, a barman in a local hotel, was single. His parents, who also live
in the town, were too upset to speak yesterday.
St Boswell's scheduled home match against Ardrossan Accies was called off just
an hour before kick-off after the news of the tragedy spread around the
tight-knit community.
Mr Dickson's funeral is expected to be held on Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000054</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000054</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The old rugged coast</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patricia Fenn</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>18</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>holiday 96</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061047</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CAN there be, anywhere in the world, a more blatantly beautiful coastline than
that of the Sorrento Peninsula? I doubt it. Our ancestors knew what they were
doing when they featured it prominently on their Grand Tours, built stately
villas-with-a-view there, and painted it from every aspect.
Across the ridiculously azure waters its northern shores face Naples, with
Vesuvius obligingly providing the drama; at night, with the lights beginning to
reflect, the scene is achingly romantic. By day it is the drive along the
corkscrewing southern Amalfi corniche, stopping to photograph pastel-coloured
villages clinging precariously to the craggy mountains, that ensures lasting
memories.
The grande dame of the peninsula is undoubtedly Sorrento; in her prime at the
turn of the century, her charms may seem a trifle faded now but the good bones
are still in evidence. An example of the period flavour is the Grand Hotel
Vigtoria Excelsior. Even if you are not staying here, do call in to admire the
painted ceilings, rococo plasterwork, gilded mirrors, marble floors, and
picture Caruso in residence. Sit, Campari Soda in hand, among the oleander
trees on the terrace and observe, far, far below, the buzzing Marina Piccola. A
private lift will take you down (otherwise it's a bus ride or a taxingly steep
ravine hike).
Sorrento is the base for numerous excursions, and from the Marina run all
manner of craft, rusty-old and jet-new to Capri, Ischia, Naples and Amalfi.
Tempting though it is to squeeze all these into a holiday, plus Vesuvius,
Pompeii, and even Rome by coach, do leave some time for Sorrento itself.
First impressions of the frenetic main highway, the Corso d'Italia, may fail to
charm, but I found the town grew on me as I explored more deeply. Parallel with
the Corso, off the main square, the Piazza Tasso, runs the Via Fuoro, a cool
alleyway lined with tiny shops which offer a glimpse of the character of the
old Sorrento. Here you will find not only tourist trash but examples of the
town's specialities - leather, jewellery and marquetry.
In high summer, when the temperature soars to the nineties and above, the
siesta hour gets quadrupled and the shutters stay down until 5.30. This is the
time to take a cool stroll and perhaps make some purchases, since the exchange
rate is favourable. It is also a good time to indulge in another Italian
speciality, the gelato. Look on the right hand side for the Sorrento Inn, where
42 varieties are made as they have been for four generations, from real eggs,
real cream, real fruit.
Walk through quiet leafy lanes and steep cobbled alleys by fin-de-siecle
villas, down to the Marina Grande, the fishing harbour, to eat at one of the
simple trattorie that ring the waterside. An insalata Caprese (tomatoes and
mozzarella salad), with grilled sardines and a carafe of vino blanco wIll cost
less than #6. Yellow and white striped bathing huts built out on a jetty evoke
the image of frolicking bathing belles and their moustachioed escorts.
Sorrento's main beach is down here, But don't get too excited. Beaches are
emphatically not what you come to the region for.
The proximity of Vesuvius gives a clue to the colour of the sand, if any, and
the water in the harbour would not pass any EU test. The Italians don't mind.
They thrive on noise and close proximity, and there is plenty of both on Marina
Grande beach. In high summer it seems impossible to squeeze one more body into
the vociferous rows, whose occupants stop shouting to their loved ones only to
step into the murky, litter-ridden depths with every appearance of delight.
Number one excursion should be the unsurpassable Amalfi coast, either by coach,
which includes a stop in the delightful unspoiled hill-top village of Ravello,
or by boat, allowing two swims on the way and a chance to shop in Positano's
chic and unusual boutiques.
A 15-minute jet ride away is the legendary Isle of Capri, with eponymous main
town and Anacapri a steep bus ride away.
There has always been rivalry between the two settlements, the Capresi looking
down (figuratively speaking) on the peasants up the hill, and the Anacapresi
maintaining that while the marauding Saracens raped the female inhabitants of
the lower slopes, debasing the blood, they never had the strength to climb the
mountain, so the locals can still claim to be descendants of the noble Greeks.
Those, like me, who remember the natural elegance of the old Capri, when the
little town was an international fashion centre, might mourn the advent of the
trainer-and-shorts day tripper influx, but in the evening, when the mob has
sailed away, the atmosphere is little changed. The photographic Piazzetta, the
hub of all socialising, is as pretty as ever, still mercifully traffic-free,
with goods and luggage being transported by hand-carts. You cannot see the sky
from here, so tightly packed are the huge cream parasols of the cafes,
sheltering the onlookers of the non-stop parade. The cost of a freshly squeezed
orange drink here - around #4 - is justified by the free entertainment.
From the Piazzetta runs a maze of narrow lines, lined with dazzlingly white
walls. Most tourists, sheeplike, follow the Via V Emanuele, bordered with
international couturiers and jewellers, who find ready customers in the patrons
of the luxurious hotel, the Quisisana, at the end of the parade; very few
bother to explore further than the Certosa di San Giacomo, which admittedly
offers superb views.
The lucky residents will have time and inclination in the early morning or
evening to climb ancient stone steps, and follow the paths high above the
little town, past flowery gardens and unexpected glimpses of the turquoise sea
below. Try turning left at the Quisisana along the Via Camerelle to the Punta
Tragara and keep going along the coast path, past the deep cave complete with
Roman remains, to the Arco Naturale, a natural limestone arch that frames a
perfect sunset shot of the distinctive Faraglioni rocks.
Anacapri is cooler, cheaper, less crowded, except at the bus depot where the
hordes disembarked to visit the villa of San Michele and to take a marvellous
funicular ride to the summit of Monte Solaro. Swinging silently high above the
vineyards it is strikingly cool and peaceful and the ultimate reward is the
view awaiting at the summit of the whole island and particularly the Faraglioni.
Otherwise the trick is to do whatever the other tourists are not. As the
minibuses roar up the hill to disgorge their contents in the centre, hop on a
local bus and take a 60p ride through the countryside to Il Faro, the
lighthouse marking Punta Carena in the south-west of the island. From the rocks
below you can swim in the bluest of blue. By five o'clock the tourists will be
back on their coaches and it is safe to do to the Blue Grotto, another bus-ride
from the town. Swimming solitarily into the truly azure cave is infinitely
preferable to paying for a jostling boat-ride.
The rest of Anacapri is a delightfully sleepy backwater, whose residents
assemble every evening in the main square, to sit on lovely green and yellow
tiled benches, watching the well-dressed children play and catching up on the
latest gossip. Tucked away in the Piazza San Nicola is the church of San
Michele, whose entire floor is covered in eighteenth-century majolica tiles
depicting a charmingly naive Garden of Eden.
Without doubt the best time to visit southern Italy is spring and autumn. A
combination of Sorrento and Capri, flying from Glasgow, costs from #399.
Patricia Fenn finds romance
in the air as she goes via
leafy lanes and cobbled alleys
</TEXT>
</DOC>
