<DOCNO>GH951204-000055</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000055</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Forest role a boost for rural community</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DAVID ROSS Highland Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061048</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE people of Laggan have won a four-year campaign to assume control of the
3500-acre Strathmashie Forest, making it Britain's first community forest.
The move, predicted by The Herald last month, is seen as the most significant
and radical development in rural policy in the Highlands for generations.
Yet the commitment of Scottish Secretary Mr Michael Forsyth has gone virtually
unreported.
He made the announcement on Thursday night at the end of his speech at
Strathclyde University on the future of Scotland.
Having dealt with constitutional matters, Mr Forsyth turned to the Government's
proposal to hand over control of the Scottish Office-owned crofting estates to
local crofting trusts.
He quoted an article by Highland writer and historian Dr James Hunter.
Mr Forsyth said: ``Our political opponents may be content just to sing
sentimentally about their wee bit hill and glen, but we give the land back to
the people who can manage it best. Similarly with forestry there is an
opportunity for the empowerment of local communities.
``There is currently much discussion, some of it embodied in the Rural White
Paper to be published shortly, about how forestry can contribute to the
well-being of those who live in rural Scotland.
``I want action as well as discussion. That is why I intend to visit Laggan to
explore with the people there practical ways of bringing the local forestry
plantation under community control.
``They have ideas about using the forest to greater local benefit and I believe
they should have the opportunity to try them out. I will therefore set up a
pilot scheme there.''
Although the financial arrangements for a forest whose estimated value ranges
from #750,000 to #2m are still to be worked out, it is understood Mr Forsyth
had to overcome considerable opposition before he could make his announcement.
This came not least from his own Forestry Minister Lord Lindsay and from the
Forestry Commission, which in recent years has been dealing with the highest
bidder, the commercial sector, rather than local communities when disposing of
any significant sections of its 1.5m acres.
In Laggan, where the population this century has dropped from more than 1000 to
about 200, it was clear the announcement held the key to the community's
future. Dr Ian Richardson, a retired doctor who has been one of the local
campaigners, said: ``There is an extraordinary feeling of optimism here now.
``It has been a real tonic, particularly to the young people who see in this
Laggan forest initiative a means of having a life in their own place,'' Dr
Richardson said.
``Mr Forsyth must get enormous credit for that. Instead of just talking, he has
done something.''
Dr Richardson said funds for a survey into local attitudes had been diverted
towards determining the skills local people could bring to the undertaking.
Fencing and forestry contractor Mr David Campbell, who has lived in Laggan for
the past 35 years, said: ``It is great, unbelievable, so welcome in an area
where there are only two men under the age of 30 in full-time employment
locally.
``The potential is enormous - from adding value to the timber products to
establishing the first forest walks for blind and disabled people. It is not
only Laggan, the whole of Badenoch can benefit from this.''
Meanwhile, historian Dr Hunter said yesterday the announcement was of enormous
importance to the whole of Britain.
``This development is considerably more significant than the proposed transfer
of all the publicly-owned crofting estates which has been attended by such
publicity,'' Dr Hunter said. ``In the first place, the Laggan forest represents
a considerable asset in financial terms, thousands of acres of mature timber.
``The crofting estates are restricted to the marginal land on the western
periphery, but there are publicly owned forests throughout the country. A
precedent is now being set in Laggan which could lead towards the Scandinavian
model of community-managed forests. These provide a stability of local
employment through environmentally - sensitive management.''
</TEXT>
