<DOCID>GH951204-000057</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>RAF probe pilot's Santa method</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061050</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN RAF pilot's method of delivering Christmas presents to his mother's house,
by using his helicopter, was last night under investigation by his commanders.
Squadron Leader Gavin Davey, 37, landed his #6m Puma helicopter in a field next
to the mansion home of his mother, Sheena, on the main street of Abernethy,
Perthshire, last week and then delivered the gifts, which included two mountain
bikes.
Mr Davey is based at Aldergrove, outside Belfast, and the helicopter is used in
Northern Ireland for surveillance work.
His mother was not available for comment last night. His stepfather, Mr David
Shepherd, defended him. ``Gavin followed all RAF landing procedures,'' he said.
``The local police were informed. He did nothing wrong.''
He said he dropped off ``presents including mountain bikes for his sons who are
coming to stay with us over Christmas. I don't know who is complaining. Our
neighbours and friends are very supportive. The whole thing seems like a storm
in a teacup.''
There had been reports that some villagers complained about the waste of
tax-payers' money by the squadron leader, who has apparently arrived by
helicopter on previous occasions.
Schoolboy Tim Coles, 16, said: ``He has been dropping in by helicopter on and
off for the last ten years.
``The first time he did it, I was at primary school and half of the village
rushed down to see him land and take off. Most people accept it now as part of
village life, but a few do moan about it.''
A shopkeeper said it was ``not unusual to see Gavin buzzing about in his
helicopter''.
An RAF spokeswoman confirmed the squadron leader had made the landing last
Monday and said: ``Checks will be made. We don't want the public thinking that
pilots are using RAF aircraft willy nilly for private purposes.''
She added: ``The helicopter was en route from Lossiemouth to Otterburn and did
not divert.''
She said landing permission had been sought.
``He has landed there before to show the aircraft to village schoolchildren,''
she added.
</TEXT>
