<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parents in bid to halt closure of secondary which is only 40% full and faces #780,000 repairs bill Opt-out plan to save school</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BARCLAY McBAIN Education Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061051</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EXCLUSIVE
PARENTS are exploiting the Government's opting-out legislation to fight the
closure of a secondary school which is less than 40% full and needs #780,000
worth of urgent repairs.
Strathclyde Region has proposed the closure next June of Glasgow's Garthamlock
Secondary, which was badly damaged by fire in May.
The authority wants to merge it with Lochend Secondary in Easterhouse or,
alternatively, pupils could be sent to Lochend or Smithycroft Secondary in
Carntyne, depending on their feeder primaries.
It is thought to be the only local authority to seek a school closure in the
months before the existing regions are replaced by the single-tier councils in
April.
A consultative document which will go before the region's ruling Labour group
today, puts forward educational and financial grounds for closing the school.
It had a capacity of nearly 1100 pupils before a major fire in October, but the
current roll of 415 is projected to fall further over the next five years.
If, as expected, Labour councillors endorse the report, it will go before the
education committee on Wednesday before being issued for consultation with a
six-week timescale for responses.
However, as a first step towards thwarting the closure plans, the school board
is tomorrow night expected to back a motion calling for a ballot on opting out.
Board chairman Mr George Boor said yesterday: ``There are gang fights between
Easterhouse and Garthamlock boys every day of the week. If you had them in the
same school you can imagine what would happen.
``We don't want the school to opt out, just to keep it open.''
A ballot would not prevent Strathclyde from consulting on the proposals - but
it would halt their implementation for six months or longer.
A decision this week to have a ballot must be reconsidered by the board again
within six weeks. If ratified, the board must inform the authority and the
Scottish Office and hold the ballot within three months.
If fewer than half the parents vote, a second ballot must be completed within
14 days. If that vote is in favour, the board must submit its proposals for
running a self-governing school to the Secretary of State, Mr Michael Forsyth,
within one month.
In Garthamlock's case, he would reject opting out because of the school's roll
and the capital expenditure needed.
The school was one of 13 unidentified Scottish secondaries which the Accounts
Commission recently said could be readily closed because they were less than
60% full and there were adequate local alternatives for pupils.
The local authorities' financial watchdog also called on the Government to
provide extra cash for schools receiving pupils from closing establishments to
enable them to offer excellent facilities from day one.
Strathclyde operates a self-insurance scheme and, if closure goes ahead, the
authority recommends using the #780,000 which would have gone on repairing the
fire damage at Garthamlock to improving facilities at the receiving schools.
Strathclyde had considered closing Garthamlock some time ago but held off to
see whether its roll benefited from other school closures in the area.
A region report states, however, that the continuing small roll makes it
increasingly difficult to offer pupils a full course choice and a broad,
balanced curriculum.
A merger with Lochend would give it a roll of more than 1100 pupils. If
Garthamlock's pupils transferred to Lochend or Smithycroft, the former's roll
would rise to more than 1000, the latter's to 800.
Under either option there would be revenue savings of more than #500,000 a year.
Dr Malcolm Green, a senior Strathclyde councillor who speaks on education for
the new City of Glasgow Council, said yesterday: ``I hope that publication of
this document will enable the whole community in Garthamlock to engage
seriously with the dilemma we face.''
The new council will be under severe pressure to tackle surplus places because
its revenue budget will be much smaller than Strathclyde's.
Meanwhile, parents of pupils at Gateside Primary, near Beith, Ayrshire, who
signed a petition calling for a ballot to opt-out, have changed their minds.
They want to withdraw their signatures - which would lead to the scrapping of
the ballot.
Cunninghame North Labour MP Brian Wilson said yesterday: ``As far as I am aware
about 40 of the people who signed the 49-name petition have had second thoughts.
``Many now feel they were misled. They thought they were signing a petition
calling for information about a ballot.
"They are now seeking legal advice to see if their names can be withdrawn
following assurances that the question of closing the school does not arise and
the school is safe for the foreseeable future.''
Mr Wilson added: ``If they succeed there will be no need for a ballot. But I am
writing to the Secretary of State asking him not to let a ballot to go ahead''
When the school board received the petition they had no option but to call for
an opting-out ballot.
</TEXT>
