<HEADLINE>Financial services industry receives qualified criticism</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Conroy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>16</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>inside business </FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061052</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE financial services industry has come in for a great deal of criticism and
Peter Griffiths-Buchanan, managing director of Whitelaw Wells Financial
Planning, believes much is justified.
He points out that, while all 102,000 financial advisers have their Financial
Planning Certificate which is the minimum qualification required by the
Personal Investment Authority, only some 1500 have taken the Advanced Financial
Planning Certificate, and less than 40 people are Fellows of the Institute of
Financial Planning.
``I have my advanced certificates and I hope to gain my fellowship next year,''
said Mr Griffiths-Buchanan, who claims the industry is better qualified in
other countries. In the United States, 30,000 hold the equivalent qualification
to the fellowship and almost 600 in Australia.
``I was a qualified engineer before I entered the financial services industry
and I was schooled in the principle that you required qualifications before you
could work at certain levels. I believe that attitude must be introduced into
financial planning.''
Mr Griffiths-Buchanan became a financial adviser when he arrived in this
country from South Africa in 1987.
His strong views on how the industry should be run come from his belief in the
need for sound financial advice.
``My family had a small farming estate in New Cumnock and my father was
eventually left #100,000 in 1972 when my grandfather died. My father was never
given any advice on how to invest the inheritance and by 1992 it was only worth
#40,000.''
He believes the financial consultants should move towards being a fee earning
industry rather than taking commission. ``I charge fees because I want my
clients to be in no doubt that the advice they receive is objective and not
clouded by commission objectives.''
Whitelaw Wells charges an average of #72 per hour and Mr Griffiths-Buchanan
said that between 30% and 40% of his clients were better off than they would
have been if the business had been done on a commission basis.
``For about half of my clients, there is no financial difference in the two
sytems but it removes any doubts about my motives,'' he said. ``But I accept
that the fee payment method does not become cost effective until a person earns
around #30,000 a year.''
</TEXT>
