<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>15</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061054</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AFTER the Budget and the flurry of interest rate speculation last week, there
is only a light diet of official statistics to feed off this week.
The narrow measure of the money supply, M0, due to be published later today, is
expected to rise by 0.6%, taking the annual rate up from 5.2% in October to
5.6% last month.
James Capel's Adam Cole is forecasting a bounce-back in manufacturing output in
Wednesday's production figures for October. He expects manufacturing to post a
gain of 0.3%. This would raise the annual rate from 0.6% to 0.9%.
TODAY - Reserves (November); M0 (November). TOMORROW - None announced.
WEDNESDAY - Index of production (October). THURSDAY - CBI survey of
distributive trades (November). FRIDAY - None announced.
</TEXT>
