<DOCNO>GH951204-000062</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000062</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Surgeon suspended for cutting off wrong leg</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061055</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FLORIDA health authorities have suspended a doctor for six months and fined him
$10,000 (#6600) for mistakenly cutting off the wrong leg of a patient in a
botched amputation.
The Florida Board of Medicine also gave Dr Rolando Sanchez a formal reprimand,
imposed two years' probation under the supervision of another surgeon, and
required him to attend a class in ``risk management education''.
``The risk management part of the decision is the most appropriate,'' said Dr
Fred Reddy, a former president of the Hillsborough County Medical Association.
Sanchez's medical licence was already suspended in July after another patient
at a different hospital complained he had amputated one of her toes without
permission during a foot operation.
The wrong-leg amputation, which drew national attention, occurred at Tampa's
University Community Hospital last February.
In a three-day hearing on the case earlier this year, Sanchez and his lawyer
argued that mistakes by other hospital staffers - including preparing the wrong
leg for surgery - and the severely diseased condition of both of the patient's
legs led Sanchez to believe he was operating on the correct limb.
Sanchez himself testified that he only learned of his mistake when an attending
nurse, reviewing the patient's file, began to shake and cry. By then it was too
late to reverse the operation.
The patient, 52-year-old Willie King, had his diseased leg removed at another
hospital. He has received a $1.2m (#800,000) settlement from Sanchez and the
hospital. The board's ruling took into account the 140 days Sanchez has already
been suspended, meaning he could be back in the operating room by next
month.-Reuter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
