<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000064</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000064</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>SCOTLAND'S GOVERNMENT The way ahead is unclear</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061057</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
YOUR editorial on December 1 claims the way ahead on devolution is clear and of
course it is easy to reach that conclusion if you ignore, as you do in the
discussion, some arguments and choose to misrepresent others.
You suggest the results of the British Social Attitudes Survey point towards an
assembly in Edinburgh. But surely the disillusion people feel towards
poliicians is an argument against and not for another tier of government.
Mr Major, you say but without supporting evidence, ignores the fact that
Scotland is a separate nation.
Throughout his five years as Prime Minister he has returned repeatedly to the
question of better government for Scotland. He has enhanced the role of the
Scottish Secretary and the Scottish Office. He has maintained Scottish Office
funding and in all his speeches and interviews, etc, he has never suggested
that Scotland is somehow subordinate to England.
But, and it is a very big but, he believes, as all Unionists believe, that the
value of the Union to all the people of the United Kingdom is greater than the
sum of its parts and that anything which threatens to break up that Union must
be resisted.
You go on to say that Mr Major is opposed to devolution, but what he is
actually saying is that a devolved assembly in Edinburgh with the power to
raise taxes is a long-term threat to the Union. Conflict between Edinburgh and
London over finance and other issues is inevitable even though it might not
manifest itself for the first couple of years.
Scotland's over-representation at West-minster could not be sustained and the
two governments would drift apart and thus independence becomes the only
alternative.
The SNP certainly see it that way and are happy to go along with it even though
the vast majority of people in Scotland wish to preserve the Union.
More immediate is the question of the tax-raising powers. George Robertson says
taxes could go down as well as up, or more likely he suggests not be changed.
Before the last election Neil Kinnock said Labour would retain the nuclear
deterrent but would never use it. George Robertson's assertion on the
tax-raising powers is similar and equally facile.
The Scottish Labour Party are by inclination more akin to Old Labour than New
Labour and if their record in local government is anything to go by the
likelihood must be that taxes will go up. Any tax increase is a tax on jobs, a
tax on people's choice, and a disincentive to investment.
No-one has enjoyed the tax increases since 1992 and understandably the
Government has suffered in popularity, but we now seem to be on a downward path
again. That must not be put at risk, particularly in one part of the UK on its
own.
In your editorial you make no mention of the role of Scottish Secretary, if we
had an assembly in Edinburgh. His position would be anomalous to say the least
and if he is not sitting at the Cabinet table daily fighting his corner
Scotland will be the loser and friction and misunderstanding between the two
governments will rise.
As yet we have not seen any real discussion about the most recent proposals put
forward by Michael Forsyth. The opposition parties have chosen to dismiss them
out of hand, but surely these ideas deserve more serious analysis and as an
independent newspaper you could do that. There are proposals for other forms of
devolution there which merit consideration.
I have to to disagree with your conclusion. They way ahead is far from clear
and the debate must go on.
Michael Ashmore,
Chairman, Clydesdale Conservative and Unionist Association,
Hozier House, Lanark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000065</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000065</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Hospitals urged to do better</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061058</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A REPORT into the way Scots hospitals communicate with patients has called for
improved complaints procedures to be put in place.
The study by the Scottish Office Audit Unit also urges greater effort in
obtaining the views of patients and highlights some hospitals' ``piecemeal''
reviews of their signposting which, in many cases, was poor. However, the
report concluded that communication standards were generally improving,
particularly in general hospital booklets.
Scottish Health Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton welcomed the findings, but
recommended further action.
``The Patient's Charter,'' he said, ``emphasised the importance of better
communications between the NHS and those who use the services, and I am
delighted the performance of the NHS in this area is improving.
``But more remains to be done, and I have asked health boards and NHS Trusts to
use the action checklist in the report to help them make further progress. For
our part, we are well-advanced in bringing new complaints procedures into force
as from next April.''
The report said the quality of clinical communication was variable, with scope
for providing better written information and more support to patients in
explaining information and counselling them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000066</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000066</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Young lady vet wins me over</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>CHARLIE ALLAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>17</PAGE>
<FLAG>farmer's diary</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Illustration</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061059</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IT is remarkable. You don't usually get pneumonia among your calves if you
breed your own and keep them at home, yet that has been the big excitement this
week.
I had been busy and had been throwing the feed at them and skimping on even
looking at them for five minutes.
It's an easy job. The heifers get one bag of nuts and the bulls get two. They
are bedded twice a week and they need a new bale of treated straw about every
five days. So if you are going to skimp it's fairly easy. You can feed the 100
beasts in half an hour, nae bother.
Finally, on Saturday I noticed. One of the bulls did not get up for his nuts.
Usually they stampede at you but there was only a half-hearted wander over to
the trough. To my horror, I realised that a fine black Simmental calf was
impersonating a bellows. And worse than that, he wasn't just heaving the air in
and out. He had that jerk in his breathing that shakes the whole body and so
often means that what you need is the knackery.
In the days when I had up to 400 barley beef bulls, we used to have chronic
pneumonia. There was never a time when we didn't have a few being treated and
at least one whose lungs were damaged and who was taking his revenge on my bank
balance. That kind would save you so much money if they would just die.
Of course, those barley beefers were collected up from all the dairy farms
around about and dealers would roll up with small lots of third-raters which
they couldn't sell. I'd always give them a bid of some kind. Unfortunately, I
so often got not merely extra calves, but more to add to the Little Ardo
pneumonia bank.
The vets weren't much help. I suspect it was just that we called them in when
it was too late. But on one occasion when our usual remedies weren't working, I
announced my intention to try the vet again.
``Well,'' said Gordon the cattleman, ``If you're phoning the vet you may as
well phone the knackery at the same time.''
That remark came back to me on Saturday as I surveyed the cream of the crop of
1995. There was another and another and another - maybe. We haven't seen any
respiratory problems since we came back from Kenya. Six cough-free years, and
there they were again.
So I called the vet despite my fears about sending good money after bad.
My natural honesty forces me to admit that when I saw that it was yet another
young lady vet I wasn't pleased.
To me, a vet should be about 55, rather overweight and male.
Those older vets went into the profession when it had no glamour and academic
standards were not the priority. They were practical chaps who would have
preferred to be farmers but hadn't the capital. They came to the profession
without much intellectual baggage and they made good vets.
Don't get me wrong. The calves died just the same, but with the old school you
get a certain reassurance in their presence.
James Herriot changed all that. He glamorised the life of a vet and chocked the
vet schools. They had no alternative but to ration places to the brightest.
When a vet under 30 comes on to the place you can be sure you are being visited
by an intellectual giant whose natural environment is the lecture theatre
rather than the byre.
Anyway, this slip of a girl came up to the byre to see the worst case which I
had tied up, not that it was going anywhere. My fears that she wouldn't know
what she was looking at were reinforced when she didn't seem impressed with the
nearness of death. It was agreed that she would give the calf an intravenous
injection and a course of other stuff into the muscle.
After a brief look in the court, she said I could pull out the coughers and
give then a jab of the intramuscular stuff and that would be about it.
I got a pen for five out in our open-fronted shed and made them comfortable.
With fearful heart I looked in the court the next day and, yes, there were two
more sets of bellows in action. And then down to the sick bay expecting to find
one dead and the others below average.
To my astonishment, there were no bellows going and even the `dead' one came to
eat.
The vet may have been too young, too intelligent, too thin and too female, but
she seems to have saved my calf and goodness knows how much money.
n I'm not as keen as the boys on killing things, though I do like the social
side of shooting. I'm happiest with the gun when I can call it pest control
rather than ``sport''.  Sport, I think, should be enjoyed by both sides and
that doesn't seem to me to reflect accurately what happens at most shoots.
We got an invitation to help a friend at Forfar who is overrun with hares. He
told us we could take a pheasant too, but cocks only.
We were taken aback when the first bird to rise was a hen pheasant and our host
shot it. Nothing was said but the second pheasant to get up was a cock. It was
Potions' but he let it go.
``It's okay,'' said our host kindly, ``you can shoot cocks.''
``Oh, said Potions. ``I thought that must be a hen 'cos it was different from
the one you shot.''
We may not be invited back.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000067</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000067</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Memories of warmth in the cold light of day</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JEAN SANDISON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061060</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN I was growing up, or trying to, the most important people in my life were
my mum and dad, my two brothers, and my sister. They gave me security and,
although I didn't appreciate it then, a whole lot of love. Yes, every family
has its ups and downs, arguments and squabbles and I remember them as well, but
I remember most of all our happy times together as a family.
Now adult, well sort of, I now lead my own separate life and we have drifted
apart, at least physically, but we keep in touch regularly by telephone and,
whenever possible, we visit each other on a regular basis. I suppose we like to
think of ourselves, at least I do, as being fully detached from the ``Old
Bat's'' apron strings; mother's family nick-name because of her great affection
for flying mammals.
As a single parent, keeping in touch with my family is not easy. Doing so
requires a bucketful of planning and careful cash-husbandry. Indeed, without
the support of my family, and the support of a caring society, a reasonable
life as a single parent would be pretty damn near impossible. I am ever more
aware, particularly as Christmas draws near, of the importance and comfort of a
stable family environment.
As I look at my daughter, Jessica, soon to be three years young, thoughts of
Christmas past come flooding back; the excitement of stockings by the chimney;
the sound of wrapping paper being opened on Christmas morning, the smell of
Christmas lunch; the obligatory, cold, brisk, Boxing Day walk by the sea; a
family, together, sharing their joy and their sadness.
I like to think of Jessica and myself as being a family but, realistically, it
could be a long time before I can create that sort of magic for my daughter.
``Family'' presupposes the presence of a father and the nearest Jessica has
ever got to hers, so far, is a brief glimpse of a denim-clad bum in the far
distance. Once in nearly three years.
OK, a mother's love is all a child really needs and single mums are as caring
as nuclear family mums any day of the week. However, few single parents would
deny that, sometimes, we get lonely and that sometimes we wish our child's
natural father would walk through the door and make it all better. With a bit
of luck he will be better-looking too and have a whole new personality and, oh
joy, perhaps even a bulging wallet.
I know this is not going to happen and I feel desperately sorry for Jessica. I
didn't plan it to be that way, but I feel that even before she was born I
stacked up trouble and angst for my daughter. As she grows older she will have
to face up to telling her friends why she does not have a father, why he did
not want her. All I can do is to love her more, make sure that she knows how
important she is, how special she is to me and to her grandparents, aunts, and
uncles.
Families take a lot for granted, small, seemingly inconsequential things; daily
chores, shopping, bumps and bruises, comment and criticism, talking and simply
being there for one another. When I was a child I could not conceive of my
parents not being together. They were always there, together, invariably happy,
and I automatically assumed that, one day, I would be in a similar position
with a husband and family of my own.
I am doing the best I can and over the past year I have created a secure and
happy home for Jessica and myself. We may not have a man about the house, but
then, men do have drawbacks, in spite of their occasional ability to mend a
leaking tap. Who knows, one day Mr Right may appear? Until he does, and proves
that he is indeed Mr Right, Jessica and I will get along just fine, believe me.
Which brings me back to the imminent advent of a family Christmas. I need not
have worried. We will be spending it with my mum, dad, and elder brother and
his family on Deeside. Also, my younger brother, who now lives in Finland, has
invited Jessica and me over beforehand for a December holiday. I can't wait to
see how Jessica reacts to her first flight - and to finding out whether or not
Mr Claus is a bachelor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
