<HEADLINE>New brews going down well</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Lachie Kennedy</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061061</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Fancy a pint of Skullsplitter or Blackout? Lachie Kennedy looks at what is on
offer to discerning drinkers
A NIGHT out at the local can take on a whole new meaning in some pubs
stretching from the Highlands and Islands to the south coast of England.
Instead of the traditional Scottish request for a ``hauf and a hauf'' you are
as likely to hear someone ask for a pint of Skullsplitter or Blackout. Or the
order might be for a pint of Christmas Noggin or Santa's Tipple.
It's all part of an ongoing revolution by discerning beer drinkers looking for
something different to whet their palates, something to tickle their taste buds
and give them a bit of a kick.
At the same time it is helping with the establishment of small local breweries
as they spring up in towns and cities the length and breadth of the country.
Even some publicans have joined the revolution and now make their own brews on
the premises.
Beer festivals are held where hundreds turn up to sample the latest brews, some
of them so powerful that pubs serve them only in one-third pint measures. Like
Uncle Igor's, a Welsh ale brewed in very small quantities with a mind-boggling
alcohol by volume content of 21%. According to Nick Bromfield, who started his
own Fyfe Brewery Company earlier this year: ``A half pint of Uncle Igor's is
the equivalent of six or seven vodkas, enough to put you well over the drinks
driving limit.''
Most of Mr Bromfield's Auld Alliance is sold in his own Harbour Bar in
Kirkcaldy, although some of his output finds its way to the west coast.
He said: ``Customers seem to like it and as far as I am concerned it has been a
success.''
In Orkney, the Orkney Brewery at Quoyloo, set up in 1988, now produces several
beers, including Skullsplitter, named after Haus Akluis, the Viking seventh
Earl of Orkney, who had a habit of splitting people's skulls with a huge axe.
Earlier this year they introduced a new brew aptly named The Red Macgregor.
Most of their output is ``exported'' to the mainland where it is sold mostly in
Central Scotland but can be found in bars as far south as Bristol and Cardiff.
Ron Hill, manager of the brewery which now employs eight, said: ``Very little
is sold locally.''
Scotland already has 18 independent brewers and six brew pubs with more on the
horizon. Some of them, such as Belhaven, have been around a long time and it
continues to produce award-winning beers supplying 56 of their 65 houses.
The revolution started 25 years ago when four lads on a boozy holiday in
Ireland decided the beer they were supping lacked something and for a ``bit of
a lark'' they formed the now well-known Campaign for Real Ale, Camra, which
quickly attracted hundreds of like-minded beer drinkers. Four years later it
spread to Scotland.
The big boys of the trade were quick to respond to the changes in drinking
habits and rose to the challenge. Scottish and Newcastle, Britain's biggest
brewers, now produce around 30 cask ales which are sold in 70% of their
nationwide chain of 2720 pubs.
Their spokeswoman said: ``It is a buoyant market. The demand for cask ales is
certainly there and they do seem to go down well with the consumer.
``Camra have certainly played their part in bringing real ales to the attention
of the public who enjoy a good beer. We responded and now provide a great
variety of ales because it appears the public like to try different varieties.''
Hotelier Paul Waterson, president-elect of the Scottish Licensed Trade
Association, said: ``Real ales are a part of the market that is growing quite
considerably and seems to be catching on with the younger drinker. It is
helping to bring people back into the pubs.''
Camra's Scottish director, Colin Valentine, said: ``We feel every town should
have a small brewery and this is something we want to encourage.''
Camra now has eight branches in Scotland - Edinburgh, Dundee, Aberdeen,
Inverness, Paisley, Linlithgow, Ayrshire, and Glasgow - boasting a total
membership of 1500.
They regularly hold beer festivals and a recent three-day one in Aberdeen
attracted 2300 real-ale lovers who tested 65 different beers - 20 of them
brewed in Scotland - and between them managed to down 9184 pints.
</TEXT>
