<HEADLINE>Player ousted from bowls championship</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By GORDON DUNWOODIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061062</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE normally sedate world of bowls was rocked at the weekend after a competitor
in the National Fours Championship Playdowns was thrown out of the match after
allegedly verbally abusing an official.
Mr John McLardy, skip of the rink representing the Galleon Club in Kilmarnock,
was told not to turn up for yesterday morning's second round match with
Auchinleck after umpire Mr Roger Black had reported him to Scottish Indoor
Bowling Association officials in attendance at the Playdowns at Paisley.
The alleged incidents took place during the first round match between Galleon
and Newton Stewart which the Ayrshire side won 25-16.
Mr Black, who is also a qualified football referee and spent 20 years on the
official SFA's referee list, said: ``I spoke to the player on a couple of
occasions regarding his general conduct on the green and after the second
warning he launched a verbal attack on me within earshot of various officials
and other bowlers.
``I reported the matter to the SIBA officials' president and was later informed
the player had been disqualified from the event. I think it's an excellent
decision.''
SIBA competitions secretary Mr Dennis Petrie said: ``Following a violation of
the code of conduct during the National Fours Playdowns, Mr John McLardy of the
Galleon Club was disqualified from the competition. The club have been
permitted to field a substitute in place of Mr McLardy.
``We will be asking the Galleon Club at a later date what action they have
taken against the individual concerned and, if satisfied, I would anticipate
that would be an end to the matter,'' Mr Petrie said.
Mr McLardy was replaced by clubmate Mr Willie Mackie for yesterday's match
which they lost 22-7 to Auchinleck.
</TEXT>
