<DOCNO>GH951204-000071</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000071</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Canadian writer  dies after stroke</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Obituary</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061064</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ROBERTSON DAVIES, one of Canada's most accomplished authors, has died after
suffering a stroke. He was 82.
The author of more than 30 plays and novels, Davies followed a principle he
credited to Mozart, but which was based as well on his own life: take on the
most serious subjects and treat them in the most humorous way.
Also an actor and critic, he was mentioned as a possible winner of the 1993
Nobel Prize for Literature, which was eventually won by the American novelist
and essayist, Toni Morrison.
Davies died on Saturday night in a hospital in Orangeville, 50 miles north west
of Toronto.
His last novel, The Cunning Man, was a best seller this year.
His best known novels, The Lyre of Orpheus (1988), What's Bred in the Bone
(1985) and the three books that constitute the Deptford Trilogy of the 1970s
had a generous mix of greed and murder, adultery and blackmail, heartache and
insanity.
But Davies set a light-hearted, forgiving tone, as if he were a god looking on
with amusement at the humans down on earth.
His eclectic career included stints in academia, as the first head of Massey
College at Toronto University.
</TEXT>
