<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Scots hospital saves life of unborn baby from Iceland</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061065</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AN Icelandic woman has made four flights to Scotland in a battle to save her
unborn baby.
Berglind Hauksdottir's unborn child became seriously ill just six months into
pregnancy. Obstetric specialists in Reykjavik discovered that it was developing
severe anaemia because its blood group clashed with its mother's.
Its only hope of survival was highly-specialised foetal medical treatment in
Glasgow. The baby's condition was so poor that the specialists decided to fly
Mrs Hauksdottir to the foetal medicine department of the Queen Mother's
Hospital at Yorkhill, where consultant Dr Alan Cameron carried out delicate
blood transfusions to the baby guided by ultra-sound equipment.
``Our baby has improved tremendously,'' said Mrs Hauksdottir. ``When the
doctors in Reykjavik told us how seriously ill the baby was, we feared it
wouldn't survive.
``I only found out during an ante-natal visit and was told to pack my bags and
arrange for someone to take care of my older children because I was going on
the next flight to Glasgow.
``Within 24 hours we were stepping off an Icelandair flight and on our way to
the Queen Mother's Hospital. Now after four transfusions the baby is in great
shape and weighs between four and five pounds - good for 33 weeks into
pregnancy.''
Dr Cameron said Mrs Hauksdottir's baby had a condition called rhesus
incompatibility which occurs when a rhesus-negative blood group mother marries
a rhesus-positive father. If the baby inherits the father's blood type, the
mother can produce antibodies which destroys the foetus's red blood cells.
Without transfusion the baby can die and, if it is born alive, it can suffer
brain              damage.
``In Mrs Hauksdottir's case, we transfused 100mls of blood into the baby once a
fortnight to maintain a healthy red blood count, and we are delighted to say
that the baby is progressing well,'' said Dr Cameron.
``The transfusion is carried out by sedating the mum. The sedatives then pass
through the placenta to the foetus, making it less active during transfusion.
``It would be extremely difficult to transfuse a baby which was trying to run
away from you in the womb.''
Rhesus incompatibility is not a problem for most rhesus-negative mothers. First
babies are not affected and the mothers are almost always given a blood
preparation, anti-D, within 60 hours of their first birth.
However, Mrs Hauksdottir explained: ``I didn't get one when my son Haukur, 11,
was born and Theodor, 3, was anaemic when he was born.
``He recovered after a blood transfusion within hours of birth, and I thought
that the same would happen for this baby, but the problem gets worse with each
pregnancy.
``We owe our baby's life to the Queen Mother's team and to some unknown blood
donor here in Scotland.''
Mrs Hauksdottir's husband, Iolafur 30, has repaid that debt by becoming a blood
donor during his visits here. Holding up his donor's card he said: ``I have
given some of my blood to help save someone else's life. It's the least we
could do.
``It's our first trip to Scotland. We planned to visit some day but never
dreamed that it would be under these circumstances.''
Mrs Hauksdottir will make one final trip to Scotland and go back to Iceland to
have her baby by Caesarean section at 36 weeks.
According to the scans she        is expecting a baby girl. ``It's         a
change after two boys,''               she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
