<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Insular' attitudes will cost jobs Agency warns companies about the high price of ignoring business markets in Europe</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By IAIN WILSON Chief Reporter</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061066</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Enterprise officials based on the Continent have warned that business
attitudes at home must change or Scotland will lose out on jobs, exports and
inward investments.
Too many Scottish firms were not only insular but had a real fear of trading
with Europeans - widely regarded as the ``real foreigners'' because they do not
have English as their first language.
The potential for trade has never been better, said David Scrimgeour of Locate
in Scotland and Scottish Trade International's David Roe, both based in Germany.
But they are concerned Eastern Europe - awakening to the business opportunities
- will win the race for the massive capital sums now available for investment
on the Continent.
The next five to 10 years will be crucial if Scotland was not to be truly ``on
the periphery of Europe''.
Mr Scrimgeour, whose task is to secure more inward investment from Germany,
said he wanted a rethink on Scotland's ``unnatural dependance'' on doing
business with the US.
Mr Roe, who is charged with boosting Scotland's export performance, suspected
business was being lost because firms often sought markets in the
English-speaking world, especially America, rather than Europe.
He warned Scotland could become the ``Isle of Wight of Europe'' unless
attitudes changed, and said of the need to look to Europe as a trading partner:
``Our market is not the English-speaking world, it's continental Europe. It
amazes me still that companies feel that the English-speaking world, has to be
the opportunity for them when they can get to Germany in a couple of hours.''
Europeans were keen to do business with Scotland, he said, but too many
Scottish firms saw themselves as companies exporting to Europe rather than
European firms based in Scotland.
Mr Roe said Scottish firms were particularly poor at marketing - tenders for
work were almost always in English, with prices very rarely quoted in
Deutschmarks. Yet businesscould soar tenfold in Germany if Scotland was
promoted properly, he said.
He supported Mr Scrimgeour's call for a long-term strategy which would
concentrate on trade in European markets with huge potential.
Scotland was ``just playing at it'' and Scottish Enterprise needed to look at
what the Germans wanted - then beat off the competition by meeting their
demands.
They want Scotland to press home advantages before Eastern Germany, in
particular, developed the managerial and technological standards required by
its western counterparts.
Their comments are contained in the agency's Enterprise Scotland magazine, to
be distributed to 10,000 Scottish businessmen, politicians, and others later
this week. Mr Scrimgeour said Germany, the second largest exporter in the
world, was ready and willing to invest in the UK, but faced difficulties. These
included Scots being ``too centred in Scotland . . . we think that people know
more about Scotland than they do''.
However, market research showed Scotland was known more as a holiday
destination that as a business location.
Mr Scrimgeour said Scotland might have an unnatural dependence on the US, with
nothing done in Europe for years because it was content with American trade.
He said Scotland had to grasp the opportunities now because ``a window of
opportunity is going  to close in five to 10 years time''.
Although Scotland at least had a presence in Germany, unlike the rest of the UK
which relied on part-time consultants, Mr Scrimgeour wants more people on the
ground to ensure the advantage was maintained.
He said: ``If we can get a decent number of Germany companies into Scotland,
and get Germans to use Scottish suppliers, then we will have a base in five
years' time to cushion us against the inevitable outcome of the way the
European economy is developing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000074</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000074</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Charity attacks sports shoe firms</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061067</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A LEADING British charity has criticised top-brand sports shoe companies for
the way they treat workers in factories in the Far East.
Christian Aid says that while the firms spend millions of pounds endorsing
sports stars, they are short-changing the people who make the products.
In a 28-page document, released today, the charity highlights the poor
treatment suffered by workers making shoes for the five UK market leaders -
Nike, Reebok, Puma, Hi-Tec, and Adidas - and urges them to increase wages and
improve factory conditions.
Adidas recently paid Rangers star Paul Gascoigne #2m to wear its boots and
tennis star Andre Agassi has signed a clothing contract with Nike worth #70m.
Liverpool Football Club is understood to have lined up a #25m deal with Reebok.
That sum, claims the report, would more than double the wages of the 40,000
workers in China and the Philippines who make the company's trainers.
The report, The Globe-Trotting Sports Shoe, has been written by Bethan Brookes
and Peter Madden who say: ``A typical pair of trainers sells for #50 in
Britain. But the 40 or so factory workers in the Philippines who make them will
share just over #1 of that price between them. Billions are spent instead on
marketing and product endorsement.''
The leading sports shoe companies contract out the production of the vast
majority of their shoes to manufacturers in the Third World, particularly Asia.
Shoe manufacturing generates valuable jobs and money for these countries, but
wages and working conditions often leave a lot to be desired, says the report.
Among the abuses highlighted are enforced overtime, health and safety
deficiencies, discrimination against trade unions and the use of hire-and-fire
policies to avoid paying fringe benefits.
Christian Aid is asking supporters to write to the five companies urging them
to increase wages and implement a code of practice.
Mr Madden said: ``As a result we might see one advertisement fewer a week or a
top sports personality given a few thousand pounds less. Is this such a big
price to pay?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000075</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000075</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Steamer sets return course</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061068</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Maid of the Loch will today set course for its sailing return to Loch
Lomond.
Dumbarton civic leaders will hand over ownership of the 42-year-old paddle
steamer to the trust set up to restore the steamer - three years to the day
that the district council saved her from the wrecker's yard.
Bad habit
THE Vatican has cracked down on priests who have got into the habit of not
wearing their clerical garb. But according to the Scottish Catholic Observer,
it is a rule which will be strongly resisted by many priests who enjoy wearing
civvies.
Crash shock
A COUPLE caught in a traffic jam found it had been caused by a head-on
collision involving their own daughter, who is fighting for her life in
hospital. The 25-year-old woman - who has not been named - had driven ahead of
her parents as they travelled to their Huntingdon, Cambridgeshire, home after a
day out.
Woman killed
A 75-year-old woman died in hospital yesterday after an accident involving a
police van which was answering an emergency call. The woman pedestrian, who has
not been identified, received multiple injuries in the incident on Saturday in
Guildford, Surrey.
Policeman dies
AN off-duty policeman died in a stabbing attack early yesterday in Killyleagh,
County Down, during a row at a house. A man was later arrested and questioned
in connection with the death of the 36-year-old RUC officer.
Murder charge
A 51-year-old man has been charged with murdering his wife after her body was
found at their home. Jack Smith, of Grosvenor Road, Wisbech, Cambridgeshire,
will appear at Peterborough magistrates court today.
Death probe
A MURDER inquiry was launched yesterday after the bodies of a man and a woman
were found in a smoke-filled house in the village of Carleton, North Yorkshire.
Neighbours named the woman as 41-year-old Pauline Akrigg.
Man accused
A 23-year-old man was yesterday charged with a pensioner's murder. Maurice
Hoyle, 69, was found dead at his home in Barnsley, south Yorkshire, on
Thursday. A 19-year-old man and a woman in her early 20s are still being
questioned about Mr Hoyle's death.
Snow warning
A BITTERLY cold weather front from Siberia will sweep across Britain this week
bringing sleet and snow, forecasters said yesterday. In sharp contrast, autumn
1995 was the mildest this century and the fifth warmest since records began
more than three hundred years ago.
Money-spinner
A COUPLE who run a filling station at Tomatin, Inverness-shire, near the A9
have come up with a bizarre way of raising cash for charity. Alistar and Jean
MacRae have amassed a mountain of wheel-trims which have fallen off vehicles on
the busy Perth-to-Inverness road. They sell them at #2 each, and all the
proceeds go the Highland Hospice in Inverness.
Take the Lot
TEEN heart-throbs Take That swept the board at the Smash Hits Poll Winners
Party yesterday. They took eight top awards.
Four in court
THREE men and a woman have appeared before a special sitting of Berwick
Magistrates Court charged with supplying drugs. Paul Townsley, 37, of St
Georges Road, was remanded in custody for six days, while Shirley Pontin, 39,
also of St Georges Road, Cecil Bloomfield, 35, of St Aidans Road, and Neil
Pattinson, 28, of The Oval, all Berwick, were released on bail.
</TEXT>
