<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unions  set to  bring pay rows to a head</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By ROY ROGERS Industrial Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061069</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
IN a key week for pay bargaining, Vauxhall unions will seek to improve on a
3.5% offer against a background of sanctions due to begin on Wednesday, and
leaders of more than a million local authority workers open negotiations on a
``substantial'' wage demand, including the introduction of a minimum wage of
#4.15 an hour.
Ford's 22,000 manual workers are currently being consulted on their ``final''
offer of a two-year package worth at least 9.25%, and, depending on the outcome
of these soundings, may yet be balloted on industrial action.
Workers at the Dagenham plant in Essex have come down against the offer while
their colleagues at Halewood on Merseyside and Bridgend in South Wales are
thought to favour acceptance.
Vauxhall's 9000 employees will be expecting their offer - of 3.5% this year and
the rate of inflation next year - to be improved to something nearer the Ford
formula of 4.75% this year and 4.5% or the rate of inflation, whichever is the
greater, next.
Neither of the two US-owned car giants is prepared to concede a union demand
for a two-hour reduction in the 39-hour working week, and both are gambling
that their UK employees will not resort to strike action even though their
German counterparts get more money for a 35-hour week.
With the Government recently confirming new spending limits which will leave
councils #3000m short of requirements, it is the local authority claim, which
it is estimated would add some 6% to the #9000m pay bill, that poses the
greatest problems for councils, the Government and the Opposition.
If met, it would put some 500,000 mainly part-time women workers on a new rate
of at least #4.15 an hour and cost some #630m, which employers say could equate
to the loss of 43,000. It would also mean a rise of 6.9% for white-collar
workers.
Mr Keith Sonnet, Unison's head of local government, said: ``We are a rich
country and it is a disgrace that we have nearly half a million local
government workers earning less than #4.15 an hour.
``Our members are sick and tired of having their pay and jobs cut and we will
campaign to make sure they get a proper settlement next year.'' Potential
embarrassment for Labour comes from the fact that, although it is committed to
the introduction of a national minimum wage, when in power it has shied away
from figures and studiously refused to support #4.15 an hour, which would lift
the pay of some low-paid workers by #17 a week.
</TEXT>
