<HEADLINE>Universities losing out on software</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061070</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTLAND's universities are too parochial and fail to exploit breakthroughs in
computer software, says the Scottish Software Federation.
The federation is to publish a national strategy to develop Scotland's software
industry later this month by the Scottish Software Federation.
Federation director Tom McCallum said that while Scottish universities produced
one of the highest percentages of computer graduates in the world, talent was
being lost abroad. The universities may have to pool their resources, in the
form of a central technology park for software companies, to make the most of
technological advances, he said.
Meanwhile, representatives of 10 software and specialist companies from the US
arrived in Scotland on the weekend to seek out trade partnerships.
It is the first software inward mission of its kind, and is expected to
generate more than #1m worth of business.
Scottish Enterprise, organisers of the trip, see it as a two-way operation.
Although the majority of the American companies are seeking partners to market
and support their products and services in Europe, some of the companies will
also be keen to find Scottish products for the US market.
The companies include PSI International, which has developed software to help
Government agencies build up databases for contraband detection, and
Interamerica Technologies, which is keen to market child-care management
software for education and social work departments.
</TEXT>
