<HEADLINE>Labour activists told of election targets</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>FRANCES HORSBURGH, Local Government Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061071</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LABOUR Party activists in Scotland were urged yesterday to make an
unprecedented effort to increase party support by winning six key seats at the
next General Election.
Addressing a party conference on local government in Dundee, assistant general
secretary Tommy Sheppard named them as Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, whose
boundaries have been completely redrawn, Ayr, Dumfries and Stirling, held by
the Tories, and Inverness, held by the Scottish Liberal Democrats.
Asked by one delegate why Edinburgh Pentlands, the seat of Tory Foreign
Secretary Malcolm Rifkind, was not on the list, Mr Sheppard said Labour
believed it would win the priority six seats before getting to Pentlands, but
they could well get to Pentlands and beyond.
A 6% swing would be needed to win Dumfries, where Sir Hector Monro was
retiring, said Mr Sheppard. In Inverness he believed the contest would boil
down to a fight between Labour and the SNP.
The six Scottish seats are part of a list of 70 drawn up by Labour Party
organisers throughout Britain.
Mr Sheppard said the party planned to make contact with 80% of the electorate
in the six key seats over the next 12 months.
With two official inquiries being held into the alleged behaviour of Labour
councillors, first in Monklands and soon in new North Lanarkshire, Tory
Ministers have also launched a series of recent attacks on Labour claiming a
``jobs for the boys'' approach by some councils over senior appointments.
They have also alleged too many highly-paid officials were being appointed, and
committees structures were being expanded to allow widespread payment of
responsibility allowances.
Mr Sheppard warned Labour councillors that the run-up to the General Election
would not be a good time to become involved in any ``new controversial
initiatives'' which might incur bad publicity.
Labour controlled 21 out of the 29 new mainland councils and it must try to
avoid any bad stories appearing about Labour-run local authorities.
Speaking on Saturday, Convention of Scottish Local Authorities' president
Rosemary McKenna told the conference that Government Ministers had been telling
lies about the structures of the new authorities.
Despite Scottish Secretary Michael Forsyth's claims that he was giving powers
back to local government, she said, he had no intention of returning control of
water services to local government.
Rounding up the conference yesterday, new Labour Chief Whip Donald Dewar
described the Scottish Secretary as a Minister who was ``out of touch, out of
time and out of line'' and prepared to do damage to the good government of
Scotland for party advantage.
The Scottish Secretary's ``devolution'' plans with regard to the Scottish Grand
Committee were ``a confidence trick and sleight of hand'', added Mr Dewar.
</TEXT>
