<HEADLINE>Another death at Cornton Vale prison</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By RON MacKENNA</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061072</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A 26-YEAR-old woman was found dead in her cell at Cornton Vale prison, Stirling
last night, the third such death at Scotland's only female prison this year.
It is believed that Joanne O'Reilly, from Nitshill in Glasgow, hanged herself.
In a short statement the Scottish Prison Service said the untried prisoner was
found shortly after 8pm in Romeo Block by staff. She had been on remand at the
prison since November 30.
This latest discovery will fuel calls for reform to the way vulnerable, untried
prisoners are dealt with by the system.
A fatal accident inquiry is already under way into the deaths of Arlene Elliot
and Kelly Holland, both 17, in separate incidents at the prison earlier this
year.
The Scottish system was heavily criticised by the Howard League for Penal
Reform, earlier this year, for remanding teenage girls. Such decisions were
described as ``archaic''.
However, the regime at Cornton Vale, which is also a young offenders'
institution, is regarded as relatively relaxed. It holds 168 people, and the
death of Joanne O'Reilly brings the total to three deaths in ten years.
A spokesman for the Scottish Prison Service said: ``The police and next of kin
have been informed and a fatal accident inquiry will be held in due course.
Until then we cannot comment further.'' He said he was unable to disclose why
she had been remanded.
Cornton Vale was criticised in June by Mr Clive Fairweather, chief inspector
with the Prisons Inspectorate for Scotland. Following a three-day inspection,
he said: ``The regime needs to be improved. Staff are carrying out their
statutory duties and little else.''
</TEXT>
