<HEADLINE>Doctors back bid to cut limit</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By CRAIG WATSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061073</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE British Medical Association has called for the drink-driving limit to be
almost halved, echoing similar demands from Scottish police last week.
The BMA has written to Transport Secretary Sir George Young calling for the
reduction of the alcohol limit from 80 milligrammes per 100 millilitres of
blood to 50 milligrammes and the introduction of random breath-testing.
The BMA in Scotland said the long-term aim was to ban drinking and driving
completely.
Last week, Mr William Spence, traffic chairman of the Association of Police
Officers in Scotland and Chief Constable of Tayside Police marked the launch of
the 10th annual festive season campaign with a call to reduce the level to 50
milligrammes.
This would bring Britain in line with other European countries and greatly
reduce the risk of accidents, the BMA said.
The request was made jointly with the Parliamentary Advisory Council for
Transport Safety (Pacts), a cross-party road safety pressure group.
In their letter, the BMA and Pacts say: ``Research evidence indicates that the
relative risk of driver involvement in road traffic accidents is increased
significantly at a blood alcohol level of 50mg/100ml.''
The letter argues that tougher enforcement, including random breath-testing,
would be needed if a lower drink limit was to be effective.
BMA Scottish secretary Dr Brian Potter said that, ideally, drivers should not
be allowed to drink at all. But he added that such a move had to be phased in
gradually.
Campaigners have stressed that alcohol limits vary from person to person. But
the proposed reduction would be amount to approximately one pint of ordinary
lager, two glasses of wine or a double whisky for a man of average weight and
build.
Scottish Roads and Transport Minister Lord James Douglas-Hamilton has said that
drink-driving legislation is under review but there are no current plans to
change the legal limit.
The Government is due to launch a #1m Christmas anti-drink drive campaign this
week targeted at young people.
The terrible effect of alcohol-related accidents, not just on young drivers,
but also on their friends, is the main theme of the campaign.
A powerful TV commercial will show that although a young drink-driver may not
be too concerned what happens to him, he does become upset about the effects on
his friends.
The commercial will be shown for the first time tomorrow.
Meanwhile, a survey out today shows that more than half of motorists do not
know how much alcohol they can drink before they pass the legal drink-drive
limit.
Drivers' responses were so muddled that it would be safer if they left the car
at home when drinking, the survey organisers said.
The survey, by insurers Eagle Star, showed that:
q.Almost six out of 10 drivers (57%) did not know the legal drink-drive limit.
q.Nearly 66% wrongly believed that a pint of lager and a single brandy
contained the same amount of alcohol (the lager has twice as much alcohol).
q.One in 10 motorists wrongly believed a woman could drink three glasses of
wine and stay under the limit.
</TEXT>
