<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The seven-year warning  Forsyth fears fast track to home rule</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>By KEN SMITH</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061074</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISH Secretary Michael Forsyth has admitted Scotland could be independent
in seven years' time.
His remarks were an attempt to warn of the dangers, as he saw them, of Labour's
devolution plans, but were seized upon by the Scottish National Party which
said it showed even opponents were accepting independence was a real
possibility in the near future.
In effect, Mr Forsyth was saying that if Labour won the next election and
introduced a Scottish Parliament, it could lead to a majority of Scots voting
for independence at the following General Election, which could be in 2002.
Questioned by interviewer Alastair Stewart on GMTV's The Sunday Programme, Mr
Forsyth blamed what he called Labour's grossly irresponsible devolution plans
for what could be the probable break-up of the United Kingdom.
He said: ``At the moment our battle is to prevent Labour creating a change
which may be irreversible and which, in my view, would actually lead to the
break-up of the UK. It may be that by 2002 we'll be looking at an independent
Scotland.''
He added: ``Two years ago I would never have thought that possible. But such
has been the gross irresponsibility of Labour over these proposals that they
are creating a situation where we could sleepwalk into separatism.''
Conservative politicians have said in the past that devolution could ultimately
lead to full independence. However, this is the first time that anyone as
senior as a Cabinet Minister has suggested it could happen so quickly.
Mr Forsyth also candidly accepted that if Labour won the election, and
established a Scottish Parliament, the Tories would nevertheless not boycott it
and would field candidates. Although this is to be expected, it is not normal
for a senior politician to discuss what would happen if his or her party lost
the next election.
His openness was quickly exploited by SNP leader Alex Salmond, who pointed out:
``Michael Forsyth and John Major claim that if there is devolution,
independence will follow in double-quick time. George Robertson and Tony Blair
say that if there is no devolution, independence will follow.
``It seems that even our political opponents are agreed about Scotland's
destination, and the political argument is merely about the route by which we
get there.''
Mr Forsyth's strategy is to convince voters that Labour's proposals are far
more dangerous to the future of the UK than people realise. If successful, it
could just convince wavering Tory supporters to stick with the party.
Shadow Scottish Secretary George Robertson was quick to attack Mr Forsyth's
claims. ``It's an insult to the intelligence of the Scottish people to assume
that just by creating a Scottish Parliament that will make them want
independence more,'' he said.
Labour, however, will be unhappy at the Secretary of State making such an issue
of independence. It had hoped to marginalise the SNP by making the next
election as far as possible a straight fight between the Government and Labour.
Mr Forsyth's remarks will ensure that the independence issue will continue to
be a major election issue in Scotland.
</TEXT>
