<DOCNO>GH951204-000082</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000082</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Unions to defy Juppe's plans</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>NICHOLAS POWELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061075</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Paris
FRANCE'S week-long public sector strike against government plans to reform the
welfare system looks set to spread.
The leaders of two major unions have called on their members in the private
sector to stop work.
Mr Marc Blondel, leader of Force Ouvriere, appealed to private sector workers
to demand the repeal of Prime Minister Alain Juppe's schemes.
``I am now going to ask all sectors to progressively join in the strike, with
one single goal: the withdrawal of the Juppe plan,'' Mr Blondel said.
He was supported yesterday by Mr Louis Viannet of the Communist sympathising
CGT.
Despite these warnings, President Jacques Chirac yesterday reaffirmed support
for the reforms.
``It is this path, the path of reforms too long delayed, that I have chosen,''
Mr Chirac said, breaking his silence on the issue during a summit of
French-speaking nations in Benin, in Africa.
The government wants to raise taxes, control health spending, reform
universities and tighten retirement packages for public employees to cut state
deficits enough for France to qualify for a single European currency from 1999.
Workers fear the cuts will trim their health or retirement benefits and lead to
state layoffs.
Members of the RPR Gaullist party were hard at work yesterday setting up
``users' committees'' to protest against the strikes and organise a counter
demonstration on the Champs Elysees in Paris on Thursday.
Mr Juppe called an emergency meeting of members of his government whose
ministries are directly concerned by the strike. A statement afterwards gave no
indication that he was prepared to give an inch.
Representatives of students, who have been on strike for a month throughout the
country to protest at under-funding and too few teachers, finally had a
two-hour meeting with Education Minister Francois Bayrou.
After refusing to shake the Minister's hand, the students, from Trotskyist and
socialist organisations, proposed a #7000m plan spread over the next five
years. Mr Bayrou offered a #400m emergency fund, and the recruitment of 4000
teachers and employees. The students rejected the move.
The economic cost of the strike, meanwhile, is beginning to bite.
Numerous small firms, especially in the Paris region, deprived of deliveries
and of their staff, are complaining of huge and crippling losses.
France's train system, at a
standstill for eight days, is suffering daily losses of more than #12m.
Many of the 8,000,000 living in the Paris region, hit by a complete stoppage of
suburban trains, metros and buses, are failing to turn up for work or working
fewer hours.
The streets of Paris have been turned into a permanent traffic jam, and
stoppages on roads leading into the capital take several hours to clear during
morning and evening rush hours.
Travel agents said the tourist industry had lost #200m over the past week.
Inland Revenue employees are due to stop work tomorrow while gas and
electricity board workers are to continue their strike action. Strikes were
also rumoured in hospitals.
Primary school teachers and workers at both Air France and Air Inter, the
domestic French airline, will stop work on Thursday.
Private coach companies have already scheduled hundreds of supplementary daily
trips between Paris and major French towns. Yesterday, the company running the
bateaux mouche, the tourist cruise boats on the Seine, announced they were
planning a regular ferry service, free of charge, up and down the river.
Many Paris hotels have announced cut-price accommodation for people living out
of town who are finding it impossible to commute to work.
Around 3000 people demonstrated in the centre of Paris on Saturday against the
strikes, demanding the government introduce a minimum service on public
transport.
Despite efforts by the RPR Gaullist party to stir up demonstrations against the
transport stoppages, a poll published over the weekend showed that more than
60% of French people sympathise with the strikers and their aims.
</TEXT>
