<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>`Mad cow' cuts under fire</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061076</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Prime Minister was called on yesterday to intervene and reverse possible
job cuts at a Scottish research unit where scientists are looking for links
between ``mad cow'' disease and its equivalent form in humans.
Shadow Agriculture Minister Dr Gavin Strang described threatened redundancies
at the Neuro-Pathogenesis Unit in Edinburgh as a result of Government grant
reductions as a national scandal.
His call came on the same day as Health Secretary Stephen Dorrell insisted that
there was ``no conceivable risk'' of people becoming infected with
Creutzfeldt-Jakob Disease (CJD) from eating beef.
Dr Strang has written to Mr Major, expressing shock that cuts could be made
when there was increasing concern over Bovine Spongiform Encephalitis (BSE).
He said the scientists in Edinburgh were told two weeks ago of the decision by
the Government-backed Institute for Animal Health, of which the unit is a part,
that they had until December 21 to find enough volunteers for redundancy or
face compulsory job cuts.
The institute is axing between 50 and 70 posts - about 10% of the workforce -
at its laboratories in Edinburgh, Surrey and Berkshire.
The NPU in Scotland is involved in developing detailed tests to identify the
agent that causes BSE in cattle and its human equivalent, CJD. There has been
growing concern about a possible link.
Institute director Professor John Bourne said that in the past he had protected
the BSE programme from the effects of cuts, but in the face of a further
#500,000 grant cut by the Ministry of Agriculture that might no longer be
possible.
Last week, leading brain surgeon Professor Sir Bernard Tomlinson called for a
ban on sales of beef offal because of concerns, and revealed he had given up
beefburgers and meat pies.
Mr Dorrell told LWT's Dimbleby programme that the scientific evidence suggested
that BSE could not be transmitted through the food chain.
Under new Government regulations brought in last week, the only organs that
could possibly be linked with the disease, the brain and the spinal cord, had
now been banned from shops.
Unlike Sir Bernard, Mr Dorrell said that he was still prepared to eat
hamburgers and to give them to his own children. The Government's Chief Medical
Officer would do the same, he said.
A Ministry of Agriculture spokeswoman said that overall Government funding for
research into BSE was set to rise by #1m next year to #6.4m.
</TEXT>
