<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Back-bench discontent gathers force as Budget proves a flop in winning back voters Ministers admit to tax dilemma</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER, Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061077</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TWO Cabinet Ministers have conceded that the Conservatives may not be able to
bring taxes back down to 1992 levels before the next election.
Party chairman Brian Mawhinney admitted this in an interview on BBC-TV's On The
Record, but said he believed the Tories could still be re-elected. The British
people realised, he said, that Conservatives were ``instinctive'' tax-cutters
and Labour were not.
Chancellor Kenneth Clarke put himself on a collision course with right-wing
Tory MPs when he indicated that tax cuts in his next Budget - the last before a
General Election - might not be bigger than those in last week's.
He said: ``We won't win the next election if we are perceived to be bribing the
electorate. We will win the election if we are seen to be running the economy
competently.''
Mr Clarke also risked right-wing wrath by describing those who wanted major
cutbacks in welfare spending to be ``living in cloud cuckooland''.
Dr Mawhinney insisted that a family on average earnings would be #9 a week
better off next year because of the combination of Budget tax cuts and higher
pay.
Labour's deputy leader John Prescott said that that assumed 4% pay rises, above
the expected inflation rate, something the Government had discouraged in the
public sector.
Mr Michael Heseltine strongly defended the Chancellor against criticism among
some Tory MPs that the Budget had proved a flop in winning back voters for the
Conservatives.
The Deputy Prime Minister said of Mr Clarke: ``He is a rock of a Chancellor and
he knows exactly what he's doing.'' The Budget, he said, would be better
received by voters as they began to feel the benefits of its provisions.
But some Tory MPs, after testing opinion in their constituencies, have begun
voicing their discontent.
They received support from an NOP poll for the Sunday Times taken after the
Budget statement showing that Labour had actually increased its lead by four
points since the previous survey.
Even more woundingly for the Chancellor, the percentage of people who say they
trust the Tories on taxation has fallen 3% since a fortnight before, and now
stands at 26%.
Mr David Evans, MP for Welwyn and Hatfield and a member of the executive of the
1922 Committee of Tory back benchers, said: ``Ken Clarke has no nose for
politics. He may be robust but when it comes to knowing what people want he is
lacking.
``The trouble is that if you try to please everyone you end up pleasing
nobody.''
Sir Rhodes Boyson, MP for Brent North, another member of the 1922 executive,
said: ``I am disappointed that there haven't been bigger cuts in public
spending which would allow a greater reduction in both direct and indirect
taxation.''
The Chancellor may be forced to make a concession during Commons discussion of
the Finance Bill, implementing the Budget, by allowing the new threshold of
#200,000 for the payment of death duties to apply at once instead of next April.
Several Tory MPs are urging this. Mr Tom Smith (Beconsfield), said: ``When
people hear a Budget announcement of this kind they naturally assume that it
will take effect immediately.
``It is then very upsetting to discover that this is not the case and that
one's liability for inheritance tax will depend on the date of one's death.''
A Cabinet battle is looming on the future of child benefit, which the
Government has been obliged by its 1992 election manifesto commitment to keep.
Some Ministers, like Social Security Secretary Peter Lilley, favour abolishing
it and giving parents more generous tax allowances.
In contrast to these expected strains, Mr Heseltine lavished praise on the
Prime Minister who, he said, had been ``extremely generous to me''. He added:
``He might not be the most flamboyant this country has had but he will prove to
be one of the most successful.''
Inside Politics - Page 13
</TEXT>
