<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Award marks out prison as a standard bearer</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>RAYMOND DUNCAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061078</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SCOTTISH prison, which up until four years ago housed the infamous ``Cages''
holding some of the country's most notorious and dangerous criminals, is to
receive a UK-wide award for facility improvements and high staff standards.
HM Prison Porterfield, Inverness, is one of 20 Scots winners of so-called
``Oscars of public service''.
A record 223 such services will be presented by the Prime Minister with the
1995 Charter Mark at a ceremony in London today.
Built in 1902, Porterfield was designed to hold 79 prisoners but recent
alterations have increased capacity to 107.
Refurbishment of the segregation unit known as the ``Cages'', mothballed since
1991, has created accommodation and activities areas for up to 12 vulnerable
prisoners.
Other measures including conversion of the slopping-out area has helped ease
overcrowding. Among other winners is Glasgow's Anniesland College which becomes
the first further education college in Strathclyde to gain the award. It is
recognised for its delivery of services to customers, especially its students.
Motherwell District Council Housing gains recognition, as does the national
housing agency, Scottish Homes.
The National Museums of Scotland becomes the first museums group in Scotland to
receive the Charter Mark, while, in the medical field, recipients are the Royal
Infirmary of Edinburgh NHS Trust, Dunfermline's Queen Margaret Hospital, and
the Victoria Infirmary NHS Trust Cardiac Rehabilitation Centre.
Central Scotland Police wins an award and the Scottish Police College at
Tulliallan, the national centre for police Training in Scotland, is another
recipent.
Annandale and Eskdale District Council Parks Section and West Lothian District
Council Pest Control Service also gain the Mark.
Three Benefits Agency Districts - East Lowlands, Fife and Highlands and Islands
- win the award as do Dunbartonshire Enterprise.
The ceremony took place at the Queen Elizabeth 11 Centre in Westminster.
Three London councils dubbed ``loony left'' by the Tories - Haringey, Islington
and Southwark - also win awards.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000086</DOCNO>
