<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Dirty tricks taint French  bid to retain Euro assembly</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MURRAY RITCHIE, European Editor</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061079</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Brussels
THE EU's auditors have concluded that ``illegal and irregular'' methods were
used in the successful French dirty-tricks campaign to keep Strasbourg as the
permanent home of the European Parliament at a cost of millions of pounds.
Their report - circulated privately to Euro-MPs last week - condemns the
decision by Mr Egon Klepsch, former president of the parliament, to sign a
contract last year which allowed work to start while the assembly's independent
financial controller was strongly advising against the move.
Work is now advanced on the building which will replace the existing assembly
at what the report says is a ``provisional'' cost to the European taxpayer of
#354m.
This is despite strong hostility from most non-French Euro-MPs who grumble at
having to travel every month to Strasbourg.
Last night, Mr David Martin, Labour Euro-MP for Lothians, condemned the methods
used by the French to force through the decision. Mr Martin, a vice-president
of the parliament, was one of two British Euro-MPs in the executive bureau of
the assembly to vote against. The other was Tory Sir Jack Stewart-Clark.
Mr Martin said: ``It seems now that very little can be done. The whole thing is
a disgrace, all brought on by pressure from the French government. The European
Parliament bureau gave approval to this project in a way which no commercial
company would have touched.''
Work is also nearing completion on another #800m parliamentary complex in
Brussels to replace its existing offices. The parliament also has seldom-used
buildings in Luxembourg. The French have fought a long and bitter battle to
keep the assembly in Strasbourg despite claims by British Euro-MPs that the
extra cost to the European taxpayer is as much as #50m a year.
The site, close to the Rhine, was chosen as a symbol of post-war reconciliation
by the EU. But most Euro-MPs resent having to travel there monthly from all
over Europe on flights which are often late and indirect and where hotel rooms
are scarce and expensive.
In a deft piece of negotiation at the Edinburgh summit in 1992, former
president Francois Mitterrand managed to get the Strasbourg deal past John
Major when the prime minister was chairing a session struggling to reach an
accord on other issues.
The auditors' report is a draft submitted to the parliament for its response.
The auditors said they wanted to know why a long lease was signed on March 31
last year without the approval of the parliament's financial controller, Mr
Eoghan O'Hannrachain.
The auditors note that three days before the contract was signed by Mr Klepsch,
the financial controller had ``concluded explicitly that in the absence of
substantial modifications the draft contract should not be signed in its
current form.''
The auditors also expressed ``serious reservations'' at the price agreed for
the land (#17m) which they said they held to be too high.
The 26-page draft concludes that the rules governing the contract and the
principles of sound financial management ``were not observed, in particular as
regards the sound functioning of internal control''.
It concludes: ``Because it has signed the contract, the parliament is bound to
make out the future payments related to the construction of the Strasbourg
hemicycle. This does not mean that, at an internal level, the parliament should
not be required to remedy the situations of illegality and irregularity that
have been found in respect of the signing of the contract in question.''
</TEXT>
