<HEADLINE>Loyalists reject Trimble plea</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STUART TROTTER Political Correspondent</BYLINE>
<EDITION>3</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061080</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LOYALIST paramilitaries in Northern Ireland yesterday rejected a call from
Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble to make the first move in giving up arms.
Mr Trimble said it ``would deprive the IRA of any possible scintilla of
objection to handing over their own weapons'', but both the UVF and UFF
organisations made clear that they would not move until the IRA did.
Mr Trimble, who is to have talks today with SDLP leader John Hume, said he had
hoped to encourage loyalists to begin a decommissioning process early next year
before US Senator George Mitchell's international arms commission finished a
report on illegal guns which is part of the Government's twin-track approach on
Northern Ireland.
Democratic Unionist councillor Gary McMichael said: ``There is no question of
any sort of physical gesture ahead of the IRA while the Provos remain
operational and at full capacity.''
British Government spokesmen also rejected suggestions that Ministers were
ready to allow all-party talks to start on an understanding that paramilitary
weapons would be handed in on a phased basis as the talks continued.
A Northern Ireland Office spokeswoman said the Prime Minister had made clear
that the process of decommissioning illegally-held arms must have started
before substantive political negotiations could begin.
Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said the IRA would co-operate with the peace
process, but Mr Major knew that they would not give up weapons until there was
a political settlement.
The province's political leaders are now studying the formal invitation they
have had from the Government to take part in preparatory talks paving the way
for all-party negotiations on the future of Northern Ireland.
These need not and will not involve all the parties talking together. Their
representatives can hold discussions separately with the British and Irish
governments if they wish.
British Government sources were stressing that, although labelled preparatory,
the talks were highly important for creating an agreed basis on which
negotiations could begin.
Mr Trimble said again at the weekend that decommissioning would have to start
before his party would consider sitting down with Sinn Fein.
The two governments could also be moving towards approving a decision by London
to call elections for a Northern Ireland assembly, after which the elected
representatives could put the views of their parties at round table
constitutional talks.
The idea is backed by Labour. Shadow Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said
it could provide an ``election passport'' into the talks. British Ministers
might also welcome an election likely to show Sinn Fein's popular support in
the Province to be around the 15% mark putting their spokesmen's claims in
perspective.
The Prime Minister is likely to be asked about the next step forward in the
peace process when he answers questions in the Commons tomorrow.
Mr Adams said yesterday that a new phase of the peace process had started
following the Downing Street agreement and President Clinton's visit.
He added: ``How far that will take us remains to be seen. We will be
proactively seeking to make it work. The test of any twin-track process is its
ability to remove all preconditions. Unless they are removed, it's useless.''
Mr Adams said that he wanted all guns, including those held by police and
troops, removed.
``Not as a precondition, but as a necessary objective. We want to see
demilitarisation.''
But Sinn Fein chairman Mitchel McLaughlin said that, when it came to
decommissioning, there had to be ``different formulations'' for dealing with
paramilitary weapons and the legally-held arms of the security forces.
``Sinn Fein never expected that the British Army would march up to the Falls
Road park, stash their weapons and we'd have a huge bonfire - any more than we
expected that was how we would deal with the IRA weapons,'' he said.
</TEXT>
