<HEADLINE>Glaur and glamour of the Scottish Amateur Cup</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JACK McLEAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061081</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was a time, really, when amateur football counted quite a lot. You used
to get stamps from Romania and the Georgian Republic with football players
because Eastern Europe had nothing but amateur teams. The great Hungarian side
which thrashed England consisted of amateur players, and I don't think.
For many years amateur footy players were close to professionals. After all,
there wasn't much difference in the pay. Twenty quid was the limit for pros:
Stanley Matthews played until he was more than 50 and earned sod-all except a
knighthood. The last professional team in the world which continues to be
amateur, and non-paying, is a team I indeed played for, many, many, years ago,
Queen's Park. To this day it pays sod-all.
Amateur football is a bit of a contradiction. Every footy player who plays for
nothing wants to play for a lot of it. Junior football has lots of players who
are quite good but who want to be a lot better and get paid handsomely for
thumping opponents. The referee does not get paid at all, save expenses. Thus
we had in Stirling on Saturday the sight of amateur teams Cambusbarron Rovers
and St Ninians Thistle wrestling with each other in the drizzle, glaur, mud,
and glamour of a second-round tie in the Scottish Amateur Cup.
Cambusbarron have won copiously for the last three years. St Ninians, promoted
by local publican George Wilson of the Borestone Bar, not a kick in the arse
aff Bannockburn, have won little other than support from the locals.
The locals included David Reynolds, a worthy player last year who broke a leg
and can give you as good a reason why amateur footy costs in a way that
professional athleticism does not. There was no insurance for David. There is
no insurance for anybody involved in serious commitment to real sport.
Norrie Lean, a seasoned supporter and former manager of St Ninians, is an
ex-miner, from Fallin Pit, a big lad, now out of work, like many others in
industrial Scotland. But yet he was there at the football.
There are still supporters of football and communities. Jim McGurk, a lorry
driver, he's there, supporting amateur football: I don't know why. Amateur has
reformed itself; came essentially from the Sunday Leagues, the matches I played
in myself for many years. It might be amateur but it is expensive. Saturday's
game cost 20 quid for the park, a wet cockpit of green sward, #20 for the
referee, #25 for strips washed, league fees #30 per month, match balls #40
every time. (Matches are meant to have a new ball every game: that'll be
right). Few amateur players are under 25, some more than 40.
In fact, Cambusbarron were expected to win because they were older. They
didn't. Cambusbarron got two goals from their lad Pincombe but it wasn't
enough. St Ninian Thistle scored three, with Les Moir scoring the winner, and
him missing an early penalty, and Johnny Symons scoring the two others, though
Johnstone Kennedy made a claim on a goal. I wouldn't know myself.
You have to be in the middle of Stirling through a glass darkly to get the full
flavour of amateur football, or even care who scored at all. It got worse. I
discovered our sports editor's boy, Alasdair, at the game. He is 14 and should
have more sense than his dad. At least his team won and the boy was too young
to get me a drink in the Borestone. Alasdair has a twin called Iain. Their dad
calls them the Krays because, though fond of the little lads, he imagines they
are rougher than Stirling neds. But Stirling is not rough at all: it is a
lovely little place, apart from the language. You think I can swear?
Back in the Borestone Bar: never saw so many bottles of malt - more than 950
separate bottles of single malts. Sponsor George Wilson is introducing me to
Tony Crawford and George Kind. They are elderly gentlemen who hailed originally
from Poland and are dressed like George Sanders in a 1950s British movie, and
they changed their names so that Scots could understand them. The referee is
having a dram.
Cambusbarron won the amateur league in 1967, 1968, 1969, and 1977. They lost on
Saturday to St Ninians. I have little idea how I got home, except that my
sports editor's boy got me a taxi.
</TEXT>
