<HEADLINE>Greig bites your leg ends</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM SHIELDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061082</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE videos detailing the footballing life and times of John Greig are subtitled
``The Legend''. The question that immediately sprang to mind was: ``The end of
whose broken leg are we talking about?''
One of the few Greig jokes not included is the one which involves a phone call
to his wife to inform her that he has suffered a bad injury. ``I'm afraid John
will be coming home with a broken leg,'' says the Ibrox official. ``Whose leg
is it?'' asks Mrs Greig.
Indeed, when I heard that the Greig story was coming out in two videos, I
assumed that Part 1 was his life story and Part 2 was a collection of his
greatest fouls. The great man himself adds fuel to this reputation when he
relates the story of Willie Waddell's team talk before the Cup-Winners Cup
semi-final in 1972 against Torino.
The Italian No.10 was the danger man, said Waddell. He told Greig to ``put him
oot the game''. ``Jist for the night, boss, or for good?'' Greig replied.
In fact, in the two hours of watching in the videos of the John Greig Story, we
get a glimpse of only one foul, delivered to a Moscow Dynamo player in the
first seconds of the Cup-Winners Cup final in Barcelona in 1972.
As Alex MacDonald, midfield colleague of Greig's and no softie himelf, says:
``When you went out for Willie Waddell during that campaign, you would have
kicked your granny.''
Just as the victors get to write history, football videos show a cleaned-up
version of the lives of the heroes which they celebrate. A warts and all, fouls
and all, approach would be much more gripping but it would not go down at all
well with the SFA.
I would recommend the Greig video story to Celtic fans of all ages who may
regard the man as a bit of a clugger - to be reviled for the times he sent
Jimmy Johnstone or Bobby Lennox six feet into the air and to be praised
grudgingly  when, wearing a Scottish jersey, he did the same thing to Alan Ball
or Nobby Stiles.
The archive film reveals the young Greig as a skilful footballer, wrong-footing
opponents and dispatching measured passes to colleagues.
Young Greig played in a midfield with a chap called Baxter and contented
himself with playing a supporting role. But when Slim Jim was called up for
National Service and Greig took over his role on an undefeated pre-season tour
of the Soviet Union, in the words of colleague Bobby Shearer: ``Baxter wasn't
missed.''
Greig soldiered on through the dark years for Rangers when Stein was in charge
at Parkhead and came through to taste success under Willie Waddell and Jock
Wallace. The ultimate triumph at Barcelona in 1972, when Greig played with a
fractured foot, being only slightly dimmed by a huge Rangers fan falling on him
at full-time and fracturing the other foot.
Then there was the fact that the trophy had to be presented in the anonymity of
a room inside the Nou Camp because of what narrator Dougie Donnelly
diplomatically describes as ``the explosion of joy'' of the Rangers fans who
``just wanted to celebrate''.
We see Greig ending his playing career gloriously and fittingly with his 857th
game, winning a Scottish Cup medal, and completing the second treble in two
seasons. Greig would have done anything for Rangers and particularly for Willie
Waddell.
Greig tells of the much bigger demand Waddell made when he asked him to succeed
Jock Wallace as manager. Three years later, despite winning two Scottish cups
and a league title, Greig resigned, his health in ruins.
Perhaps John Greig was just too nice a man to be a football manager in these
days when those in the game seem all too eager to devour their own. The warmth
and respect shown in the video for John Greig from all his contemporaries is
immense. Not least from Celtic's Billy McNeill and Bobby Lennox, despite the
latter's somehat tattered leg-end after the attentions of Mr Greig.
q.Celtic fans who wish to re-educate themselves on the subject of Gentleman
John Greig have a chance to win my review copy of John Greig The Legend Parts 1
and 2 (Cameron Williams, #12.99 each). Simply send your name and address to Tom
Shields at the Herald, 195 Albion Street, Glasgow, G1 1QP. I will pick the
winner out of my unbiased Hamilton Accies tammy (somewhat unused of late).
</TEXT>
