<HEADLINE>United bounce back in black</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061083</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHEN Dundee United ran out on to Tannadice to face Dumbarton on Saturday decked
out in new colours, predominantly black, there were those among the home
support who judged the choice befitting of the general mood about the place so
far this season.
Inconsistency of performance having marred all but a few match days since
August, the overall impression of the United supporter has been one of intense
disappointment at what has been on offer.
Compare that attitude with the adulation heaped on their favourites some 90
minutes later, after a record-breaking 8-0 drubbing of strugglers Dumbarton,
and you appreciate the fickle nature of the football fan.
And if one is prepared to listen to United's scoring hero Craig Brewster, there
could yet be more afternoons of a similar nature to come from the side this
season.
After bagging a personal four-goal haul, the 28-year-old claimed: ``It just
proves that if everyone works as hard as they did in this one, anything is
possible.''
Brewster's scoring tally from limited top-team appearances this season through
injury - seven goals in just four starts - indicates his determination to hold
down the front-line recall he earned just nine days ago.
He added: ``The boss spent big money purchasing both Gary McSwegan and Owen
Coyle while I was recovering from a broken wrist, so I knew that I was going to
have to wait my turn, then grab it when it came.''
Brewster grabbed two goals in the first 15 minutes to point United in the right
direction, although the remarkable fact was that it took two great stops by
goalkeeper Ally Maxwell     to deny the visitors a shock lead.
However, once Grant Johnson added to the home lead five minutes from the
interval, the contest was over. The second half was best forgotten by the Sons
as Brewster struck in another superb double, Martin Melvin nodded one into his
own net, Owen Coyle made it seven, and Gary McSwegan stepped up off the bench
to complete the scoring.
Spare a thought for Dumbarton manager Jim Fallon. He has to lead his Boghead
side along the same road and the miles to Dundee tomorrow for a rearranged
league date against the other half of the City of Discovery.
Dundee United 8,
Dumbarton 0
</TEXT>
