<HEADLINE>A question of who should cast the final vote Scots' open challenge to change UK selection</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUG GILLON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061086</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ANGER over the exclusion of Scots from the British team which snatched
individual and team bronze in the Northumberland Challenge European
cross-country championships on Saturday may yet bear fruit, and the point was
driven home by a Scottish success in the open race.
Scottish skirmishing on traditional reiving territory beneath the battlements
of Alnwick Castle could help to establish a UK grand prix of up to six races
which could be the selection method for future UK teams.
Matt Frazer, secretary of both the British Athletic Federation and of the UK
cross-country commission, formally was handed a letter by Bob McSwein, convener
of the sport in Scotland.
It expressed disquiet at the exclusion of Kilbarchan's World championship
internationalist Robert Quinn from the team, demanded restructuring of
selection policy, and questioned the impartiality of coaches who chose the team.
McSwein believes UK commissioners should be among the selectors and should hold
the casting vote over the coaches' representation.
``With so many commercial interests now in the sport, coaches should not have
exclusive powers,'' he said.
However Bud Baldarro, the national coach, denied that any of the team were
looked after either by him or any other commission coach.
Frazer, who has agreed to re-examine selection before next year's event in
Belgium, said: ``I should like to see a UK grand prix of six races, with one in
Scotland. That would help promote the sport, and help with selection.''
Though Andrew Pearson's individual bronze was Britain's first men's medal in a
major championship since Tim Hutchings's world silver in 1989, it merely served
to underline Britain's inability to get it right.
With four to count, Britain had three runners in the first six, yet had to wait
until forty-second place before the team was counted home.
Absent from the UK squad were Paul Evans, Rob Denmark, Eamonn Martin, Jon
Nuttal, and Gary Staines - all world-class runners, any one of whom would have
made the difference between team bronze and gold. Britain's inability to field
its best men must be addressed before the World Championships in South Africa
next March.
Emphasising that was the presence in Eire's team of John Downes, who finished
seventeenth. Downes declared availability for Britain two years ago, but his
valid claims for inclusion in the UK team for the European track championships
were ignored, and he reverted to the Republic.
If his position on Saturday had replaced the fourth British counter (42nd) the
25-point swing would have seen Britain's total two points better than Spain,
who took team gold. ``Yes, I could have been running for Britain,'' Downes said.
Pearson produced a Hotspur performance, thrice trying to break the defending
champion, Portugal's Paulo Guerra on the final lap. However it was by just one
second that he fought off Keith Cullen who, only two months ago, was stabbed in
the chest by a mugger.
Of even greater triumph over adversity was the second place in the women's race
by Sara Wedlund of Sweden. Wedlund - with her blond hair and large-lensed
spectacles, she looks like the Milky Bar Kid - as recently as February still
suffered the effects of anorexia which almost halved her body-weight. ``I had
the problem for four years,'' she said. ``I could stand, but could hardly walk.
``This is the first year I have been able to run normally again,'' she said.
The 19-year-old Wedlund finished 15 seconds behind the winner, Annemari Sandell
of Finland. Just 18, and still eligible to defend the world junior title she
won last year, Sandell hopes to return, as she did last winter, to train with
the Kenyan team.
``They promised they would let me come back, but that was before I beat them to
win the world title,'' said Sandell.
Such a glorious recovery from death's door should be noted by several young
Scottish female athletes who are currently fighting the condition.
Scotland's exclusion from Britain's finest recent men's cross-country hour was
made the more poignant when the UK reserve, Steven Wylie, scored a runaway
success over the same course in the open race as the dusk fell on dank, bleak
afternoon.
Wylie, running his sixth race in 17 days, won by a distance from a field which
included most reserves from the 21 competing nations. His time would have
placed him seventieth overall in the 103-strong championship field, 93 seconds
ahead of the final UK team member, Carl Udall, who did, however, damage an
ankle in a fall.
The experience will cause the 24-year-old Cambuslang runner to reappraise his
excessive racing programme. Details (British names unless otherwise stated):
