<HEADLINE>Capital success in the inter-city clash</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061087</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EDINBURGH, who failed to win any of their matches in last season's
championship, made it two wins out of two, as they comfortably defeated last
year's champions Glasgow at Neilson Park, Haddington, on Saturday.
Edinburgh opened the scoring after three minutes when for the only time in the
game the ball was flashed along the line to winger Dean Jones, who went over in
the corner.
That was the only score of what became a scrappy first half as both back
divisions thereafter ran through their repertoire of rehearsed stereotyped
moves lacking in any inspiration or spontaneity. Too often they failed to take
the ball at pace, making life easy for both defences who tackled solidly.
Too little was seen of Glasgow as an attacking force. Chris Smith did make one
good break but ran out of support, and Stuart McAllister, who looked solid at
full back, was given little opportunity to show his attacking ability.
Up front, Edinburgh's pack produced the better possession as Paul McGinley and
Stuart Tait won a lot of good lineout ball. Glasgow's Ally Smith, however, took
the only strike against the head.
Further scoring was delayed until midway in the second half. From a lineout on
the Glasgow line, a loose ball was won by Edinburgh skipper Euan Thayne who fed
Ross Balmer who went over for the try assisted by his pack. Jonny Sim added the
conversion.
Jamie Millan pulled back Glasgow with a penalty. Thereafter Sim, who made a
couple of good breaks and generally kicked well, dropped a goal and later
slotted a well angled penalty to give Edinburgh their final margin of victory.
The result leaves Glasgow looking as favourites to take the wooden spoon, while
for Edinburgh a victory next Saturday against the South will give them the
district championship.
