<HEADLINE>Share of the spoils a fair result in six-goal classic</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>STEVE TONGUE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061088</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Wimbledon 3, Newcastle 3
WIMBLEDON and Newcastle, in their markedly different ways, brought colour and
passion to a grey south London afternoon yesterday as well as delighting
television viewers all over the world with one of the season's outstanding
Premiership games.
The result was the only fair one after 90 minutes of such equally divided
possession and opportunities. It leaves Newcastle five points ahead of
Manchester United at the top of the table, beaten just once in 20 games, while
Wimbledon, deprived of their first victory in 13 attempts, nevertheless climb
out of the bottom three.
For all their stylistic differences - or perhaps because of them - these teams
have a good effect on each other. In the previous two seasons, Wimbledon had
won the fixture 4-2 and 3-2; two months ago at St James' Park it finished 6-1
to Newcastle, after Wimbledon had keeper Paul Heald sent off and had to put
Vinnie Jones between the posts.
Yesterday Jones was absent, suffering from flu, and a wonderful game flowed all
the better without his abrasive interventions. Each side kept two men wide,
with two strikers in between them, so for once there was abundant room for the
remaining midfielders to work, rather than operating in conditions more like a
rugby scrum. The flanks were used well, passes went forward rather than
backwards or sideways and, not surprisingly, goals flowed - five of them before
half-time.
There had been three near misses even before Les Ferdinand opened the scoring
for Newcastle in the eighth minute. Their former striker Mick Harford lost
possession to John Beresford, who sprinted down the left and crossed for
Ferdinand to side-foot in.
Two ripostes in three minutes midway through the half reminded Newcastle of
their opponents' famed resilience, as well as their own occasional frailty in
defence. Keeper Shaka Hislop may have been blameless when Dean Holdsworth
clipped Jon Goodman's cross past him, but he was guilty of dropping a cross and
allowing Harford to drive in a shot that Efan Ekoku may just have got a touch
on.
On the half-hour, David Ginola, disappointingly quiet for much of the match,
made his one telling contribution with a cross that invited Ferdinand to clip
in his twentieth goal of the season.
Only four more minutes and Newcastle had regained the lead, with Ferdinand this
time the provider. Muscling along the bye-line, he refused to concede
possession and Keith Gillespie just beat a lunging defender to the pass.
Kinnear's two half-time substitutions, sending on Alan Reeves into defence and
Marcus Gayle on the left, kept his charges a little tighter at the back without
weakening their attacking threat, and they deserved the final goal. Holdsworth
scored it, after Harford headed Alan Kimble's cross square for him.
For once both managers agreed about the quality of the game and the justice of
the result. ``That's probably the hardest game Newcastle have had all season,''
said Joe Kinnear. Kevin Keegan did not disagree. ``Wimbledon ask different
questions of you, and we found some of them difficult to answer,'' he said.
