<HEADLINE>Stirling feel they have 43 points to prove Don't count County out of a last-gasp triumph</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BRIAN MEEK</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061089</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Stirling County 33,
Boroughmuir 14
STEWART Hamilton, who has been acting as Stirling captain in Kevin McKenzie's
absence, had to miss this one because of an attack of shingles.
But after the game, cigar at the glow, he was well enough to assure me that his
merry men might well be able to score the required points against Heriot's and
thus retain the championship.
``Let's see - we need a differential of 43 points. We'll score six converted
tries and then we'll only want a penalty. Perfectly possible.''
Hammy, 40 in February, will probably bring down the curtain with a vital
dropped goal.
McKenzie, agonising in the stand too, informs me he will certainly be fit for
the big one; he hopes to make his return on Saturday.
Bill Gibson, the Stirling president, spoke a bit more realistically when he
conceded: ``It will be a bit of a tall order to take so many points off a side
as good as Heriot's. Whatever happens, I am most proud of our side.
``Defending the title was never going to be easy and we made a horrendous
start. In the second half of the campaign, they have performed tremendously.''
For long spells, they did just that against Boroughmuir. County were emphatic
winners, though they may rue sitting back on their heels in the last quarter
when the Edinburgh side scored a fine try.
In truth, though Stirling were also without Ian Jardine, it was the visitors
who missed absent friends most. Take Peter Wright, Grant Wilson, Darren George,
and Stuart Reid out of a Boroughmuir pack and the first team does not pass the
Trades Descriptions Act.
Brian Robertson and John Manson made life miserable for the Edinburgh props and
Stirling had bags of ball. Mostly they used it well.
Everyone, not least his legion of admirers and readers, was pleased to see
Kenny Logan come good with two tries. Full back is his best position - I wrote
it two months ago and have not changed my mind.
Kenny Harper had an immaculate game too, but if one were awarding a
man-of-the-match prize, it would have to go to the old lad himself, Sean
Raymond Patrick Lineen, still the best play-maker in the land. ``I need the
money - I am going on until I am 50,'' he told me when battle was o'er. No-one
will complain.
The first half provided a high standard. Mark McKenzie opened up with a penalty
goal then David Elliot broke away, supported by Gavin Flockhart and Malcolm
Norval, to create a try for Colin McRobert.
Referee Eddie Murray played advantage which allowed Stuart Thom to nip over
from a ruck for the Boroughmuir reply, Bryan Easson converting.
McKenzie kicked a penalty and dropped a goal before Logan, who had already
demonstrated his sharpness, rounded off a flashing break by Gus Turner for
County's second try.
It was our Ken taking the bows again early in the second half. Gordon Mackay,
who had just come on, made the opening and Logan's finish was as deadly as
ever. McKenzie kicked the goal.
I think Elliot scored the final home try out in the murky corner though three
players gave me different names. If it was Harper, the other main suspect,
please accept the apologies. McKenzie definitely converted.
Boroughmuir, to their credit, ran everything and were finally rewarded when
Nick Marsdon set up a try for John McKinlay which Easson converted.
At the end, the announcer, and the large crowd, paid tribute to former Scotland
wing Iwan Tukalo, playing his last league game for Boroughmuir. I add mine;
nobody came off the left foot quite like ``Tuks'' and he was a model
professional when they did not even get paid.
