<HEADLINE>No argument from Ebdon as Hendry again wins by a distance</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061093</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNDISPUTED snooker king Stephen Hendry lifted the UK crown for the fourth time
in six years at Preston last night and warned: ``There is definitely room for
improvement.''
A 10-3 demolition of arch-rival Peter Ebdon earned the 26-year-old Scot a
#70,000 jackpot from the Royal Liver Assurance prize fund of #380,000.
In addition, he scooped #25,000 more for a 147 maximum against stablemate Gary
Wilkinson in the last 16.
Just for good measure, hot-shot Hendry rounded off another superb display with
a clearance of 146 in the final frame of last night's contest.
Despite that, the five-times world champion claimed after having secured the
twenty-fourth ranking title of a glittering career: ``You'll see the best of me
in the next two or three years.
``But if I'm to improve, I need someone to push me.''
There doesn't appear much chance of that happening on the evidence of the past
15 days. He slaughtered fellow Scot and provisional world No.2 John Higgins 9-1
in the semi-final and has now dismantled the provisional No.3, who in the past
has enjoyed numerous battle royals with the unstoppable Scot. So who else is
there?
In six matches at Preston the super-Scot has an aggregate frame record of
55-15, and not one opponent has taken more than three frames off him.
``My main aim for the rest of the season is to try and be more consistent. I
want to be involved at least to the end of every tournament,'' said Hendry.
``Last season I was either winning tournaments or getting knocked out in the
early rounds.''
Ebdon, appearing in his first UK final, had defeated Hendry twice this year but
lost their last meeting when he was beaten in the final of the Regal Masters in
Motherwell in September. Overall, he had three wins and five defeats in
previous head-to-head clashes with the No.1, and six of their eight meetings
had gone to deciding frames, including two contests in which Hendry had held
four-frame leads.
But this time Ebdon was never given a chance of upsetting the odds. He soon
found himself 4-0 adrift as Hendry knocked in breaks of 118 and 79 before the
Londoner opened his account with 76 in frame 5.
Crucially in the next three frames he found himself ahead but missed vital
balls, and Hendry cleared with successive runs of 66, 69, and 52.
The first session ended with Hendry 7-2 ahead and though his 25-year-old
Wellingborough-based opponent won the opening frame on the restart, the match
was soon over.
Twice in succession Ebdon broke down at the vital moment, and runs of 59 and 49
took Hendry within one frame of the winning post.
There was never any chance of a second maximum, as he potted a pink with a red
right at the start of his 146 clearance. But it brought the house down when the
final black disappeared, prompting Hendry to say: ``I love this town.''
Ebdon who gained a runner-up prize of #37,000 said: ``I've had a good
week-and-a-half and one bad day. But I'm sure I will get my time against him.
``The balls didn't run particularly kindly and though I didn't miss too many
balls, Stephen punished me severely.''
SNOOKER
</TEXT>
