<TEXT>
ICE HOCKEY
SCOTTISH internationalist Frank Morris scored an equaliser 19 seconds from time
to give premier division strugglers Fife Flyers a point in a 7-7 draw with
Nottingham Panthers at Kirkcaldy last night.
Flyers pulled their netminder in a bid to salvage something from the game and
won a face-off in Panthers end. The puck fell to Morris, and he scrambled it
home to send the 2000 home fans wild and complete a dismal weekend for the
Englishmen, who lost their grip on the Benson &amp; Hedges Cup with a 5-2 defeat by
Sheffield Steelers on Saturday.
Panthers, with netminder Scott O'Connor in good form, held a 3-1 lead after 13
minutes, but Flyers hit back to level at 3-3 by the first break. The English
side went 5-3 ahead at the mid-point only to see Mark Morrison's men pull back
to 5-5 two minutes into the final stanza.
Panthers went 7-5 ahead with nine minutes to go and it looked over for Flyers
until Doug Marsden slid home their sixth with four minutes left and Morris
proved the hero with his second of the night in the final minute.
Premier division - Fife 7, Notingham 7; Humberside 9, Newcastle 4; Cardiff 7,
Basingstoke 2; Durham 6, Milton Keynes 6; Slough 3, Sheffield 14.
Division 1 - Bracknell 8, Medway 3; Dumfries 16, Billingham 4; Paisley 8,
Telford 10; Peterborough 0, Manchester 7; Swindon 8, Guildford 3; Solihull 4,
Chelmsford 4.
