<HEADLINE>Footballing dream holds no guarantees Duffy's dilemma is a matter of propriety</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>KEN GALLACHER, CHIEF FOOTBALL WRITER</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061095</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE present English manager Terry Venables told me several times over the years
how he would like to own his very own football club; not just run the club as
chief executive the way he did at Spurs, but really to own it - lock, stock,
and barrel.
He had this dream while he was at Queen's Park Rangers, cherished it still
while he was at Barcelona, and insisted to me that it was the only sure way any
manager had of putting all his dreams into practice.
I think that Graeme Souness harboured the same idea at one time, but now Jim
Duffy has been handed the opportunity that those two much better-known football
figures sought; one which would place him in a similar position to Jim McLean,
who stepped from the dugout into the boardroom and who has placed his very
clear imprint on the Dens Parkers' city rivals, Dundee United.
Whether Duffy accepts the offer from Ron Dixon, the Canadian millionaire who
still owns Dundee, remains at the crux of the current situation surrounding the
Tayside club.
The player-manager has said nothing himself. The vice-chairman, Malcolm Reid,
has insisted that the offer which is on the table is totally dependent on
Duffy's acceptance.
If that falls through, Dixon will have to find other buyers to take on the
first-division club.
At the moment the proposed partnership of Reid and Duffy is the one which would
be approved by the supporters, coupling, as it does, the business sense of one
man and the football knowledge of the other.
Around Dens Park it is seen as the ``dream team''. Duffy has immense standing
among the fans because of the way he has guided the team through one apparent
crisis after another.
Clearly, Dixon has understood that, even from his Vancouver headquarters some
6000 miles away from Tayside.
The question now, though, is whether the man who has defied doctors to continue
playing the game he loves is ready to battle on all fronts to turn Dundee into
a successful club once again.
I do not pretend to know the answer to that. Presumably neither Dixon nor Reid
has the answer, either, otherwise there would have been a formal announcement
made by now.
It might seem, on the surface, to be an attractive proposition.
As Venables spelled it out to me all these years ago, it did seem an answer to
all the worries a manager has to face; no more interference from directors who
know nothing about the game, and no need to kow-tow to chairmen who will sack
you with more alacrity than they will back you when things turn sour.
Yet it was when he moved into the business side of football that Venables found
all his troubles, the ones which still haunt him today as he attempts to
prepare his English team for the European Championships next summer.
It could be that Duffy is mulling over these problems which have pursued
Venables down through the years since his famous bust-up with Spurs' Alan Sugar.
There is plenty to think about. Football acumen may not transfer easily to the
business side of the game.
At Tannadice, United have suffered since Jim McLean gave up his managerial post.
They did win the Scottish Cup under the guidance of Ivan Golac, but they are
now sitting in the first division on the same points as Duffy's team, who have
a match in hand.
That is a long way from their glory days in Europe.
Of course, Dundee had their own slide towards obscurity long before United
suffered.
It is only now they can claim that they are on a solid footing after years of
financial worries.
Only a personal loan from Dixon has kept them afloat, of course, and if Reid
and Duffy do accept the offer to move in, there is no guarantee that the club's
travails are over.
That, however, is the way of things at most clubs. Owning your own football
team may seem to be a dream come true, but for most men who achieve these dizzy
heights there are nightmares to follow.
Not everyone can be as successful as Jack Walker or David Murray.
Not everyone can afford to throw many millions of pounds into a club and
continue to do so until success arrives.
All of this will be churning through Duffy's mind as he weighs up the offer he
has been made.
He must decide soon, and while the fans want him to take on the job and while
it is clearly the best solution for Dixon, who wants to dump Dundee and devote
more time to his many other business interests around the globe, Duffy is the
man who has been put on the spot.
It will not be an easy decision for the Dens Park manager to make, but while he
ponders the issues he can always look on the bright side of life - after all,
he might have been offered Hearts and their #5m overdraft.
</TEXT>
