<HEADLINE>Monteith hoping to go one over the eight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>TOM McCONNELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061096</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PETER Monteith will be looking to consolidate his position at the top of The
Herald's Scottish trainers' championship at Edinburgh today when Killimor Lad
takes on Lucinda Russell's impressive Kelso winner Rocket Run in the Lasswade
Novices' Chase.
Monteith celebrated the 150th winner of his career at Catterick last week when
Flash of Realm, somewhat luckily, landed the Bobby Faulkner Memorial Chase.
The evens favourite was struggling three lengths behind Grazamber when the
leader took a crashing fall two fences from home.
Flash of Realm's victory gave the Rosewell man his thirteenth success of the
season and he now has a lead of eight over Russell and Colin Parker, with
reigning champion Len Lungo, on four.
Monteith intended to have four runners today but, after having walked the
Musselburgh track on Saturday, he found the going on the fast side, and
withdrew three.
Apart from a disappointing run at Hexham when he was pulled up, much to the
consternation of the trainer, Killimor Lad has performed consistently, with one
win - albeit the only finisher in a three-horse race - two seconds, and a third.
The former Irish point-to-pointer will have to be on his best jumping form if
he is to topple Rocket Run, who stayed on strongly to defeat Martin Pipe's
Banntown Bill decisively at Kelso last week.
Russell continues to make a big impact in the North in her first season as a
licence-holder, and her consistent chaser, Fiveleigh Builds, is almost certain
to start favourite for #5000 Wee Jimmy Mitchell Handicap Chase.
He won his first two races and has never been out of the frame in five outings.
Course and distance winner Countorus, has yet to find the form in which he was
successful in three novice chases last season, and Nigel Tinkler's Puritan may
pose the greatest threat.
Although he is having his first outing, the six-year-old gelding is suited by
the tight track, and won a novice chase here a year ago.
Pims Gunner is a sound jumper and genuine sort, but will have to improve on his
performance at Kelso last week when sixth behind High Padre, with Fiveleigh
Builds in second place.
Jim Goldie must have an excellent chance of breaking his duck with
Thisonesforalice in the Levy Board Handicap Hurdle.
The seven-year-old ran a promising race at Aintree when runner-up to Anlace in
a conditional jockeys' handicap hurdle.
If he repeats that performance, the son of Lochnager should bring overdue
success to the Uplawmoor yard.
</TEXT>
