<HEADLINE>Kirton denies #5m Euro loss</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061097</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EURO '96 chief Glenn Kirton yesterday slammed suggestions that the FA is facing
a #5m deficit when England stage the finals next summer.
``The alarmist talk of losing millions is rubbish,'' said the European
Championship tournament director.
``The bottom line is that both myself and Sir Bert Millichip (FA chairman) have
an undertaking from UEFA that they will not allow the tournament to make a loss
for the home association.''
While the FA have revised their budget for the first major competition they
have hosted since the World Cup in 1966, Kirton still believes they will come
home with a profit, around #2.5m if they manage to sell all 1.3m tickets.
But he insists: ``We are committed to staging an excellent tournament - and
excellence comes before profit.
``The championship belongs to UEFA, who take the largest proportion of the
income after the competing teams have taken their share for the development of
European football. The FA acts as UEFA's agent in this process.''
Kirton said the quality-before-profit principle applied particularly in the
areas of ticket sales, crowd policing, ground facilities for fans, and working
conditions for the media.
``We will ensure Euro '96 delivers on all these terms and that the Championship
will be a resounding success,'' he added.
Kirton also hit out at suggestions that the FA has gone ``cap in hand'' to UEFA
to ask for financial help.
England has asked for a contribution to soaring media costs and for one million
Swiss francs the FA have had to pay to buy back ``on-screen'' rights from the
European Broadcasting Union as part of a computer deal with a company called
Sema.
``UEFA have indicated that these are exceptional costs which they may pay
back,'' he said.
But he pointed out that the FA always regarded this tournament as a prestige
occasion, not as an opportunity to swell their own coffers.
``We do not control the commercial rights, we do not control the television
rights.
``We do have some control over ticketing and we will get 20% of any profit from
that. At the moment we need to sell 70% to break even and, if we manage to sell
100%, we will make a profit of between #2.5m and #3m.
``They are going extremely well. We have sold almost 400,000 on the UK market
and have to take it as read that the 440,000 available for the competing teams
will be taken up.
``That is all before a single game is known, so that's a pretty fair rate of
sale.''
EUROPEAN CHAMPIONSHIPS
</TEXT>
