<HEADLINE>Speaking of the future in Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOHN BEATTIE</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061099</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BIG NEWS! The GHK dinner is safe again! Many of you will be shocked and
saddened to know that what was once the most outrageous and dangerous dinner in
the UK for speakers has now become a gathering for a listening audience. I hear
Chris Spence got lost later, but there you have it.
``I am not going to show them I'm nervous,'' I said to Big Jill as I left the
house. Ten minutes later I was back having had to return from the Pond Hotel to
change out of my suit into black tie. There's nothing worse than turning up in
the wrong rig.
``I think you've now screwed up in that department,'' she said as I slipped
past her, giving me a knowing look that only women can.
Only speakers know what it's like to sit there at the top table, hardly able to
eat a thing, when you've just been invited as a macabre side show. I was to be
last up out of four.
Each time I passed the players' tables I could hear mutterings. They were scary
mutterings.
The incomparable Jimmy Martin was chairman. ``You've never written a decent
thing about GHK,'' he said in his intro, signalling me to my feet. Or at least
I think that's what he said. I hadn't had a single drink but my senses were
racing. My heart was pumping.
I could feel the apprehension in the room. On the one hand they all worried a
bit that I might suffer some dreadful fate. On the other they were desperate to
see it happen to the bloke they hate to a man. They were filled with the kind
of fear that tightens your testicles when you're about to sit down to a
terrible horror movie. You don't want to watch, but you can't miss a thing. You
want to groan as the blood flows. Oh, lovely!
Fifteen minutes later, like a flirtatious meeting with a 19-year-old blonde,
and it was all over. Okay, I'm boasting at 15 minutes. I lived. Or, more
accurately, they let me live. God knows how, but Harry Houdini would have been
proud.
But the message was simple. Here we all are in Glasgow, this great big city,
fighting out own little territorial battles, and going nowhere. I can pretend
as a Glasgow Accie that I hate GHK.
I don't. I could pretend that I hate West. I don't. I admire West hugely for
what they do with no direct feeder system.
What I gathered from the GHK dinner on Saturday - and GHK are the biggest club
in the city - is that the good Glasgow rugby people who filled that room all
now think that there has to be a new look at what is to happen to kick-start
the city into the next few years.
I looked at the players in the room. How much better is Graham Shiel than Harry
Bassi? Who would you rather put into a sevens team? If it is either, then it's
a marginal call.
There was Alan Watt. How we should have used him. There won't be many better
second rows than Cecil du Plessis. It was a room filled with rugby people, and
I think it was a room filled with rugby people who know that their club could
do better.
It was one of the assembled throng, and I won't name him, who came out with the
most observant line. ``Just what is our long-term aim in Glasgow?'' he asked.
Quite late it was.
``Nobody has sat down and tried to figure out what we want from the city. When
we formed GHK we did so to provide the best standard of rugby for the players
leaving the schools. That has changed. What we are needing now is a strategic
view. We now need to ensure that we can create a club that can take on the best
and beat them.''
We all nodded. It was sheer common sense. At the moment we have Glasgow Accies
employing Kevin Greene, one of the best coaches in the world, and I am sure
that is partly to try for our own success and thumb our noses at GHK, but I am
convinced it's also in the hope that GHK say: ``Okay, we see you're serious -
let's talk.''
GHK have made huge strides themselves. West of Scotland likewise. Hillhead
Jordanhill want to be a big club, and they have New Zealanders. Glasgow
Southern have grabbed the bull by the horns. Cartha want to go places. But
there isn't room for everyone at the top. Maybe two clubs.
Don't worry, I'm not going to do the ``let's pull down the fence'' bit, because
I know it winds people up. But the clubs in Glasgow have to sit down round a
table and hammer something out, and soon. There isn't an easy answer about what
happens to all the fourth XV players. But there are enough sensible thinkers in
this city to lead us forward.
I escaped the hanging. But only just.
</TEXT>
