<HEADLINE>Door to golfing's big-time opens for two Scots Gallacher and Russell pass test with honours</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061101</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WINNING golf tournaments on the European Tour is a demanding task; getting the
opportunity to win them is a great deal harder. As with aspiring tennis players
and Formula One drivers, chance would be a fine thing for the sweet young
swingers of Europe who play the Royal and Ancient game with a style, class, and
skill that makes most of their predecessors appear mediocre.
Such has been the effect of the golf explosion well beyond the confines of the
British Isles that the prospect of making lots of moolah on the major tour
inevitably has hoisted amateur standards and at the same time encouraged a
greater number of amateurs to take the game seriously.
The consequence of it all is the increasing difficulty for even the cream of
the young men chasing that place in the sun to get the card which opens the
doors to the big-time and, if they survive well enough, riches. Glory can come
later.
The enormous challenge of a pre-qualifying competition over three rounds, in
which something in the region of 600 ambitious young and not-so-young golfers
chase the 180 or so places in the qualifying tournament, is daunting enough,
but the lads are only just warming up. They then have to compete for 40 places
over six rounds, invariably over the most taxing of courses.
It is a procedure which must have been the brainchild of an ex-Burma Road
commander, 108 holes of mental torture, at the end of which the failures find
themselves back at ``Go''.
All of which should be good reason for everyone with Scottish golf interests at
heart to offer unstinting congratulations to Stephen Gallacher and Raymond
Russell, the two home stalwarts who came through the latest test at San Roque
in Spain last week.
Russell was putting himself through the agony for the third time and is
entitled to a gentle winter.
Gallacher, however, came straight from the amateur ranks to tackle the
nine-round examination for the first time and, at one stage, looked as if he
might finish in front of them all.
The 21-year-old nephew of successful Ryder Cup captain Bernard Gallacher,
Stephen had a fine year as an amateur, winning the Scottish Strokeplay title
and the Lytham Trophy, among many other prizes, but his finest moment came as a
member of the triumphant Walker Cup team.
Even that impressive track record, however, does not prepare anybody for the
nine rounds of stress in the professional qualifying contest. Stephen would
tell you that himself.
Back home in Bathgate and still, on his own admission, ``on a high'', Gallacher
confesses that he could not sleep on the night before his final round.
``I was sitting at four under and at that point the cut was five over, so I had
nine shots in hand. You just start thinking how you would feel if you shot 80.
I suppose that is why I got a bit negative in the last round. Maybe I shouldn't
have done but it was a good lesson, I suppose.''
Stephen acknowledges that the qualifying test is the toughest golf competition
that he has had to face.
``The pre-qualifying especially is hard. You could feel the tension. I was
lucky in that one of my best pals caddies for me and that helped break the
strain a bit.
``In Spain, you could see guys who had lost their card and were back trying
again for the second or third time and maybe they were trying too hard. That is
one of the dangers.
``It is also very tense until you get past the fourth round. At least you know
then you will get some kind of category that will let you play in some
tourna-ments.''
He followed the advice of Uncle Bernard by not thinking of winning.
``That was good advice because I stuck to thinking about getting my card and
didn't go for anything silly.''
Stephen, a young man who gives the impression of maturity beyond his years,
reckons he got a wee glimpse of what the pro scene will be like, the
self-discipline and restraint that is required to build a score and a career.
``In a way, the qualifying makes you think like a pro,'' he said.
His first year on the circuit will be eased financially by the backing of a
sponsor to be announced soon but before he sets out on his great adventure,
Stephen intends to seek out Bernard again for a long talk and, in his case,
listen.
``I want to ask Bernard about what is the best way to go about this year,
tournaments to play, etc. There is nobody better qualified to ask, is there?''
He knows that to survive and stay on the tour he has to get into the top 120,
which would mean winnings of around #40,000.
``That is my goal for this year. I don't want to go back to that qualifying
again and I don't want to set myself targets. It will depend on what Bernard
says about everything, including whether I need management or not.''
Whatever advice his uncle offers, Stephen already is determined to keep his
feet firmly on the fairway.
``I know there is a world of difference between being an amateur and a pro.
Hopefully, if I can hold on to my card, I can then try to progress. I don't
expect to win anything, but, if that comes along, it would be great. My aim
would be to make the cuts and take it from there.''
He and the family were still coming down from the celebrations . . . ``my
caddie brought a bottle of champagne but didn't tell me until I was through'' .
. . but now he will have a rest until after Christmas. Then he will be off to
see the Guru of Largs, Bob Torrance, to sort out some parts of his game he
feels need attention.
Stephen has never had any other ambition than to be a professional golfer.
Whatever else happens, he can claim he has made it. The next bit is even
tougher but don't bet against him reaching the top of that tree, too, in due
course. His feat in making it first time into the tour is best illustrated by
recalling that Ian Woosnam tried the qualifying method three times and never
made it, eventually getting on the circuit via the Safari Tour, and Barry Lane
had to go seven times before he got there.
It hasn't become any easier in the meantime.
</TEXT>
