<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000109</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000109</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Injuries produce a game of two halves</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061102</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
DUNFERMLINE delighted the home support by turning on the style in the opening
30 minutes and scoring three times to snuff out Hamilton's weak challenge.
But then the league leaders disappointed their fans by failing to drive home
their advantage for the rest of the game.
The key to the problem was the loss of strikers Stewart Petrie and Greg Shaw,
who both went off with ankle injuries after scoring in the opening burst of
action. Their departure seemed to upset their team-mates.
But Dunfermline manager Bert Paton knows he will need more consistency from his
players to maintain their promotion challenge in a very competitive first
division.
Goals from Shaw after only three minutes, Derek Fleming in 13, and Petrie in
25, gave Dunfermline a comfortable lead.
But it was not until two minutes from time that Andy Tod added a fourth goal.
Paton said he was pleased with the way his team played in the first half, but
admitted he was very disappointed with the second-half display.
``There are still one or two players who are a bit rusty after missing games,''
he said. ``But they are coming back and we are getting there.
He added: ``When the two strikers went off, Hamilton tightened things up a bit
in the second half. The injuries affected us, but the second-half display was
not acceptable.''
Hamilton, who recorded their first league win of the season at Paisley the
previous week, never even looked like scoring against Dunfermline.
``We were well beaten by a better side,'' confessed manager Iain Munro. ``We
defended poorly. We have no complaints. They did their job very
professionally.''
Munro said the promotion race would remain very competitive with both Dundee
sides, Morton, and Dunfermline all making a strong challenge.
``They will all beat each other, and Airdrie and St Johnstone will have a say
in what is going on,'' he added.
``But Dunfermline will not be far away. They are a premier club, and that is
why they have to take a look at expanding the league.''
Dunfermline 4, Hamilton 0
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000110</DOCNO>
