<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Weight for it, Hamed</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061103</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
PRINCE Naseem Hamed can bank the regal sum of #1m for a showdown with Irish
star Wayne McCullough.
That was the figure put on the table by McCullough's American manager, Matt
Tinley, after the Ulsterman's triumphant return to Belfast to retain his WBC
title with an eighth-round stoppage of Denmark's Johnny Bredhal at the King's
Hall.
A seven-figure cheque would appeal to Hamed, but there is a crucial condition
which is likely make the offer extremely difficult to accept - ``Naz'' must
reverse through two divisions to fight McCullough at bantamweight.
Hamed has not had to trim down to the 8st 6lb division for more than a year,
has progressed to super-bantam, and on to the WBO featherweight (9st) title
during his rapid rise to stardom.
To demand that a young, growing athlete like Hamed takes off 8lb to backtrack
his career is asking a lot, probably too much, and enough to knock-out the
fight for good.
McCullough is convinced that Hamed will not lose pounds to gain them. ``Naz
won't come down to the weight because he is scared. I'd fight him any time. I
want to beat the best at my weight.''
Television executive Tinley added: ``Wayne does not need Naseem. He packed out
the King's Hall, he is on worldwide TV. But if Hamed can work and train hard to
fight at bantam, he can have #1m to fight Wayne for the most legitimate title
you'll ever have.''
McCullough is also big for a bantam and is not far away from the day when he
progresses to super-bantam and then on to feather, although his 84-year-old
American motivator and trainer Eddie Futch - rated by many as the best in the
business - insists the Irishman is still strong at the 118lb category.
McCullough's next outing is scheduled for Dublin in February or March. There
appears to be a possibility of him having a dart at the WBC super-bantam crown
of the 35-year-old Daniel Zaragoza, or a defence of his own title against
another Mexican, Jose Bueno, a winner on the Belfast undercard.
On the Belfast fight, Tinley observed: ``Bredahl was running around after
Wayne, looking like Carl Lewis disguised as Bredhal.''
And McCullough observed: ``The referee told Bredhal 30 seconds before he ended
it that he must throw more punches.''
The intervention of Mexican referee Lupe Garcia after 1min 55sec of the eighth
looked premature. The Dane was hardly given a chance to obey the orders to
punch more.
BOXING
</TEXT>
