<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Main has a hand in exasperating Airdrie</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061104</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIS result was of little use to either side as they became further detached
from the leading pack. However, it was difficult for Airdrie manager Alex
MacDonald to complain about his team's performance.
The draw was more about the brilliant individual performance of Alan Main in
Saints' goal than the shortcomings of his strikers. ``That's the second week in
a row that a goalie has had an outstanding game against us. Last week it was
Ally Maxwell, today it was Main.''  From the fifth minute when he touched over
Peter Duffield's volley from Jimmy Boyle's cross, the keeper was inspired. Jim
McIntyre's header looked netbound until Main flicked it over.
Even when Kenny Black's pass put McIntyre through, the keeper stayed on his
feet until the last second before diving to save. Another Duffield snap shot
and a drive from Boyle were both palmed away.
Main was suitably modest about his own contribution. ``They were all reaction
saves, but obviously I'm delighted about the way things are going for me now.''
Matters looked even brighter for the visitors when they took the lead early in
the second half. From Euan Donaldson's free kick, Sean Sweeney's mis-hit
clearance only reached Philip Scott, who drilled his shot low past John Martin.
Airdrie equalised with just 16 minutes to go . Black's in-swinging free kick
required only the slightest of glances from Jim McIntyre's head to leave the
keeper helpless.
Airdrie 1, St Johnstone 1
</TEXT>
