<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000114</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000114</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Judging the final decision</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061107</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
RANGERS' latest problems with the SFA disciplinary committee may be construed
by some as a continuation of the alleged selective application (in their case),
of both the football and criminal laws. This is for the punters to judge for
themselves.
Last Friday's highly publicised case does, however, add weight to Rangers'
argument. Paul Gascoigne's behaviour in the recent match against Aberdeen
cannot be condoned, provocation or otherwise, but Rangers' statement that
``certain aspects of the reporting of disciplinary matters require close
scrutiny'' is surely correct.
I, along with Rangers, have a problem with the use of referee supervisors. This
is because, in this and other recent cases, the referee supervisor's evidence
has been accepted on incidents where the referee has taken no action during the
game. I do not profess to know the exact details of what goes on behind the
closed doors of Park Gardens, but this must be the case, mustn't it? I mean
they don't accept television evidence!
If the SFA are going to allow the supervisor to overrule the referee, then
logically this is an admission that the referee can get it wrong. Furthermore,
if they are willing to admit that referees are fallible in disciplinary matters
then they must surely be prepared to accept that some of their judgments on
play are also wrong.
Most of us can recall examples where undeniably bad decisions by referees have
cost clubs dearly. When equally bad judgments are witnessed by the supervisors
in future, can we look forward to them overturning them retrospectively? I
think not! It is high time that Mr Farry and his organisation got consistent in
these matters.
For over 100 years, we have been told that a referee's decision, good or bad,
is final and I would advocate that this should remain so. My understanding is
that the other officials are referee supervisors and if so, their only duty
should be to report on the performance of the referee, NOT the players. If
their reports are to be used in evidence against players then they should be
submitted within two hours of the conclusion of the game. This would eliminate
the possibility of their being influenced by what they see on television, or
indeed read in the press.
Bryan D Weir,
32 Beaton Road,
Balloch,
Dunbartonshire.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
