<DOCNO>GH951204-000116</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000116</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Championship show but champagne on ice Melrose will just have to sit it out - and hope</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061109</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Melrose 31, Gala 11
JUST as the light was fading at The Greenyards, the Premiership trophy was in
the bag. But it wasn't headed for the Melrose trophy cabinet. It was back in
the Murrayfield bagman's hold-all ready to re-merge in a fortnight's time after
the championship showdown between Stirling County and Heriot's FP.
Melrose have now played all the cards in their hand. To discover whether or not
it is a winning hand they must now await the outcome of that Goldenacre game on
December 16. If Stirling beat Heriot's by 43 points or more, then the
championship is theirs. If not, then Melrose take the honours.
It is not the most satisfactory manner in which to bring down the curtain on an
enthralling championship season but, with the Western Samoan tour and the final
stages of the Premiership calendar running in tandem, alternative scenarios
were few and far between. Just thank the weatherman that Jack Frost was not
added to the equation.
It would have been all over on Saturday if Stirling had lost to Boroughmuir -
and how the defending champions must now be ruing their slow start to the
championship campaign and that home draw against Melrose last weekend. But now
it goes to the wire and, although it must be a long shot, a second championship
resting on wiping out that 43-point differential remains a possibility, just.
To refresh the memory, when County and Heriot's met first time around this
season, the scoreline was 38-6 in Stirling's favour. Add 11 points to that
margin this time and what threatened at one point to be a wash-out season for
Stirling will have a rainbow at journey's end.
At The Greenyards on Saturday, Gala should have been put to the sword by
Melrose. Sadly for Gala, pre-match bravura that they had nothing to lose and
that the pressure was all on Melrose failed to produce the kind of display
which would have been a fitting farewell to Division I.
The Melrose star which shone most brightly was Craig Joiner. He had a hat trick
and combined aggression and balance in his running, which suggests that, after
injury, he returns to the fray sharp and eager with the Five Nations' beckoning
next month.
Bryan Redpath had another fine game and the facts that Joiner saw so much of
the ball and that Melrose's other try came from Gary Parker on the opposite
wing indicate that the half-backs were spreading play when the opportunity
arose. Twice, the intruding Shepherd was involved in Melrose tries and Graham
Shiel, with a majestic break, was mostly to thank for one of Joiner's. From a
Melrose viewpoint, and with the points chase in mind, the pity was that they
scored only eight points in the second half.
Gavin Dalgleish kicked Gala into the lead with a penalty goal after eight
minutes. Parker equalised with a penalty after a Shiel half-break which caught
Gala offside. Gala were defending at full-stretch when Parker kicked his second
penalty, then Joiner had his first try, converted by Parker, after a Redpath
break, good back-up work by Joiner and Feau'nati, and a ruck-feed from Redpath
on the line.
His second try, after 34 minutes, proved the truth of that old adage which says
that speed kills. The ball went via Redpath, Chalmers, and Sheil before Joiner,
still with a bit to do despite a two-man overlap, sped in at the corner.
Dalgleish, suffering as did scrum half Paterson from haphazard service from the
Gala pack, had a penalty for the Maroons as half-time approached but Melrose
hammered home their superiority with Joiner's third try. From a scrummage on
the Gala 10-metre line, the ball zipped along - Redpath, Chalmers, Shiel,
Shepherd - and the winger made it 23-6 at the turn.
Parker's try was a gem. A reverse pass from the base of a scrummage by Redpath
saw Shepherd careering down the middle and Bain sending the effervescent Parker
over. Gala were awarded a couple of penalties, both missed by Dalgleish, before
Parker kicked his third and a minute from the end Gala, at last, were rewarded
for a spirited final 10 minutes with a try by Moncrieff after spadework by
Amos, Weir, and Paterson.
</TEXT>
