<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000117</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000117</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>What might have been</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ARTHUR SHORT</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061110</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Watsonians 39, Hawick 6
IT HAD all the hype of a Gavin Hastings show. The TV cameras were on the
touchline, the autograph hunters were there in strength, and the charismatic
former Scotland captain was nodding to or shaking hands with all sorts of
visitors to Myreside.
Although Big Gav was getting top billing, the supporting cast in the
Watsonians' line-up soon proved it was no one-man show.
With the first-division title now a two-horse race, Watsonians must be
reflecting ruefully on some of the uncharacteristic slip-ups they have made.
They could so easily have been right at the top of the tree this season.
Their back division moves at electric pace allied to super-glue handling that
could tear apart the best defences in the country when they are on song.
Injury-stricken Hawick were witnesses at their cost to the devastating cutting
edge of this Watsonian team in full flight.
Every player behind fly-half Andrew Garry scored in the six-try bonanza. The
bold Gavin did not get a touchdown but collected nine points with his trusty
right foot and slipped into every position in the back division at some time or
another.
The visiting Greens had eight first XV players out of action but can be proud
of their younger set asked to do a job.
Other than Watsonians, Hawick had managed at least one win over the other
first-division combatants. But the Myreside team earned the ``double'' in
devastating fashion.
The first cruel blow was struck in just 27 seconds when Kiwi Si Farland went
over for a try when skipper Fergus Henderson caught the visitors napping with a
quick lineout throw-in after Hawick full back Graeme Renwick had allowed an
Andrew Garry diagonal kick to trundle away from him and into touch. He dropped
the ball and Henderson picked it up to feed his hookers.
It took the Greens a long time to recover from that and in fact they were 17-0
behind before they intruded into Watsonian territory with any real threat.
Garry, Jamie Mayer, Scott Hastings, and John Kerr interpassed before the
younger Hastings went over.
Then a burst by Scott H sent Henderson careering over for another try.
Hawick got into the game about now but despite some well-earned possession,
failed to produce an incisive edge to beat the Watsonians' blanket defence.
Just before the interval, Gavin Hastings had his only penalty success.
Hawick restarted with renewed vigour and Grant Blacklock and Grant Harris
responded to the lead of skipper Brian Renwick. A lot of ball was won and run
from one side of the pitch to the other. Green jerseys launched themselves at
the Watsonians line but there was no way through.
Fly-half Scott Welsh failed with a drop attempt then, in desperation to get
points on the board, kicked two penalties after numerous awards had been run in
an effort for a touchdown.
Watsonians absorbed all that pressure and the flamboyant Gavin Hastings burst
on the scene again to take play to the other end and set up a score for Alan
Kittle which Gavin converted.
Scott Hastings set winger John Kerr on the road to the Hawick line and his
power took him over with defenders clinging to him.
Gavin converted but failed to goal a fine try by the straight-running Jamie
Mayer, who finished off great support work by both his wingers.
Watsonians - G Hastings; F Henderson, S Hastings, J Mayer, J Kerr; A Garry, J
Weston; M Stanaway, S Farland, A Kittle, S Grimes, C Mather, G Hannah, C Brown,
I Sinclair.
Hawick - G Renwick; G Sharp, R Allott, D Grant, K Suddon; S Welsh, K Reid; M
Russell, G Blacklock, B McDonnell, M Robertson, A Barnes, G Harris, B Renwick,
G Allott.
Referee - J Fleming (Boroughmuir).
SCORERS: Watsonians - Farland, 1t; S Hastings, 1t; Henderson, 1t; Kittle, 1t;
Kerr, 1t; Mayer, 1t; G Hastings, 3c, 1p. Hawick - Welsh, 2p.
</TEXT>
