<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000118</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000118</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Competition the key for Morton</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061111</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
NINE clubs in the first division all have the one question this morning - will
nothing upset Morton?
The Greenock club in recent weeks have had to deal first with the transfer of
their outstanding midfielder Derek McInnes to Rangers and then with the sight
of their manager Allan McGraw being rushed to hospital during one of their
matches.
Yet, they still seem to power on regardless in much the same way as manager
McGraw bounced back to return to fitness and work within 48 hours.
The other clubs had been waiting to see if there would be any sign of weakness,
but there was no suggestion of uncertainty during this 90 minutes, and indeed
there was an air almost of inevitability that the Greenock side would end up
the winners despite a goalless first half.
That view was enhanced a minute into the second period when Derek Lilley opened
their account when he shrugged off the challenge of Colin Sutherland to score,
and continued with a double from Marko Rajamaki in a four-minute flourish.
Manager McGraw has his own explanation for the continued success. ``There is
competition for places in this side, and the players are responding,'' he said.
``Look at our keeper David Wylie. Since we signed the Cameroon keeper Andre
Boe, David has not had a bad game.
``We also have strength and flair in the middle of the park, where Janne
Lindberg is playing a captain's role and where Alan Mahood sees things that
other players cannot see.
``Up front there is the like of Derek Lilley, who has the pace to worry any
defence, and Marko, who got those two goals today, is very dangerous at the far
post.''
Certainly, the truthful Clydebank coach Brian Wright was under no illusions
about the outcome, for he said: ``I have no complaints for they were a better
team in all departments.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000119</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000119</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Pavin is one in a million</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061112</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
GOLF ROUND-UP
COREY Pavin, the US Open champion, won the richest individual prize in golf in
the Million Dollar Challenge in Sun City yesterday. The 36-year-old Californian
won by five from 1993 champion Nick Price to take the $1m jackpot with a
72-hole total of 276, 12 under par.
``It's kind of fun to win a million dollars. I've never done that before,'' he
said after his six-under-par 66, the lowest of the week, took him clear.
Price birdied three of the first five holes to go one ahead, but bogeyed the
sixth, which Pavin birdied. The final blow came at the par-5 fourteenth. Price
took 6 while Pavin had a birdie. For the second day in a row Pavin did not drop
a shot.
Scotland's Sam Torrance shot a closing 72 for fourth place in his first
appearance in the event.
Nick Faldo's poor showing was compensated when he was named first winner of the
``Canon Shot of the Year'' for his 93-yard pitch to four feet on the final hole
of his Ryder Cup match with Curtis Strange. Final scores:
276 - C Pavin (USA) 69, 72, 69, 66 (#666,000).
281 - N Price (Zimbabwe) 71, 67, 72, 71 (#166,000).
283 - B Langer (Germany) 72, 69, 71, 71 (#133,000).
284 - S Torrance (Britain) 69, 73, 70, 72 (#116,000).
