<HEADLINE>Players' demands on the table</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS Chief rugby writer</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061114</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Scottish Rugby Union has now received an amended contract from the
international squad's lawyer, and negotiations will begin with a view to having
the players under contract to the union before Christmas.
The contract, said to be worth around #22,500-a-man if the Scottish side had
won all of its five games until the end of March - last month's draw against
Western Samoa being accounted for retrospectively - effectively will make the
players employees of the SRU with all of the two-way responsibilities that such
a relationship implies.
SRU senior vice-president Fred McLeod said yesterday that the amended version
had been received only at the weekend and he had not had time to study it in
detail but the players were making observations about the intended make-up of
the cash available.
``It was, I suppose, inevitable as the negotiations continue, that the players
should seek more money, or at least, to seek to have the money divided up in a
different format. As the employers, we have to speak to them about the
distribution of money within a framework that we can afford.''
Yesterday Craig Chalmers, one of the player-representatives on the contracts
working party, said: ``We've not asked for more money, but there are a number
of things that we are not entirely happy about and the manner in which the
contract cash is divided is one of them.
q.FRED McLeod also said yesterday that the SRU were now examining ``blocks of
dates'' for the new European Championship.
McLeod was in Dublin last week for a European Championship meeting and is
reporting to the SRU. The decision on whether clubs or districts from Scotland
compete in next season's championship for the first time is dependent to a
large extent on how it will fit into the Scottish domestic season.
</TEXT>
