<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Remorse should be name of the game</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JAMES TRAYNOR</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061115</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
UNLESS you are so narrow-minded you can look through a keyhole with both eyes
open at the same time, you will have detected an absence of remorse among those
who have been bleating because a handful of footballers were summoned before
the SFA to explain recent behaviour.
It is not as though Gascoigne, Brown, Sweeney, and co. were forced to shuffle
up the hill to the front doot of Bleak House in leg irons. In fact, miscreants
usually arrive in style and leave tight-lipped and stern-faced, like men who
have been wronged.
I have lost count of the number of times journos have huddled together on the
Park Gardens pavement awaiting verdicts, but I do not recall hearing one
player, manager, or club director saying: ``Sorry.''
The apparent inability of people within the game to admit guilt, or to accept
unacceptable behaviour on the pitch which could endanger the well-being of a
fellow professional is a screaming indictment of the standards employed. If
just once someone emerging from a disciplinary hearing said: ``I got what I
deserved and I'd like to apologise for my actions,'' that just might be the
beginning of a better tomorrow for us all.
Then again if players said after a match in which they had used foul methods
against opponents that they were sorry, and if their clubs then made it clear
severe punishment would be handed down to the players, football might again be
allowed to police itself. A referee's negligence or the cunning of a player who
strikes behind the official's back should no longer mean the offender escapes
punishment.
Aberdeen have made it clear they would be taking action against Stewart
McKimmie, sent off early in the match against Partick Thistle on Saturday, for
alleged use of an elbow on Callum Milne, and the Pittodrie club are to be
commended. However, Aberdeen should have declared the extent of the punishment
and the player also ought to have issued an apology.
Football is under greater scrutiny and those who believe only the referee
should have the power to enforce justice are naive. Arguments over
technicalities concerning referee supervisors merely cloud the issues and
transmit the wrong messages to outside agencies, so let us not waste any more
time debating whose job it is to referee a football match.
It is a simple matter with the match official's word standing as law, but when
incidents which are against the spirit of the game occur and go unpunished
because the referee either missed or chose to miss them for whatever reason,
the authorities are entitled to expect a supervisor in the stand to make
reference to them. It is then the SFA's duty to take the appropriate action.
Since there are clubs who wish to use the mere wording of the supervisor's job
as a means to protect players whose behaviour may have been reckless, perhaps
the relevant description should be amended. Let's all start behaving sensibly
and perhaps then the procurator-fiscal will remain a fan of the game rather
than a participant.
So many people become incensed when the police are ordered to investigate
on-field behaviour and yet some of those who complain loudest possess the
remedy. Club managers, directors, and chairmen have to make it clear to their
teams that severe financial penalties will be imposed when a player resorts to
unacceptable behaviour, and please, don't give me that stuff about the game
being one of passions and adrenalin.
Wild tackles and flailing arms and legs, and the heading of anything other than
the ball cannot be allowed.
Acts of violence which endanger the health of others must be discouraged, and
surely it is obvious to everyone by now that when football fails to punish
offenders, some higher authority will.
It is wrong to let players believe anything they do inside the white borders of
a football pitch should be considered beyond reproach. Again I say it is the
duty of clubs to make their players certain they must play fair and that if
their tempers are uncontrolled, there will be serious repercussions.
The recent stance adopted by Rangers when they were unhappy about some of their
players being called to the SFA on the basis of a supervisor's report and not
one compiled by the referee, was ridiculous. Instead of complaining, Rangers
ought to have taken their own action from the beginning.
The game and everyone involved must start playing their parts and a little more
honesty has to be employed. Football's people must accept there is a greater
responsibility weighing on them and it does no good when players, who may have
crossed the line between what is and isn't acceptable, are protected by their
clubs.
The sooner footballers believe it is not a weakness to say ``sorry'' the easier
it will be to keep procurators-fiscal at bay, but as things stand you would
have to say the attitudes of just about everyone involved in football are
irresponsible.
The perfect example of what is wrong in our game was displayed in the circus
which surrounded Duncan Ferguson's recent return to Goodison after a spell in
prison.
He was given a hero's welcome and took a bow before Everton's fans in a display
which suggested he had been victimised, that somehow he had been wronged. It
was a demonstration of football's inability to grasp the fact the sport is not
above the law.
What sort of messages did Ferguson's welcome send out to the children who watch
and play the game? Football really is a most disrespectful and irresponsible
world.
</TEXT>
