<HEADLINE>Catching tall tales at the riverbank</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JOANNA MacDONALD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>11</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061116</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE was talk of priests and gaffes but no mention of the unfortunate Bishop
Casey of Galway, undone by a woman's wrath. It was a day when long silences
were punctuated by tall tales.
St Andrew's Day means different things to different people. It's about Saltires
and Scottishness, and this year Michael Forsyth and the Constitutional
Convention.
For one disconsolate group it meant the last day's salmon fishing on their
favourite river in Dumfriesshire. And so it was that three men and I went
fishing - but not in a boat.
A day on the river, it seems, requires rigorous planning and as many
accoutrements as Vlad the Impaler.
First, the all-important provisions. I sensed some deep-seated insecurity when
The Three packed what appeared to be enough for a convoy to Bosnia. Clearly,
however, this was an integral part of the day out. And so there was soup,
sandwiches, cake, coffee, and the ubiquitous hip flask.
Next came the equipment. Salmon rods, at 17ft, are as long as many rivers are
wide. There were dinky little boxes of flies, nets (for the countless salmon to
be caught), reels galore, torches, and all manner of lines from floating ones
to sinking ones.
And yes, they did all have Barbours on and waders that reached up to their
oxters.
The business of getting started is laborious. Putting the rods together was a
bit like playing with a Meccano set and the boys loved it. They paraded up and
down the river, checking out their favourite pools.
And then the fishing got under way. Style is all. As in all walks of life, you
either have it or you don't. One of the party was relatively new to the sport
and flaggelated the water with a style reminiscent of the Wild West. The salmon
would have had to be remedial to be fooled by Rawhide.
Another was more timorous. His line went on to the water like an apology, in
marked contrast to his appearance. Fatboy just wasn't at home on the water.
But The Third Man was an expert. Confidence oozed from every cast and he seemed
completely oblivious to the strong east wind blowing straight at us as his fly
shot out in a true line across the water.
The morning went by. The salmon, apparently, were sleeping, for nobody caught
as much as a glimpse of one. Not a single splash had disturbed the silence,
except possibly from Rawhide.
Then it was time for lunch. It was like being back at school. ``Oh, you've got
egg. That's good. I'll give you a ham salad for one of those,'' Fatboy enthused.
Fishing bores have much in common with their golfing counterparts. The golfers
gather in the clubhouse reliving that shank on the fifth or the hook on the
twelfth and discussing the added distance with graphite clubs.
Meanwhile, the fishermen huddle on the grass with tales from the riverbank.
They ponder the merits of stiff rods, weight forward line, Delphi Silvers and
Silver Wilkinsons. Lunch passed with stories of former glories, of minnows
missed and tussles with 20 pounders.
Then it was back to the fishing. But boys will be boys. As children they
compete to see who can pee furthest up the wall. As men on the river little has
changed. By mid afternoon, with the salmon still posted missing, they were in
competition again - to see who could cast the longest line.
The waiting finally got to Rawhide and he erupted. He thrashed his rod across
the water, wailing: `` Bite, you bastards.'' The salmon weren't listening.
Changed days from 1870 when a group of four went on a fishing expedition to the
Outer Hebrides.
They went by steamboat from Greenock to Harris where fish would be ``plentiful
and simple-minded''.
And indeed there were so many ``dancing about like live ingots of silver'' that
they had no trouble in catching more than 200lbs of sea trout and salmon in a
week as well as shooting gulls, pigeons and guillemots. They duly stuffed many
of their trophies and then set sail for home.
Their week, including fishing, food, accommodation, horse hire, boats and
copious quantities of Talisker came to a modest #14 and five shillings - for
four. Changed days indeed.
</TEXT>
