<HEADLINE>The all-American dream rolls ever on</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ANDI ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061118</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
EMMA Carrick-Anderson's American dream continued yesterday in the glories of
Winter Park, Colorado, when she won a NorAm giant slalom against top-class
opposition to make her best world-ranking points score of the season so far.
After a breathtaking first run, later described by coach Kurt Scherl as the
best run he has seen her ski since he started work with her three years ago,
she was an almost uncatchable 1.7 seconds in front. A safe second run allowed
her a one-second winning margin.
``This was Emma at her best. She skied like this in the summer in training and
now it looks like she might be able to convert this type of world-class
performance to race day,'' said Scherl yesterday.
With three top-ten results from her last three outings, Carrick-Anderson races
a short series of further NorAms and FIS races before returning to Europe later
this week to compete in the rescheduled World Cup races, at Lech in Austria.
Carrick-Anderson travelled yesterday to Loveland, where she added another
victory - in the NorAm slalom, by 1.5sec over the two runs, beating Katerine
Tichie, who is ranked in the world's top 15 in slalom.
ANDI ROBERTSON
SKIING
</TEXT>
