<HEADLINE>Rovers keep home run going</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061119</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SATURDAY was stalemate day in England, with those pools coupons draws that were
missing from the Scottish premier division popping up in the English
equivalent. Eight matches produced only two winners, in Blackburn Rovers and
the newly revived Manchester City.
Blackburn's ability to knock over domestic opposition at Ewood Park remains
unchanged.
Like Rangers, they have been found out in Europe, but unlike the Scottish
champions, they can do nothing right away from home, where their record is two
draws and three goals from eight matches.
West Ham were the latest to suffer at the ground that Jack (Walker) built, as
Alan Shearer collected his third hat trick in as many months there.
Gerry Creaney is becoming Manchester City's super-sub, heading another valuable
goal after having come on just before half-time at Leeds. That one won the
game, extending City's improved run to four wins and a draw in five matches.
Liverpool's fourth successive home defeat was on the cards at Anfield when Neil
Shipperley gave Southampton the lead on Saturday but Stan Collymore's first
goal since September prevented that ignominy.
Manchester United also were held at home, something they must have feared in
view of Chelsea's excellent record at Old Trafford. Alex Ferguson spoke of a
hoodoo after John Spencer, returning after injury, had set up Dennis Wise for
an opening goal that David Beckham eventually equalised.
Another former Ibrox striker, Mark Hateley, made his debut at last for Queen's
Park Rangers, adding useful aerial strength. Hateley had one header cleared off
the line and set up Alan McDonald's goal with another. In between,
Middlesbrough's Chris Morris had put the visitors ahead, and that, eventually,
was another drawn game.
So was the meeting of two high-fliers at Villa Park, David Platt scoring for
Arsenal against his old club before Dwight Yorke replied. And Nottingham
Forest, who take a 1-0 lead to Lyon in the UEFA Cup tomorrow, also finished
1-1, thanks to Colin Cooper's late effort at Bolton.
If there was a lack of goals and excitement in the Premiership, romance was
missing, too, from the FA Cup second round. Of the seven non-league clubs drawn
against Endsleigh League opposition, not one even managed to score.
The first division, meanwhile, remains as contrary as ever, three of the
erstwhile top four losing at home and the other, Leicester City, requiring a
last-minute equaliser to hold Barnsley. Leicester are confident of holding
manager Mark McGhee to his contract rather than allowing him to escape to
Wolves, who want him to replace Graham Taylor.
A Martin Scott penalty against Crystal Palace yesterday was enough for
Sunderland to jump up six places to join Millwall at the top of the
division.
STEVE TONGUE
IN ENGLAND
</TEXT>
