<HEADLINE>Official row may be settled tonight</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH DAN MACLENNAN</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061120</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Camanachd Association's Executive Council meet in Fort William tonight to
discuss the appointment of the game's first full-time official.
The meeting was called after the confirmation that the President, Duncan
Cameron of Glasgow, was to be one of the candidates, along with the current
part-time official Alister MacIntyre of Fort William.
The Association's past president, Ken Thomson, took over Cameron's duties in
supervising the selection process, which advanced as scheduled on Friday when a
short-leet was drawn up.
Mr Thomson will brief the executive tonight on the progress so far. He said:
``I will also be taking the opportunity to clarify certain matters and will put
proposals to the meeting which hopefully will ensure that we will be able to
appoint an official of the highest calibre.''
It is expected that details of the short-leet may be issued in advance of the
final selection meeting, which is due to be held on Friday.
With play in the national premier league due to resume again this weekend,
Kingussie emphasised once again that they are the team to beat against
first-division Lochaber in the Keyline MacAulay Cup, netting 13 times.
Kingussie now await the outcome of the replay between Fort William and
Newtonmore.
HUGH DAN MACLENNAN
SHINTY
</TEXT>
