<TEXT>
CRICKET:
SECOND TEST
MIKE Atherton jogged out to the National Anthem - and trudged back
seven-and-half-hours later with the sound of premature South African victory
songs ringing in his ears in Johannesburg yesterday.
England had asked for a recording of God Save Our Queen to be played in a bid
to lift their spirits when they took the field in the morning. But, it seems,
not even another undefeated innings from the captain will be enough to spare
this team from eventual defeat.
Atherton battled through 71 overs for 82 runs out of a total of 167 for four.
But South Africa's supporters were convinced last night that their side is
certain of victory provided Johannesburg's weather stays fair for one more day.
They need six more wickets, have another 90 overs in which to get them, and a
second Test that has been going against England since Atherton and manager Ray
Illingworth decided to field first, now is within Springbok reach.
So long as the captain remains, hope of a great escape is not lost. But it will
need the finest innings even he has played for his country plus long and loyal
support from Robin Smith - his last fully fledged batting partner - to keep
Allan Donald and his friends at bay.
Donald struck the final significant blow of day four by capturing his 100th
Test wicket when Graeme Hick made contact outside off stump to give keeper Dave
Richardson a straightforward catch. But the main damage was done by Brian
McMillan, who followed an unbeaten 100 by dismissing Alec Stewart and Mark
Ramprakash in the space of three deliveries.
England - set 479 to win (73 more than any country has made during a successful
fourth innings run chase throughout 120 years of Test cricket) - were making
encouraging progress at 75 for nought.
But then McMillan shattered an air of calm by uprooting Stewart's middle stump
as the vice-captain drove outside a long half-volley.
Suddenly, South African fans among a capacity crowd of 30,000 found their
voices again. Ramprakash's winter was resting on what happened next - and
everyone seemed to know it.
He survived an lbw appeal first ball but the next was a near carbon copy of
Stewart's . . . and it had the same devastating result. More devastating, in
all probability, from Ramprakash's point of view for it is hard to see how
England can stand by him after three consecutive Test failures this winter and
a long record of under-achievement.
Graham Thorpe, followed Atherton's lead, hanging around for two hours. But when
he missed a straight one from Meyrick Pringle to fall lbw and, soon after, Hick
gave Donald his milestone wicket, England were in sharp decline.
However, the captain refused to budge. Smith, who might have been run out after
having turned for a non-existant second, kept him company for 57 minutes to the
close but a mountain must still be climbed.
If they reach the top of it still in one piece their hosts could regret batting
on for so long.
South Africa had established an unassailable lead of 428 by the time they
accepted an offer for bad light on Saturday evening. It was as though they
wanted to make England suffer as long as possible.
