<HEADLINE>Dens men complete eventful week with a victory Bad start for Saints sees experience pay dividends</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>4</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061122</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
St Mirren 1, Dundee 2
DON'T bet against Dundee topping the first division tomorrow night with a
smash-and-grab act that was honed to an art form at the weekend.
Experience counted. Their ageing back four in particular know how to protect a
slender lead and keep three points.
When under the cosh - as they were for half-an-hour at Love Street - they dig
in, keep it tight. No-one does it better than 36-year-old player-manager Jim
Duffy. Somehow he managed to forget the boardroom wrangles and play with a
dogged determination that was frightening in its intensity and an inspiration
to his comrades.
``It's been a hard week,'' he said later, the master of understatement
following a Coca-Cola Cup final defeat and the proposed management takeover of
Dundee which hinges around him.
Even then his thoughts were of the players. ``They are fragile creatures
sometimes,'' he said.
But his counterpart Jimmy Bone was rattled. St Mirren were two down within 18
minutes, killing the game regardless of a spirited fightback which probably
merited at least a draw.
Bone conceded later: ``You can't give teams starts, especially good teams.''
Saints keeper Campbell Money, back for the first time since August after a
hernia operation, risked another rupture within two minutes when he had to pick
the ball out of the net.
The goal underlined the difference in the sides. Morten Wieghorst waltzed
through Saints' young defence, makeshift because of injuries. His shot was
palmed out by Money - to George Shaw, who scored from four yards. Wieghorst,
who had a fine game, later hit the woodwork with a 20-yard volley.
The goal put the fizz back in Dundee after the Coca-Cola flop. Paul Tosh netted
the second from 12 yards. There should have been a third via a super through
ball from Ian Anderson. But Shaw and Jim Hamilton, clear through, seemed to
question who should take control and Hamilton eventually shot weakly, straight
at the keeper.
But Saints rallied, with Martin Baker hitting the bar from 25 yards, in an
open, passing game which was also clean regardless of six bookings - including
two in bizarre circumstances. Hamilton was yellow carded for leaving the field
without permission, and his replacement Gerry Britton suffered the same fate
for going on too soon.
The antics were watched by Rangers' John Brown, who denied he was on a spying
mission. The former Dens Park player said he was there only ``to see old faces
. . . and there's none older than Jim Duffy's.''
Brown left with eight minutes to go, immune to the hurly-burly finish.
A change of referee at the start of the second half, because of a pulled
muscle, coincided with a change in mood. Saints now had grit. Front-runners
Barry Lavety and Mark Yardley gave the Duffys - Jim and Neil - a hard time.
Lavety got his reward in 69 minutes after the ball broke his way in the penalty
box from a splendid Brian Hetherston run from midfield.
Michel Pageaud then produced a series of remarkable saves. One fingertip stop
from Yardley in 77 minutes deserved the hyperbole from the manager later.
Dundee brought on Gary McKeown for the second half, his first game for 14
months after horrendous cruciate ligament damage. McKeown, who finally had an
operation in January and has faced daily hospital visits for the past seven
months, said: ``It's been a long road. At times I felt I would never play
again.
``For me, the season starts now.''
Duffy declined to talk about the #3m deal that would see Canadian millionaire
Ron Dixon leave and put the manager and Dundee vice-chairman Malcolm Reid in
control of the club.
Instead, he looked forward to tomorrow's home game with Dumbarton, and added
only: ``I cannot be unhappy after the week we have had. And we could be top of
the table on Tuesday.''
Bone was disappointed with the result, but remains optimistic. He expects soon
to have a full squad to choose from. Norrie McWhirter and Jamie Fullerton are
likely to play for the reserves on Wednesday.
``I was pleased with our approach to the game, and the injury list is clearing
up. That creates pressure for places, with the young ones in on merit,'' said
Bone.
Brian Hetherston, 19, in particular was ``breathtaking, exciting.'' He was also
booked on Saturday for dissent, although Bone claimed later it was a case of
mistaken identity, with Lavety to blame for speaking out of turn. ``I don't
know if they will use video evidence,'' joked Bone.
</TEXT>
