<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Sampras the hero</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061123</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
BATTLE-scarred Pete Sampras clinched the Davis Cup for the United States by
sinking Yevgeny Kafelnikov in straight sets in Moscow yesterday.
Sampras, urgently needing a quick victory because of a hamstring problem,
downed Kafelnikov 6-2, 6-4, 7-6, ending the final emphatically with an ace to
hand the Americans their first title since 1992.
It was the Wimbledon champion's third victory of the weekend, and gave the US
an insurmountable 3-1 lead in the best-of-five final, rendering meaningless the
final singles match between Jim Courier and Andrei Chesnokov.
Sampras, who was carried off court with cramp after beating Andrei Chesnokov in
a five-set thriller on Friday, was in ``ace'' form as he crushed the world No.6
in just more than two hours.
It was the Russians' second home defeat in an Olympic Stadium final in
successive years. A sometimes boisterous crowd of 14,000 had cheered them on
but they are now left still seeking their first cup.
The Russians had installed a red clay court last month especially to slow down
the powerful Sampras, whose record on clay is unspectacular.
But ``Pistol Pete'' had acted as if it were his favourite surface all weekend,
outlasting Chesnokov in a gruelling match on Friday that saw him collapse with
leg cramps, and then overwhelming the opposition in straight sets in Saturday's
doubles and yesterday's finale.
Sampras lost only four points in his first eight service games, reeling off 11
points in a row during one stretch of the second set as his cheering
team-mates, including Andre Agassi, were on their feet to cheer him on. He
survived the hamstring injury through a tense third set.
Sampras said later he had played his best clay-court tennis in beating
Kafelnikov.
Sampras paid tribute to captain Tom Gullikson. ``It is a great win for the team
and I am happy for Tom.''
He said he had thought during the match of Tim Gullikson who used to coach
Sampras until taken ill last year. ``It has been a tough year for both of us
dealing with Tim's situation,'' Sampras added.
Kafelnikov, mindful of Sampras' cramp attack, said he wanted to keep him on
court for as long as possible.
``I felt the third set was very important and if I had won it the match could
have gone the other way as Pete looked tired.''
DAVIS CUP FINAL
</TEXT>
