<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Coaching must be sensitive</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Correspondence</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061124</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
JIM Leishman's proposed project whereby full-time Livingston FC players will be
coaching in local primary schools seems an excellent initiative.
This valuable link between school and community can bring benefits to all
concerned, especially the pupils. Basic skills and techniques can be developed
and positive attitudes towards the sport encouraged, which hopefully will
motivate the youngsters to continue playing the sport.
However, adults coaching young performers must be aware that their charges are
not mini-adults performing under adult conditions and standards.
Coaching approaches must be sensitive to the needs of the developing child in a
number of areas.
Too many coaches and parents ignore, or are ignorant of, the mental, physical,
and technical factors which require to be considered when coaching and working
with young performers.
Playing sport should be a fun experience for young people, where enjoyment is
the first priority.
A desire to improve basic skills and techniques should develop through this
enjoyment. This can be achieved by adopting appropriate coaching styles and
methods which put enjoyment at the top of the coach's agenda.
The pressure of competition should be reduced and qualities of team play and
fair play emphasised. Adult pressure often leads to children developing a
negative attitude to sport, which often results in the child giving up sport.
I sincerely hope that those responsible for planning and managing the
Livingston FC initiative will ensure that the players working with the children
will be suitably prepared for this very responsible task.
The players concerned will also have to realise that they will become role
models, with the responsibility which this involves.
I hope that other sports clubs throughout Scotland will recognise the valuable
potential for this type of initiative in forging links which will benefit young
people in sport and the community.
Ian N Cosgrove,
Programme Co-ordinator,
BA Sport in the Community,
University of Strathclyde,
Faculty of Education,
Jordanhill Campus.
</TEXT>
