<DOCNO>GH951204-000132</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000132</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Shade of the rising Moon</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DEREK DOUGLAS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport in touch</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061125</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
A SEASONAL tale. There has been, so far, a marked absence of a bright light in
the heavens but this week three wise men will alight on these shores, not out
of the East but from the deep South.
There is a Moon among them, but no sign of a guiding star, and even though
Christmas is fast approaching, whether they will bring with them gold,
frankincense, and myrrh remains yet to be seen. The jury is out, too, on
whether or not they will be wise.
We are witnessing the first real, discernible signs of player power. In England
and Wales, the clubs have already rattled their corporate sabres and rattled,
too, the dovecots at Twickenham and Cardiff Arms Park. The premier English
clubs have formed their own limited company and you can bet your bottom dollar
that, once broadcast contracts come up for negotiation, they will be demanding
a much greater slice of the financial action.
Now, a new force is abroad in the land. RUPA, the Rugby Union Players'
Association, is about to set up shop, with Richard Moon, Peter Winterbottom,
and Bob Norster at the helm. They are due in Scotland this week, where Keith
Robertson, the former Melrose and Scotland threequarter, is keen to set up a
series of meetings.
The intention is that they will hold talks with SRU senior vice-president Fred
McLeod, the chairman of the premier clubs' association David Kilshaw, Gavin
Hastings in his Hastings International marketing mode, and Rob Wainwright,
Craig Chalmers, and Scott Hastings, the three player reps on the International
Players' Trust.
At the weekend, Moon - a lawyer, ex-Saracens, and brother of Rupert - was
declaring that RUPA were the only impartial operators ``out there''. Out there
being the brave new world of professional rugby where the wide-boys are even
now queueing up to carve out their pound of flesh.
``We are the only independent voice for the players,'' he says. Professional
footballers have their own trade union, if you like, with Tony Higgins in
charge in Scotland, so it was inevitable that as one of the apparent
accoutrements of the professional game, rugby should get one, too.
Hitherto, the view from Murrayfield might well have been one of consternation.
The natives are revolting, they might have said, but are, perhaps, less likely
to do so now. In any event, it is yet another file which will land with a thump
on the desk of director of rugby Jim Telfer.
Sometimes, before I lay me down of a night, I thank the Lord that I'm not Jim
Telfer. And sometimes I think that the good Lord must thank himself that he's
not Jim Telfer as well. Actually, I don't believe in the concept of a
metaphysical supreme being. But existentialism (and this I can state without
fear of contradiction, is a Herald Sport first) is another philosophical
doctrine altogether.
You knew this already, of course, but existentialists believe that people -
even rugby players - are moral free agents who must create values for
themselves through their own deeds and must accept the ultimate responsibility
for those actions in the seemingly meaningless universe.
Kenny Logan and I often while away an evening mulling over existentialism and
related philosophical doctrines. I have come to the conclusion that, as Supreme
Beings go, then in Scotland Jim Telfer is about as close as you can get without
crossing over to the other side.
Existentialist players as free agents in a post-Thatcherite free market? In my
book that's a recipe for chaos.
And let us, for a moment, return to reality. The word is that clubs have
started recruiting for next season already. The premiership is not yet over but
already the feelers are going out and a price if being levied on club loyalty.
Before very much longer we must have a properly thought out and regulated
transfer system in place. When can clubs approach players and how should the
approaches be made? Should there be transfer fees? If the answer is yes then is
there a role for agents? Will expatriates in England be given leave to play for
their districts in Scotland?
And, just what is myrrh anyway?
DEREK DOUGLAS
</TEXT>
</DOC>
