<HEADLINE>Lambie shaken as tide turns</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>HUGH McKINLAY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061126</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Falkirk 2, Raith Rovers 1
PAUL McGrillen has come through the pain game since joining Falkirk from
Motherwell last season. His cruciate injury was the one which halted his
progress, followed by a stress fracture which did not help his chance of an
early comeback.
After this match at Brockville - in which McGrillen scored both home goals -
Falkirk manager John Lambie had a stress fracture of the mind, while his Raith
Rovers counterpart was in a daze - the ``I cannot believe it'' syndrome.
Lambie's opening remark, as he searched for some tobacco relief, was: ``Ma
hert's still tickin'.'' This was followed by the thoughts of a man under the
type of pressure which had a couple of his contemporaries in the news recently.
``We were so bad in the first half - and we began it really well - that I was
desperate for the whistle to end it.'' The next question was obvious. ``Did you
have words with the players at half-time?''
Reply: ``I had to give them a rollicking. We were not competing. Raith Rovers
are good side, especially at creating movement.''
The rollicking seemed to work, while Raith lost their way. ``We were caught
sleeping for their winner,'' was all that a stunned Jimmy Nicholl could admit.
``We had so much of that game.''
Whereas Lambie had made his views clear to his players, Nicholl could only
admit: ``The way the players have been performing, I could say nothing to them.
That's our first defeat in five games, and they did little wrong.''
Now to McGrillen. ``It has been a frustrating six or seven months, but I feel I
am sharper now. Amazingly, my only three goals this season have been against
Raith - I scored the winner at Stark's Park.''
They were also the first goals conceded by Raith in five games - and two in
seven minutes at that, as first he fired home from close range after a
scramble, and then he took advantage of a fine run by Mo Johnston to touch home
a David Hagen knock-back.
The ``handful'' as described by Lambie - striker Ally Graham, to Raith
supporters - knocked home a fine equaliser. Even then, he needed two chances as
keeper Tony Parks blocked his first effort.
Around all the second-half mayhem that followed a disappointing first half in
which Raith were in command, the ball had paint on it several times as it hit
posts, crossbars, or even the stand roof - and on one occasion, it disappeared
into the night sky from a Raith clearance.
The final remark of Lambie said much: ``I don't want just a football team, I
want one with wee bit of devilment in it.''
The Brockville side's move up the premier division a couple of places might get
the message through to the players - and with the continuing battle of Lambie
to ``find a couple of fresh faces,'' the competition will hot up in the
dressing room as well as in the league.
</TEXT>
