<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aberdeen react swiftly to recurrence of on-field violence Skipper McKimmie pays price for Firhill elbowing incident</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN BROADLEY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>1</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061127</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ABERDEEN will fine captain Stewart McKimmie for the elbowing incident which
earned him a red card against Partick Thistle at Firhill.
Manager Roy Aitken broke off from yesterday's civic reception to honour the
Pittodrie club's Coca-Cola Cup triumph to reveal that disciplinary action will
be taken. McKimmie will be fined #500 for the offence which was blamed for the
Dons defeat.
But Aitken insisted: ``It was a very uncharacteristic thing for McKimmie to do
and obviously he will pay the price. He will be disciplined under our own code.
But it was a one-off from a player who is a very well-respected professional
within the game.
``There is no doubt that losing such a player after just nine minutes cost us
the game. The rest of the players battled very hard but the extra man Partick
Thistle had eventually told.''
McKimmie, the last link to Aberdeen's golden era of the last decade, was not
permitted to discuss the incident.
The Scotland star's gloom was forgotten as thousands of supporters turned out
in driving rain to line the streets of the city and celebrate the first cup
victory in five years.
All their Hampden heroes were aboard an open-top bus which took more than two
hours to reach the Town House through the packed streets.
Aitken added: ``This is the first time in my career that I have been able to go
among the supporters en masse after winning a competition. It is a very special
day for me and this club.
``It does not surprise me that so many of our fans turned out despite the
dreadful conditions. They have been invaluable to us over the last seven or
eight months and given our players a great lift. There is a real buzz in the
city nowadays and I'd like to thank them all for getting behind us.
``I just hope this is the first of many more days like this. But there is a lot
of hard work still to be done.''
q.AYR goalkeeper Cammy Duncan is recovering at home after a horrific accident
in which he swallowed his tongue. Duncan was hurt in a collision with David
Kennedy of Queen of the South during Ayr's 2-0 first-division victory on
Saturday.
The 30-year-old former Partick Thistle keeper swallowed his tongue in the
incident and it took prompt action by the Ayr physio John Kerr to save him.
``John pulled his tongue out as soon as he got to him and that probably saved
Cammy's life,'' said Ayr manager Gordon Dalziel.
``Our club doctor decided at the interval that although Cammy had played on, we
should not send him back      out.
``Instead he went to hospital to be checked out, because we do not want to take
a risk with his health.
``In the event we are all relieved that he got the go-ahead to return home and
to drink plenty of fluids over the next few days. We will keep a close watch on
him.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000135</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000135</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Parkhead men jolted from slumbers Killie strikes sting Celtic into action</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>IAN PAUL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061128</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Celtic 4, Kilmarnock 2
NOT being one of the natives, Pierre van Hooydonk may be unaware of Burns (the
bard, not the manager), but, after Celtic's remarkable recovery, he gave a
pretty accurate description of Rabbie's perception of what
happens to the best laid plans.
The Dutchman, scorer of two goals against the luckless Killie, explained that
he and his colleagues had talked before the game of getting a good start,
scoring early, and getting the crowd behind them.
``Then it went wrong, they scored, we couldn't get going, and nobody wanted
the
ball,'' he said, ``but after half-time everybody wanted the ball. That was
the
difference.''
Pierre is also beginning to understand the Scottish football critics'
mentality.
``I think it is quite usual in Scotland that when a foreigner first comes here
they look at his good points, but after a couple of weeks they must find
things
to criticise. But Andreas (Thom) and I can handle that.''
Thom, sitting beside his loquacious colleague, does not have the same command
of English but he was able to get across the message that the Parkhead team is
determined to keep Rangers    in their sights as the championship race
progresses.
Although van Hooydonk was the sponsors' man of the match, many of us thought
Thom had even greater influence on the day's events, while Tommy Burns
reckoned
Peter Grant was the outstanding player of the day.
The divergence of opinion might illustrate how well Celtic played later on but
for most of the first half they had looked like a team going through the
motions.
``I think we started nervously,'' was how Thom put it. He didn't explain why
but, whatever the cause, the Kilmarnock team soon sensed that they had a real
chance of delighting the bookies.
When Ally Mitchell scored their first goal, after Gordon Marshall had dropped
a
Tom Black cross, although he did seem to be impeded by Mitchell, the vast
majority of the 33,812 on site was reduced to mild annoyance but, when Tom
Brown headed in the second, there was something akin to apoplexy in the stands.
By then, Burns admitted, he was thinking up expletives in preparation for his
half-time dressing-room admonishment. He then had to pack them away for
another
day as his players conjured up two goals inside a minute, both of which
infuriated Killie manager Alex Totten, who could not believe his side would
collapse in such dramatic fashion.
Paul Wright was guilty of dithering when he lost the ball to Thom, although he
might have been fouled in the process, and the next moment the German had laid
the ball on the head of Grant.
There was virtually no time for the Ayrshire lot to regather as van Hooydonk
played the sweetest of passes to Thom, who took his time before hitting the
equaliser. The mugged had got up and belted the muggers.
There was really no way out for Killie then. Two goals up on Celtic at
Parkhead
and controlling the game, they will never have a better chance of making a
name for themselves.
Celtic, having come alive, then gave their supporters a treat, scoring two
more
goals, each by van Hooydonk.
The first was a well-worked 1-2 with Simon Donnelly and the second an easy
task
after brilliant play by Thom and John Collins.
The party was in full swing, with Celtic playing the knockabout game to such
effect that, on one occasion, they made more than 30 passes before Kilmarnock
intervened, and that was with a foul that earned Derek Anderson a booking.
``Without disrespect to Kilmarnock, we have to beat teams like them at home if
we are to keep in the championship,'' said van Hooydonk, who admitted that
before the season even began he had anticipated a two-horse race with Rangers.
That, in his view, is progress for Celtic. ``There is a hell of a difference
from last season, although we still have a lot to learn. But we are trying to
play football all the time.''
Burns thought Grant was ``immense'' but now has to think about picking a team
without him and John Hughes, as both are suspended for the next three matches.
Phil O'Donnell should be about ready to return by the weekend, however, to
slot
into the midfield, while he has plenty of options in the heart of defence,
with Rudi Vata or Malcolm Mackay ready to come in.
For Totten, the day that had begun so thrillingly ended in abject
disappointment. He left out Wright for the second half, although indicating it
was only because he wanted to try Colin McKee's pace up front, and he clearly
was very angry at the way the two goals were lost just before the break.
``There are times when you play football and times when you clear your
lines,''
he said. ``For more than 40 minutes Kilmarnock showed that they are as good
as
any team in the league but you can't give away goals like that. We laid it on
a plate for Celtic.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000136</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000136</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Samoans slump as Dawson shines out</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061129</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
MATT Dawson showed all the skills of the scrum-half art and moved nearer a
first cap by masterminding Midlands' 40-19 demolition of Western Samoa at
Leicester on Saturday.
England manager Jack Rowell and two other selectors watched Northampton's
Dawson play the game of his life and were left to compare his performance with
that of Kyran Bracken in the Test defeat by South Africa last month. They will
announce their verdict on the scrum-half place for the Test against Western
Samoa later this week.
Dawson, who was within a physio's diagnosis of a cap when Bracken was injured
on his debut two years ago, said: ``With that sort of game I am saying to the
selectors `here is what I can do'.
``If you like the way I play, I can do that job for England. I want to be
chosen on my merits.
``We go for variety at Northampton and it has been very successful in the
second division. But we still needed to prove to everybody that we could do it
against international opposition.''
Dawson linked up with club colleague and Midlands captain Tim Rodber. They
helped each other to a try each and provided the variety of different types of
kicks, breaks and service to the other backs.
Flanker Rodber, who admitted that he should have come off earlier in the
Springbok Test with his bruised arm, proved his fitness and renewed hunger, and
temporarily silenced criticism from former international colleagues.
``Dawson and Paul Grayson organised the whole thing and this was the way
England should play against Western Samoa at Twickenham,'' said Rodber.
``We united the best of the Northampton and Leicester styles and did everything
we wanted to.''
Western Samoa's tour is in trouble, despite their draw with Scotland and two
big midweek wins. Their Saturday side, bulging with Test players, has endured
two defeats.
The tourists' defence was easily opened up and their scrum conceded two penalty
tries as they were being shunted back over their own line.
Matt Allen scored Midlands' other try. Grayson kicked three penalties and three
conversions, and struck woodwork with two more.
The Pacific Islanders came late with tries from Mark Birtwistle, Too Vaega, and
Alex Telea, with a couple of conversions from Darren Kellett.
Meanwhile, in Cork, South African tourists Transvaal overcame the sending-off
in 56 minutes of tight-head prop Kapstok Van Greuning for punching to earn a
draw with reigning Irish provincial champions Munster in a cracking game.
The South Africans, beaten last week by Leinster in Dublin, clinched the tie
with an unconverted try in injury time from centre Christiaan Scholtz. Indeed,
they should have won, but full back Joe Gillingham missed the easy conversion.
Munster fly-half Paul Burke opened the scoring with a penalty after 13 minutes,
but two minutes later full back Joe Gillingham equalised with a similar effort.
Burke landed his second penalty after 28 minutes but Gillingham tied the scores
after 60 minutes with his second penalty.
The South African side then took the lead when right wing Ip van der Merwe
crossed for an unconverted try at the start of the final quarter.
But Munster hit back, Burke kicking his third penalty and then converting an
excellent try by lock Mike Coughlan to give Munster a 16-11 lead with six
minutes left, only for Scholtz to snatch the equalising try from a tapped
penalty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000137</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000137</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>South hopes are exiled in London</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>7</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061130</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Scottish Exiles Under-21s 24,
South of Scotland Under-21s 8
THE South of Scotland met an Exiles side at Richmond who proved to have too
much in the way of power and pace, and ultimately ran out convincing winners of
a match which came to life only in the second half.
The watching Scotland coach, David Leslie, was running the rule over Exile
captain and fly half McKee, and he must have been impressed with the Cardiff
Institute student's performance, which included three penalty goals and a
superb individual try.
The first of his kicks in the fifth minute opened the scoring, and while the
South backs impressed with their handling in tight spaces, solid Exile tackling
ensured the first South score came from the boot of Selkirk outside half Alan
Clark in the twenty-fourth minute. Of the busy Exile flankers, McIntosh
particularly shone as a stocky open side.
McKee added two further kicks either side of the half-hour, and the quiet first
half was brightened in 36 minutes when the powerful Renfrew shot through the
South's porous defence to send in right wing Reed for the try.
While the gloom at the Athletic ground deepened, a veil seemed to lift from the
players after the break and they resumed with heightened intent.
The Exiles worked full back Munroe outside the cover on the left only to see
him hauled down two yards short. From the lineout, a ruck formed infield and
McKee burst down a broad blind-side corridor to round the defence and score.
Feeling the pressure of time, the South threequarters took to the wide open
spaces but it was 25 minutes into the half before the South finally linked a
set of drives with some quick handling and with the Exiles stretched, Kelso
scrum half Graham Cowe shot away from a ruck and scuttled 20 metres to score.
Three minutes later the Exiles rounded off the scoring as Sale centre Farrow
chipped through and Renfrew scored a deserved try in the corner.
