<HEADLINE>`Sudden' can have rivals in a spin</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>WHITE and GOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>8</PAGE>
<FLAG>SPORT</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061131</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SUDDEN Spin, a useful horse to have in a lowly grade, can show the benefit of
his recent reappearance at Uttoxeter by winning the Gorebridge Conditional
Jockeys' Handicap Hurdle for Steve Norton today at Edinburgh.
A fair performer on the Flat for Jack Berry a couple of years ago, Sudden Spin
showed little promise during his first season over hurdles for Vivien Aconley.
But he appears to have strengthened since his arrival at Norton's Barnsley
stable, which is reflected by an upturn in his fortunes.
On his reappearance over hurdles last term, he produced a gutsy effort to win a
seller at Catterick, and was far from disgraced back there in a similar event
next time out.
Once again at Catterick, he regained the winning thread in selling company with
a four-length defeat of Friendly Knight.
His successes have not been restricted to the National Hunt side of the sport,
with three victories on the all-weather in 1995, the last being when landing a
handicap over a mile and a furlong at Wolverhampton.
His return to action over jumps at Uttoxeter gave every indication that he is
primed for another victory.
This time lining up for a non-selling event, he still had a firm hold of his
bridle when moving up to challenge with two flights remaining but could do no
more from soon after, going down by three-and-a-half lengths to Elflaa.
That run will have put him straight and Sudden Spin is napped to go one better.
The Stan Mellor-trained Bone Setter has shown fair form in his first season
over fences and is taken to win the Stokesay Novices' Chase at Ludlow.
</TEXT>
