<HEADLINE>Premiership place beckoning for steady Glenrothes</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061132</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TENNENTS NATIONAL LEAGUE ROUND-UP
GLENROTHES stay targeted for the Premiership with a 38-16 home win over lowly
Dunfermline. An even first half saw them 8-6 ahead with the try coming in just
22 seconds from winger Jonathan Goldie. With the advantage of the slope, Ralph
Henderson, Brian Delorey, and Andy Grieve touched down before young Goldie
scored again - his seventeenth try of the season.
With Hillhead/Jordanhill going under 16-12 at Portobello, Stewartry go clear in
second place. A try from Den Smith, converted by Alan Freeman, gave Portobello
a 13-3 half-time lead. In last week's defeat, Hills missed many penalties - on
Saturday they ran them instead, to no greater effect.
A converted try from Trinity's Gordon Miller tied the score at Stewartry on
22-22 with five minutes left. However, an unconverted try from Davie Fulton,
added to those from Sandy Craig and Jimmy McGill, won it for the home side.
East Kilbride stay top of Division Two thanks to a comprehensive 56-8 win in
the Lanarkshire derby at Dalziel. Aberdeen GSFP maintain thir second place
after living dangerously at bottom club Howe of Fife. Two penalties from Brian
Simmons from four excursions into the Howe half gave Grammar FPs the interval
lead. With two minutes left Howe's flanker Mike Black scored but Robbie
Gilmour's conversion faded away.
Cambuslang lie third, coming back from a 10-8 interval deficit to beat
Perthshire 11-10. Alan Stark for Cambus and Gavin Brown were the try scorers
but two Iain Thomson penalties made the difference.
Hutchesons'/Aloysians pulled away from Livingston with a scrappy 19-9 win at
Auldhouse. A tremendous run by lock John MacDonald set up Paolo Bardelli's
early try. Euan Baillie's was a late gift.
Third-division table-toppers Berwick won 27-14 at Cumbernauld and are now the
only unbeaten National League side.
Allan Glen's won 30-10 at lowly Highland thanks to tries from Chris Hughes, Jim
McParland, and Alistair Robertson. Taking advantage of Cartha QP's home slip,
they move into second place.
Two tries from Gary Grant gave Cartha a 15-12 lead over Alloa after 45 minutes.
Alan Imrie's try put Alloa ahead again and despite Grant's being twice over the
line, they held on for a 19-15 success.
Early tries from Alaister Graham, Stuart Williamson, and Mark Hollis sent Annan
to an eight-try 51-3 home win over Division Four leaders Lismore, allowing
Clydebank to take over the top spot, courtesy of a 29-0 win at Falkirk.
q ENGLAND'S new hooker Mark Regan faces an anxious wait before discovering
whether he will be cleared to face Western Samoa at Twickenham on Saturday week
after collecting his second yellow card of the season on Saturday.
Bristol forward Regan was cautioned by London referee Ray Merloo for an
off-the-ball challenge on Moseley centre Bob Massey.
However, as Gloucestershire's disciplinary committee have a backlog of cases,
his hearing is unlikely to take place before the international.
Regan, who won his first cap against South Africa two weeks ago, received his
first yellow card in the Courage League One game against Saracens in September.
England's team for the Western Samoan international will be announced on
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
