<HEADLINE>Stirling turn on the style</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>BILL SUTHERLAND</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061133</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SECOND DIVISION
KEVIN Drinkell was understandably happy on Saturday as his Stirling Albion team
strolled to a 4-1 home win over Forfar. ``That was the best I've seen them play
for a while,'' he observed.
Albion not only entertained the crowd - they are probably the best footballing
team in the division, although still six points behind East Fife - but had
goals to show for it, too.
``We used the width of the pitch well,'' Drinkell reflected, and even excused
the loss of a soft late goal to Mark Bowes as demonstrating that Albion try to
avoid negative play.
Within half-an-hour, a David Woods cross provided Ian McInnes, quickly followed
by Steve McCormick converting an Alex Bone cut-back. On the hour, Ronnie
McQuilter tapped in from a corner before McCormick rounded the keeper for the
fourth.
A Mark Donaghy shot almost on half-time was enough to end East Fife's four-game
winless home run at the expense of Berwick.
Miller Mathieson struck twice and made one for Gareth Hutchison in
Stenhousemuir's 4-1 win at Montrose, while goals by Mark Smith and Tommy Steele
gave Ayr their second straight home win and let them leapfrog over visitors,
Queen of the South.
Stranraer and Clyde, unsurprisingly, finished goalless at Stair Park.
</TEXT>
