<HEADLINE>Taylor aims to make his mark</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>12</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061134</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA captain and opener Mark Taylor survived a torrid spell by Pakistan
leg-spinner Mushtaq Ahmed in Sydney yesterday to leave the third and final Test
evenly balanced as the home side chased 247 runs for victory.
Taylor remained unbeaten on 49 after Australia had lost two early wickets in
their second innings.
At the close on the fourth day, Australia were 121 for three, needing another
126 runs to complete a clean sweep of the series. The hosts scored 257 in their
first innings in reply to Pakistan's 299.
The tourists, who relied almost entirely on a spin attack of Mushtaq and
off-spinner Saqlain Mushtaq, made a breakthrough just before yesterday's close
when captain and fast bowler Wasim Akram had Mark Waugh caught behind by Rashid
Latif.
The tourists, seeking to restore morale after heavy defeats in the first two
Tests, were jubilant at Waugh's dismissal for 34 after having wasted several
chances to take a firmer grip on the match.
Even with seven wickets in hand, Australia must contend with a pitch offering
significant turn and uneven bounce for the spinners in today's run chase.
Pakistan lost their last five wickets for just 19 runs yesterday to slump to
204 all out in their second innings.
In reply, Mushtaq's one success came in his sixth over when he trapped opener
Michael Slater for 23 with the total on 42. Slater did not play a shot on the
back foot and was struck on the pads by a ball that moved back from outside his
off-stump.
David Boon fell to Saqlain for six when the ball deflected off the back of his
bat to give substitute fielder, Moin Khan, a catch at silly point.
Earlier in the day, fast bowler Craig McDermott had taken five for 49, his best
Test performance in Sydney, as Pakistan struggled for runs after resuming on
101 for four.
Inzamam-ul-Haq, batting at No.6 because of a shoulder injury sustained while
fielding, scored 59 before becoming one of McDermott's victims.
AUSTRALIA V PAKISTAN
</TEXT>
