<HEADLINE>McKimmie sending-off opens the door for a Thistle revival</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>JIM REYNOLDS</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061135</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Partick Thistle 1, Aberdeen 0
WHAT a difference a week makes in football. At Hampden last Sunday, there was
Stewart McKimmie hoisting aloft the Coca-Cola Cup to signal Aberdeen's first
trophy win in five years and his own first triumph as club captain.
Those good people from the north, who have to travel further and spend more
than anyone else to follow their team, had every right to expect the dawning of
a new era.
Yet, on Saturday, on a return visit to Glasgow, McKimmie put in what was
probably his shortest-ever working shift.
He was sent off after just nine minutes at Firhill for elbowing Partick
Thistle's Callum Milne in the face, leaving a depleted side to battle uphill
for the rest of the afternoon.
The cup was paraded up Union Street in fine style yesterday, as a gesture of
thanks to the Aberdeen fans, but a more fitting thank-you would probably have
been a more responsible attitude from the club captain at Firhill - a rash
youth he is not - and three much-needed premier division points.
Manager Roy Aitken, who has done such a marvellous job in his short spell in
charge, left nobody in any doubt as to who was to blame for the defeat.
``The bottom line is that the sending off cost us the match,'' he said. ``You
spend 20 minutes in the dressing-room before the match talking about the shape
of the side, then within 10 minutes of the start you've got to change it.''
Thistle, much maligned in recent weeks, took full advantage of having an extra
man.
They had, in fact, started the match in a bright, eager mood which belied
current form, and when referee Martin Clark sent McKimmie packing, the Firhill
side really took a grip on things.
Their control in the midfield - the fact that Eoin Jess was carrying a groin
strain certainly didn't help Aberdeen - allowed defenders breathing space and
what followed was a thoroughly professional, and at times entertaining,
performance from Thistle.
Towards the end of the match, they even had a bit of a swagger about them, a
kind of arrogance which comes only through extreme confidence.
Thistle could have won more comfortably. Indeed, before Tom Smith headed the
only goal of the match from an Andy Gibson cross in 63 minutes, they had
squandered several better chances.
Said Smith, a product of Thistle's youth policy: ``I was delighted to score,
because just before that I had put two good chances past. When Andy's cross
came over I was determined to get my header on target.''
The previous week, Thistle were jeered for their performance against Raith
Rovers, but even their fiercest critic could only have admiration for them
after this showing.
in a side which didn't have a weakness, special mention must go to Milne, who
won the man of the match award.
On Saturday, he played his fourth match in eight days, and he was still going
strong at the finish.
Said Thistle manager Murdo MacLeod: ``We had a long chat after the Raith Rovers
match, and I'm delighted at the response. We can take a lot of confidence from
that performance.''
</TEXT>
