<HEADLINE>Tough times for 'Well</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>DOUGLAS CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<GRAPHIC>Photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061137</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Motherwell 0, Hibernian 2
THE mood was as dark as the evening when the ball stopped rolling at Fir Park
on Saturday. These are indeed trying times for those connected with Motherwell.
The club has been successful in just one match in their past 11, and, following
this latest defeat, they are now keeping Kilmarnock company at the wrong end of
the premier division. Things can only improve.
When another Keith Wright header struck the back of the home net, it appeared
as though a signal had been given for home sections of the ground to be
evacuated, and as referee Louis Thow's whistle pierced the chill evening air
after 90 minutes there were few Motherwell fans remaining. Those still seated
hollered their disgust at the situation now enveloping the club.
As journalists mingled at the main entrance at Fir Park, words like ``crisis''
and ``critical'' could be heard, but before such a scenario is entered into a
few facts should be taken on board.
Had it not been for the agility of Hibs' keeper Jim Leighton, and if the home
strikers had had a smattering of good fortune, then all three points would not
have been lost.
In similar circumstances, some managers have been known to disappear into the
night. However, Alex McLeish, thankfully, is not such an individual.
The Motherwell manager chatted quietly about the day's proceedings and his
club's situation, and there was an air of determination about the man, a
feeling that all will be well when it matters. We'll see.
``And so it continues,'' said the big man, of his club's recent run of poor
form. ``We showed Hibs too much respect, especially in the second half,'' said
the manager.
``It is the little things that are costing us dearly. There is nothing major,
apart from the fact that we have a lot of experienced players out. If we are
not scoring, we have to keep the door shut at the other end, and we are not
doing that.''
On the subject of injuries, McLeish did not use that matter as an ``excuse''
but admitted his club's playing resources were being ``severely tested.''
However, if Motherwell's lot was not a happy one, Keith Wright exited
Lanarkshire with a large smile on his face. He opened the scoring after 51
minutes following fine work by Michael O'Neill and the Irishman again was
Wright's supplier for the concluding goal in 77 minutes.
On the negative side for Hibs, they will go about their business without
O'Neill, who must kick his heels in the stand for the next three matches
because of SFA suspension.
Life could hardly become more negative for Motherwell and, with Aberdeen and
Rangers to be faced before Christmas, it probably feels to the Motherwell
people they have perpetrated a grievous mischief in another life and are now
being repaid.
With the wealth of experience and gifted individuals on the Fir Park payroll,
matters such as being in the wrong place in the league should soon surely take
a turn for the better. Mind you, that was said of Dundee United last season,
and look what happened to them. Who would be a Motherwell fan these days?
</TEXT>
