<HEADLINE>Home knowledge vital</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>MIKE HAGGERTY</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061139</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SCULLERS Kevin Plank and Willie Brown used their knowledge of the twists and
turns of the river around Stirling to full advantage as they won yesterday's
Head of the Forth, seven seconds ahead of Clydesdale.
They were followed by lightweights Joe Kelly and Mark Hely.
The Castle Semple double of Allan Watt and Peter Murray slipped down the
rankings, crashing from bank to bank on the five-kilometre course.
Nithsdale's junior four came home ahead of their rivals from George Heriot's to
take that division, while the junior women from the Dumfries club were also
victorious. In the women's small boats events, George Watson's dominated,
taking the double and the pairs events, while Inverness won the women's senior
restricted fours division, ahead of Strathclyde University.
St Andrews University provided the fastest men's novice four of the day, while
Stirling University emerged winners of the women's novice              category.
MIKE HAGGERTY
ROWING
</TEXT>
