<HEADLINE>Watters waits for winner</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Bill Sutherland</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>3</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061140</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THIRD DIVISION
THE name of Willie Watters was familiar to John Brogan in his time in charge of
Stirling Albion. Usually it was a chant from the crowd, urging him to bring the
striker on from the bench. On Saturday, the Arbroath manager had reason to be
grateful to the same Watters, writes Bill Sutherland.
The striker was expected to join Arbroath when he refused re-signing terms at
Stirling in the summer. Alloa seemed to have picked him up, only for Watters to
walk out and be reunited with Brogan at Gayfield.
On Saturday Watters popped up in the final minute to convert a Lee Gardiner
pass and seal a 2-1 home win over Cowdenbeath that let Arbroath leapfrog over
their visitors to within three points of second place. Arbroath's trialist - by
coincidence, Michael Watters - had opened the scoring, while a wind-assisted
lob by Martin Humphreys had levelled.
Livingston failed for a third time to score at their new home - the crowd this
time was 3444 - but as the visitors were second-placed Ross County, the gap at
the top remains seven points. Caley Thistle missed chances and had to settle
for a 1-1 draw at home to East Stirlingshire but Brechin fared even worse,
falling to a lob by Albion Rovers' Andy Willock.
Alloa had the better of the goalless draw at home to Queen's Park.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000148</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000148</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Weah strike takes Milan clear in Italy</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>2</PAGE>
<FLAG>sport</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061141</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
LIBERIAN striker George Weah showed his lethal finishing touch with a late
winner for AC Milan in their 1-0 win against Lazio yesterday in Rome, as the
league leaders opened up a four-point gap in Serie A.
But champions Juventus, inspired by a Gianluca Vialli hat trick in a 5-0
humiliation of local rivals Torino, have not given up the title hunt.
Weah, whose goals have transformed Milan's strike-rate this season, rounded off
a counterattack three minutes from time to make amends for a series of missed
chances in the first half.
Milan now top the table with 27 points from 12 matches, four ahead of Parma,
who owed their 1-1 draw at Napoli to Gianfranco Zola's second-half penalty
against his old club.
Fausto Pizzi had given the Neapolitans the lead after 38 minutes after the home
side had twice hit the woodwork.
Fiorentina moved into third place on 22 points, one behind behind Parma, after
Gabriel Batistuta's goal earned them a last-gasp win at Padova.
The Florence club were joined by newly promoted Atalanta, who notched up their
fourth successive win, 3-1 over Vicenza, with two goals from Sandro Tovalieri.
Internazionale continued their rehabilitation under English coach Roy Hodgson,
recovering from the third-minute dismissal of Gianluca Festa to defeat
Cremonese 2-0 with goals from Javier Zanetti and Maurizio Ganz.
Enrico Chiesa claimed his first hat trick as Sampdoria defeated Bari 3-1 for
their first away win of the season.
Another last-minute goal, this time from Abel Balbo, earned Roma a 1-1 draw at
his old club Udinese.
IN EUROPE
</TEXT>
</DOC>
