<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rolling back abortion rights</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ros Davidson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061232</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Pro-lifers in America will score a major success if Congress votes to ban an
abortion procedure, reports Ros Davidson
AS debate over America's abortion policy escalates once again, an infant whose
mother was at the centre of one of the most disturbing incidents in the battle
will soon be one year old.
On Capitol Hill the US Senate is about to consider an unprecedented ban on a
rare type of abortion sometimes performed late in pregnancy. Debate about
whether to make the so-called ``dilation and extraction'' method a federal
crime is expected today, with a final vote - which lobbyists predict could be
extremely close - as soon as Wednesday.
Meanwhile in Nebraska a child born as Americans readied to celebrate Christmas
last year will have his or her first birthday on Friday. The mother of the
baby, whose name and gender are not being publicised, was an unwed teenager
whom town officials held in custody until she agreed to have the child and not
an abortion. They objected that she had an appointment later that week at a
local clinic. The procedure would have been legal and with her parents' consent.
In a tale that seems out of the Dark Ages, 15-year-old Ruby Scott was held
against her will by a posse of local sheriff's deputies, her high-school
boyfriend and his family and other officials acting as vigilantes in the
isolated Nebraska town of Blair. The girl had just discovered she was 23 weeks
pregnant, apparently as she had always had irregular periods.
The scene that unfolded on a quiet street in the small, conservative community
as the pregnant youngster was taken from her family was hardly biblical. The
Scotts, already in hiding at a cousin's house after being assaulted on their
own doorstep, awoke to find themselves surrounded by more than 10 police cars
containing armed lawmen. That is according to a civil lawsuit filed on behalf
of the family.
The pregnant teenager, her father Bud, who is a truck driver, and her mother
Connie, had long-term ties to the area and had been law-abiding people, says
their lawyer Janelle Kleveland. But they did have an appointment at the local
clinic, where Ruby would have had a day and a half of counselling before
agreeing to a termination.
The girl was arrested and held overnight at the local jail house, while that
night town buildings were plastered with posters calling the Scotts ``baby
murderers''. The next day the girl was placed in what was called foster care
and interrogated alone, although she was a minor, by the county attorney. And
within a day a judge ordered the girl released on condition there would be no
abortion - unless ordered by the court.
Two local doctors, apparently ``pro-life'' in their sympathies, even stated in
writing that the procedure might harm the young woman, although they had not
examined her and were not basing their opinions on her history, says attorney
Kleveland, whose complaint is backed by the American Civil Liberties Union in
New York.
Not surprisingly, Ruby and her parents, who had no legal representation, agreed
she would not have an abortion. Yet when the youngster tried returning to high
school afterwards she was so harassed and threatened she had to be tutored at
home. And four months ago the family moved to another town within Nebraska.
Emotions in Blair still run high. The day the lawsuit was filed the Scotts' old
home was vandalised. Even so, the case is unprecedented even in the small
conservative community, on the Missouri River in the American heartland. ``No
other case quite like it has ever gone to court in the US,'' says Kleveland.
``(Ruby) does not want this kind of thing ever to happen to anyone again,'' she
said.
The fight against legal abortion - or ``pro-life movement'' - has already made
inroads in Washington. Last month the House of Representatives banned the
procedure about to be debated again in the US Senate. Supporters and opponents
alike described it as a first move in rolling back abortion rights, protected
since a landmark US Supreme Court decision.
``I think this is a step forward in the battle to protect the unborn in this
country,'' said the Bill's sponsor, Congressman Charles Canady, after an hour
of emotional debate. The procedure at issue in the Bill, ``D&amp;E'', is performed
on perhaps 450 women yearly, often because the foetus is tragically deformed or
the mother's life at risk.
But during the debate the technique was dubbed ``partial birth'' and an ``ugly
reality'' of the abortion business. Drawings unveiled on the house floor, said
to depict the procedure, were gruesome - and apparently inaccurate. And one
congressman long known for opposing abortion, Henry Hyde, commented: ``It is
too cruel, (more suited) to Dr Joseph Mengele or Dr Kervorkian.''
The vote also marked a change in strategy. Republican Christopher Smith, a
leading supporter of the Bill, said anti-abortion law-makers would ``begin to
focus on the (abortion) methods and declare them to be illegal''.
America's abortion rate is higher than in any other developed country. And
although numerous opinion polls suggest most do want abortion available under
certain conditions, opposition is extremely vocal - and sometimes violent. Of
the 1.5 million abortions performed yearly in the US, an estimated 13,000 are
after 4!s months and 600 in the third trimester or after 26 weeks.
If the US Senate follows suit and outlaws the procedure, it would be the first
time the US Congress has voted to ban a specific medical procedure. Under the
Bill, doctors could be jailed for two years and fined up to $250,000. It would
also be a startling measure of the success of the agenda promoted on Capitol
Hill by fundamentalist Christians and conservatives so prominently over the
past year.
Although President Bill Clinton says he will veto the Bill on constitutional
grounds, lobbyists for reproductive rights fear that it is merely a first step
in dismantling access to abortion.
In other legislation currently pending in congress, government payment for
abortions would be denied for poor women except in cases of rape, incest, or
risk to the mother's life. Federal employees would not have abortion covered by
health benefits. And abortions would be explicitly banned at US military bases
overseas.
</TEXT>
