<DOCID>GH951204-000153</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Chamber Group of Scotland, Concert Hall, University of Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Michael Tumelty</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061233</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WHATEVER developments and transformations of style his music had been through
over the past 35 years, the great Polish composer Krzysztof Penderecki has not
lost his teeth. In his early days, his was the most searing, abrasive music
that could be heard. Subsequently, over several decades, his music began to
take a romantic, expressive turn.
On Saturday, following the conferment of an honorary degree of doctor of music
on the legendary Pole by the University of Glasgow, the Chamber Group of
Scotland gave the UK premieres of two of his recent chamber works, pieces which
revealed the composer's absolute mastery of style and technique.
The String Trio, from 1991, opened like the Penderecki of old, with a machine
gun-like series of explosive chords, fired off with tight, abrasive attack.
These acted as a sort of framing device for a set of highly expressive solos,
beautifully played by violist Carolyn Sparey-Gillies, cellist Robert Irvine,
and violinist Ruth Crouch. With scurries into the shadows, and very fast,
bristling music leading into a more traditional, driving finale, this was
classic, breathtaking Penderecki. Clarinettist Lawrence Gill joined the trio in
a mesmeric performance of the 1993 Clarinet Quartet, a stunningly beautiful and
rather elliptical work whose evocative and melancholy lyricism, especially in
its haunting finale, where the music ended in a halo of suspended sound, was
suggestive of Shostakovich.
</TEXT>
