<DOCNO>GH951204-000154</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000154</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>West End Gala Evening, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Harry Magee</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061234</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
WOW, what a knock-out show. The explosion of rapturous applause that greeted
the finale to this tour of hits from musicals must have been heard halfway down
Buchanan Street.
A West End Gala evening was the bill, presenting a quartet of singers who have
all starred in a clutch of recent major stage productions ranging through Miss
Saigon and Phantom of the Opera to Les Miserables. And in support none other
than our very own Royal SNO under the baton of a singularly urbane Martin Yates.
This was a performance that genuinely lived up to its title. It had everything
- snappy introductions from Martin Yates, soft-coloured lighting with a wisp of
smokiness, slick entrances, three changes of outfit for the ladies, silky
playing from the orchestra and, best of all, it had four voices that really
knew how to sell a song.
Ethan Freeman got the biggest reception in the first half for his dramatically
powerful duet Phantom of the Opera with Katrina Murphy. And with the aid of
mega-amplification mikes, the spectre of the notorious concert hall acoustic
was well and truly blasted away.
The two ladies sounded as good as they looked, Katrina Murphy having the purer
sound but Kim Criswell taking the edge in expressiveness.
Graham Bickley was up against strong competition here, but still managed some
powerful crescendos.
Power was the catchword and, in a stunning One Day More, orchestra and singers
combined to go out in a roof-raiser that could be followed only by encoring it
all over again.
</TEXT>
