<DOCNO>GH951204-000155</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000155</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Try loving your nation, Daphne</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ruth Wishart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061235</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Conservative councillor was being interviewed on the airwaves the morning
after the launch of the Constitutional Convention's parliamentary blueprint.
Riveting stuff it was too. For was she not able to tell the nation to the penny
what a Scottish parliament would cost the average shop assistant in tax
increases? This is truly impressive. Before the next election has even taken
place, before there is any change of government, before the drafting or passage
of a Scotland Bill, before the election of a single member of Scotland's new
legislature, before the make-up of its ruling administration is known, before
any debate has even begun on its budgetary options, Councillor Daphne Sleigh
just knows that the parliament will instantly employ its reserve powers to vary
income tax.
Moreover, since we must presume she knows these reserve powers cannot be
employed without consulting the electorate, she has been able to conclude this
will happen and the people will say yes please.
Councillor Sleigh, such are her quite remarkable powers of prediction, even
knows the result of the subsequent vote on the proposal, how much the tax will
rise by, and has intimate knowledge of the normal contents of Senga
McCafferty's take-home pay from Boots.
Truly this is a woman whose talents have been squaundered on the modest stage
of local government in Edinburgh. Surely a woman of such remarkable certainties
should be sitting on Chancellor Clarke's right hand announcing with equal
facility the likely percentage growth of the UK economy, the level of the
public-sector borrowing requirement until the millennium, and the projected
inflation rate for the tax year 1996/97. And this is not the kind of input Mr
Clarke could readily scorn, given that he got that particular set of statistics
entirely wrong in his previous Budget.
Of course there could be another explanation for Daphne's fiscal fluency. It
may be that she is not quite the mathematical mystic Meg her broadcast
suggests. It may be that her startling prescience has more mundane origins. It
may be that Mr Forsyth and his growing army of streetwise aparatchiks (morning,
Brian, Hi, Gerald) has concluded that the only tactics left are the scare
variety. So they have quickly concocted on the back of some handy envelopes the
kind of sums they hope will frighten the pants off the average Scottish
taxpayer. The strategy, after all, has a very reasonable track record. Back in
1979 the same horror stories were relentlessly circulated. And the fact that
the modest Assembly then proposed had no revenue-raising powers didn't prevent
Mr Forsyth's predecessors from predicting it would all end in financial tears.
The sheer beauty of having every Tory spokesperson sing off the same hymn sheet
about tartan taxes and the like is that since the figures are entirely made up
and wholly spurious nobody can actually contradict them. Shrewd eh? And of
course there is the general rule of thumb that if you repeat something often
and loudly enough some people will think you're telling the truth.
But what is so depressing about this orchestrated vilification of a Scottish
parliament is that the debate is being conducted solely on cost. What does it
say about your view of the Scottish people if all you think they give a damn
about is the thickness of your wallet?
The Rev.Bob Waters of the Congregational Church of Scotland has taken a lot of
stick over the past few days because his speech likened Scotland's union with
England to being married to a money-grubbing, unprincipled prostitute.
I doubt he really intended gratuitously to insult individual friends and
neighbours. I suspect his comments were intended for a culture of government
which made the acquisition of personal wealth the only goal which matters. An
ethos which didn't just suggest there was no such thing as society but
undermined the efforts of voluntary and civic bodies which believe that
individually and collectively we have a responsibility to each other.
Many millions of people all over the UK share the view that the agenda has to
change in pursuit of shared public goals. Indeed many Tories of what used to be
called the one-nation tendency are profoundly unhappy at the party of their
choice being hijacked by the wild-eyed right. So as another preacher man said
last week, loving our own nation doesn't mean lacking respect for others.
But loving our own nation is what this debate should be about. Hell mend all
these prophets of doom, let's clear space for the prophets of democracy. Let's
listen to the unsung heroes and heroines who devoted years to keeping the flame
of Scotland's parliamentary ambitions alive.
People not exercised by tax rates but genuinely enthralled by the opportunity
to shape a new style of politics which might not be adversarial for the sake of
it.
Thrilled at the possibilities of a new voting system actually giving the
electors what they asked for in terms of party representation. Mesmerised by
the thought of starting a new chapter with a level of gender equality about
which Westminister women can only dream.
Of course we don't all share the same ambitions. Some of us are natural
federalists, some determined on independence, some content with partial
devolution. But surely we can agree that a Scottish parliament will better
reflect democracy. Surely we can share genuine excitement at creating something
to reinforce our culture and heritage. Put away your purse Daphne. Loosen your
stays. Listen to your instincts.
Risk a moment of passion about your country. They can't touch you for it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000156</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000156</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The devil you know</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Geoffrey Parkhouse</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>inside politics</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061236</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
SO now we know. Mr Major has a maximum of 18 months left to him to turn round
the woeful situation of the Tories. He has this time - signposted by the
``neutral'' Budget - only if he gets lucky and there are no more by-elections
or defections.
At any time now he could find himself in minority Government and subject to a
lethal confidence motion providing Mr Blair with an earlier springboard to
No.10. Mr Major has gone for the long gamble that he can pay off enough debt
and cut state spending sufficiently to deliver a 20p standard tax rate next
autumn.
As the latest, post-Budget, opinion poll (NOP/Sunday Times) indicates that even
more people (71%) distrust him on tax, Tory MPs were becoming even more
fatalistic about their chances. Naturally, most of them, like Mr Heseltine,
state in public that another election win is possible. In private the mood is
very different.
There are three varieties of Tory opinion which, if anything, have hardened
since the Chancellor eschewed a ``go-for-broke'' Budget presaging an election
next year. There are those who believe that after 16 years in power they are
doomed to a real licking, giving Mr Blair a majority in the hundreds. Others
believe that in defeat, Mr Blair's first Government majority will be contained
to 40-80.
The third segment expect defeat, but find reason to hope that the next Labour
Government will have a majority of about only 25. Only 25? - five times greater
than Major's majority now. This is plenty for a normal five-year Parliament;
the element of Tory hope here is that 25 would not be enough for two
Parliaments, or three.
For balance, let me add a fourth strand of opinion which also crops up in
conversation with both Tory and Labour MPs. This provides a scenario in which
Mr Major is able, over the next 18 months (May 22, 1997, is the last deadline
for a General Election), to restore the desperately illusive ``feel-good''
factor. Then the electorate, unable to define the difference between two
conservative parties, will endorse the devil it knows.
This possibility is emphasised by a few Labour MPs who are disconsolate at
their party's lurch to the capitalist right, its low taxation, and
affordable-only state spending policy. They wonder if the voters will think it
worth handing the palm to Labour. It will be interesting to see how many Labour
back benchers defy Mr Blair's abstention order on Tuesday night and vote
against Mr Clarke's 1p cut in the standard rate.
For such Labour fears to come true - Mr Major is preferred as the devil the
voters know - the Prime Minister surely needs an uncharacteristic run of good
luck, not to mention solidarity in his own ranks. It has not escaped the notice
of some, by the way, that since Major is going for another session of
Parliament after this one he might have to face another leadership challenge
next November.
The Prime Minister is gambling heavily on the prospect of sufficient economic
growth between now and then to deliver the #9 a week improvement for the
average family which this Budget puts on offer. He is also depending on the
Private Finance Initiative (PFI) to produce that 20p in the pound standard rate.
His Chancellor writes in today's House Magazine: ``The PFI will lead to better
public services at lower cost. Our objective is to contract out services that
can be provided more efficiently in the private sector, cutting management
overheads and bureaucracy. This does not mean less capital spending, but it
does mean that we will concentrate on priorities.'' The hope is that as the PFI
takes off, he will be able to redirect billions of pounds a year.
Add to this a prospect of cutting interest rates, particularly if the economy
slows down, and a consequential easing in the Treasury's ability to reduce the
#10billion-awry borrowing requirement. This comes from the
``always-look-on-the-bright-side-of-life'' wing of the Tory Party.
You could say that Mr Michael Forsyth, the new ``listening Scottish
Secretary'', has at least shown willing to address the call for devolution;
that he has given the Tories a position on the subject that is not entirely
negative. Maybe, just maybe, it will be sufficient to prevent a Tory wipe-out
in Scotland. And if it can be prevented in Scotland, perhaps it can be
prevented south of the Border too.
Optimists have been encouraged by President Clinton's visit to think that a
permanent peace through constitutional agreement in Northern Ireland is more
possible. Should this fall within the 18 months, no doubt Mr Major would gain
much credit. Should peace survive in Bosnia, and with it the Nato
implementation force, the Prime Minister would gain applause. Mr Blair has been
careful to be bi-partisan on both these issues, so the Government's credit for
statesmanship would not be entirely unmitigated in crude political terms. Such
items can nevertheless improve Mr Major's reputation for competence.
More importantly it may be seen that in last week's Budget in which the Tory
right's desire for trenchant tax cuts was thwarted, that Mr Clarke will restore
the balance of the public's belief in the Tories on taxation. He has not sought
to buy votes back in an outrageous fashion.
Labour warns that it will latch on to the slogan ``7p up, 1p down'' from now to
polling day. But Labour will not, it seems, maintain its accusation that Major
has ``lurched to the right''. Mr Blair has fallen silent on this one since the
Budget statement. It was always a cheeky claim, bearing in mind how much he has
shifted his party to the right.
To this extent Mr Blair has been trapped by his own rhetoric. He cannot oppose
Major's 1p cut without weakening his hold on the middle classes. I suspect
``lurch to the right'' is now a dead phrase whether the election is 18 months
or 18 weeks away. Watch them scrap for the middle ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000157</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000157</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Conan Doyle and the immortal image of Holmes</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>ALAN BOLD</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>book review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061237</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THERE will never be a last word on Sherlock Holmes but the first words on the
subject famously appeared in A Study in Scarlet. Looking for lodgings Dr John
Watson, narrator of the novel, meets Stamford who offers to introduce him to a
fellow who might share the rent in some nice rooms: ``You don't know Sherlock
Holmes yet; perhaps you might not care for him as a constant companion.'' As
the world knows, Watson delighted in Holmes as a constant companion. As does
the world delight.
The Glasgow Herald got it right when reviewing A Study in Scarlet in 1887: ``He
is a wonderful man is Mr Sherlock Holmes, but one gets so wonderfully
interested in his cleverness and in the mysterious murder which he unravels
that one cannot lay down the narrative until the end is reached.''
Michael Coren gets it wrong when he writes: ``As for those people who believe
that somehow Holmes was a real person and Conan Doyle a mere conduit, they are
to be pitied.''
Sherlock Holmes is thrillingly real to those who respond to the truth of
fiction; Conan Doyle remains a remote figure in fact. Sherlock Holmes is a real
person by another name and made the name of Conan Doyle matter.
Conan Doyle was the first author whose name meant anything to me. I grew up in
Gayfield Square in Edinburgh and my home from home was the Salon cinema where I
often watched Basil Rathbone playing the part of Sherlock Holmes in moving
films that amazed and enthralled me. One day I wandered from my home to a house
around the corner: number 11 Picardy Place.
This, a plaque explained to my childish amazement, was the birthplace of Sir
Arthur Conan Doyle, creator of Sherlock Holmes. It seemed astonishing that the
Great Detective on the silver screen could be connected with the name of a man
born round the corner from my little corner of the world. Holmes was more than
a name in my native town.
The birthplace was demolished in 1969; the name of Conan Doyle is now the name
of a pub standing near the site. Conan Doyle would not have been amused by the
development. His father, after all, was a man who turned the corner from
unsuccessful careerism to self-destructive drinking to escape from the grim
reality of his life as a clerk and architect in the Office of Works in
Edinburgh.
Charles Doyle disliked Edinburgh, and so did his first son Arthur as a boy
about town. ``Of my boyhood I need say little,'' wrote the mature Conan Doyle,
``save that it was Spartan at home and more Spartan at the Edinburgh school
where a tawse-brandishing schoolmaster of the old type made our young lives
miserable.'' Same old story of Scottish schooldays as the unhappiest days.
Coren touches on the familiar story of Conan Doyle as a medical student at
Edinburgh University but, perhaps thinking it too familiar, provides few
details. He accepts Joseph Bell as partly the original of Holmes and admits
Conan Doyle himself played a part in the personality of the Great Detective.
Then he fumes: ``Those critics who are convinced that Holmes was simply a
caricature of Bell or just the alter ego of his creator have done enormous
damage to Conan Doyle's reputation as a writer.'' Nobody said it was simply
such or just so.
When Conan Doyle settled down, in March 1886, to write A Study in Scarlet he
thought of the deductive skills of Bell, consulting surgeon at Edinburgh
Infirmary, professor at Edinburgh University, editor of the Edinburgh Medical
Journal - thought of ``my old school teacher Joe Bell, of his eagle face, of
his curious ways, of his eerie trick of spotting details''. Writing to Bell in
1892, Conan Doyle declared: ``It is most certainly to you that I owe Sherlock
Holmes.'' Bell, while flattered by the compliment from Conan Doyle, replied:
``You are yourself Sherlock Holmes, and well you know it.'' Literature is
larger than life and Holmes is Conan Doyle writ large with a little help from
his old friend Bell.
Conan Doyle attempted to emulate Holmes in two classic cases of actual
deduction. He exposed the injustice done to George Edalji, wrongly accused of
the crime of mutilating cattle in 1903. He championed the cause of Oscar
Slater, wrongly accused of murdering an old woman in Glasgow in 1908. Conan
Doyle could not have acted so impressively had he not been mindful of Bell and
had the heart of Holmes. Considering Conan Doyle as a man capable of mind over
mentor does no damage to his reputation as a writer.
What did damage Conan Doyle's reputation was his book The Coming of the Fairies
(1922). He had complete faith in photographs of fairies faked by two Bradford
girls in 1917. Conan Doyle was absolutely convinced by the obviously cut-out
characters strutting their supernatural stuff around the girls.
How could the creator of Sherlock Holmes be so credulous? Coren contends Conan
Doyle was unfortunately affected by ``a heavy dose of wishful thinking, spiced
with the trusting assumption that the two girls were above board''. There is an
easier explanation. Conan Doyle could be as daft as any man seeking escape from
an appalling experience, in his case the death of his son Kingsley in 1917.
Conan Doyle was an imaginative escapologist. Hence his fascination with Harry
Houdini, the greatest escapologist of all.
Although Houdini was sceptical of spiritualists Conan Doyle had his wife Jean
insist, as a medium in a seance, she had an automatically written message from
the dead mother of the great magician. Conan Doyle was certain of his wife's
spiritual strength but Houdini found the message weak. First, it was signed
with a cross, and Houdini reckoned this an unlikely communication from a
religious Jew. Second, the message was written in English which disturbed
Houdini: ``Message written by Lady Doyle claiming the spirit of my dear mother
had control of her hand - my sainted mother could not write English and spoke
broken English.''
Houdini denounced Jean in an article and Conan Doyle wrote to Houdini: ``I felt
rather sore about it...... I know by many examples the purity of my wife's
mediumship.'' The creator of the Great Detective could not convince the Great
Houdini.
Coren is convinced by Conan Doyle's enthusiasm for the afterlife: ``A man who
was sufficiently gifted and brilliant to invent and develop Sherlock
Holmes...... surely did not have one gargantuan weak spot when it came to his
personal belief in life after death and the supernatural...... A contemporary
student of Arthur Conan Doyle should in a broad sense be a spiritualist.'' So,
of course, when Conan Doyle died he ``entered through the very large door into
a world that we can only imagine''. Beyond belief.
Coren believes in Conan Doyle as more of a man than mad ``Sherlockian
monomaniacs'' can imagine. Yet who would read this extremely lively study of
Conan Doyle had he not escaped from domestic dullness and recreated himself in
the apparently immortal image of Holmes?
I rest my case for Holmes as the quintessential Conan Doyle on that question.
CONAN DOYLE
By Michael Coren
Bloomsbury, #18.99
</TEXT>
</DOC>
