<HEADLINE>City of Glasgow Chorus, Royal Concert Hall, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Kenny Mathieson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061238</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE City of Glasgow Chorus pride themselves in investigating the less familiar
corners of the repertoire. Neither of the two works they performed with the
Orchestra of Scottish Opera under their conductor and musical director, Graham
Taylor, could be described as concert hall staples, at least in this part of
the world.
Poulenc's Gloria captures the more expansive side of his religious music at the
expense of the quiet mystery of his more introspective religious meditations.
The chorus sounded well-focused and nicely balanced, but have a tendency to
sweeten the music which served to underplay the spikier, Stravinskian echoes of
the work, and made the Laudamus more reminiscent of a Hollywood spectacular
than devotional hymn of praise. Elsewhere, though, they achieved a pleasingly
serene elegance, notably in the final movement.
It seems reasonable enough that an opera orchestra should feel at home playing
Puccini, and, apart from some radiant woodwind playing in the Poulenc, they
sounded happier in the Italian's large-scale Messa di Gloria. It was Puccini's
first major work, and remains a substantial achievement for a 20-year-old
student, although it is not without its longueurs.
The chorus revelled in its even more substantial, emotionally overt canvas,
while all three soloists - soprano Linda Gerrard, tenor Peter Wilson, and bass
Graeme Danby - contributed solid performances. As in the Poulenc, however, the
overall effect seemed a little routine, and the performances ultimately emerged
as agreeable rather than absorbing.
</TEXT>
