<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Lives lived against the odds</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Ruth Wishart</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061239</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Ruth Wishart examines how the arts can change lives - transforming the
expectations of many whose potential was restricted by artificial social
boundaries
WHY are we here? We write to stop ourselves going nuts.
THUS says the preface of a poetry and prose anthology produced by a
single-parents writers' group in Strathclyde. They've learned at first hand one
of the wondrous bonuses of this trade...... that writing is not merely a means
of self-expression but an escape from uncomfortable realities.
And in exploring that creative potential as a group come other benefits born of
shared experience; the growing sense of confidence and self-belief, the comfort
of learning that while every human being is unique almost no human condition,
however difficult, is. Knowing that other people are trying to navigate life in
the same leaky craft doesn't give you safe passage through the hazards but it
does help place them in manageable perspectives.
Today the Scottish Arts Council publish Changing Lives, the latest of a series
of works highlighting the effects of the arts when they are interwoven with our
social fabric rather than seen as an optional add on.
This particular publication explores the effects of arts-based projects on 10
groups, all of whom have differing needs, but all of whom bear witness to the
message that dance, or drama, or music, or writing or any combination of those
can transform expectations and enhance - sometimes in the most unpredictable
ways - the quality of lives being lived against the odds.
Yet often one of the difficulties these groups had to confront was that the
limitations placed on their experience were not as a result of disabilities but
as a result of carers who had consistently underestimated potential or placed
artificial boundaries on experiment.
Strathclyde Orchestral Productions, for instance, met initial resistance from
some people running adult training centres who advised artistic director Gordon
Dougall that ``none of our members will be able to play because they are
physically disabled''. A judgment which quite failed to take into account the
potent combination of the human spirit wired up to technological advance.
Dougall has always seen the operation as an ideal way of integrating
able-bodied and disabled players rather than having professional musicians
parachute in for limited interaction.
The result has been a skill level which has seen SOP make recordings and reach
live audiences beyond the constituency of families and friends. In fact, some
disabled musicians who began with SOP have gone on to join professional musical
ensembles.
The importance of this project is not just the uncovering and nurturing of real
potential, but insisting that disabled artists are not judged by separate
standards. All artists want to be thought of as good, not ``good under the
circumstances''.
Many of the other projects were more temporary but apparently no less
fulfilling. The Patchwork of Memories, as they called an oral history project
on Islay and Jura, used the knowledge and experience of senior citizens to
ensure that traditional skills and local culture would be passed on.
A pilot study at Annan in Dumfriesshire gave the long-stay elderly professional
help and materials to explore latent talent in the visual arts.
And once you've witnessed the fruits of these ventures at first hand it's very
difficult not to get religion about the potency of the arts for ordinary
people, however extraordinary their current circumstances. It's no accident
that many of these projects found funding through education and social work
departments because the evidence of their success in dealing with everything
from mental illness to delinquency is now overwhelming.
The resident drama therapist at Dundee Rep's community department now provides
a region-wide service for people dealing with all kinds of mental problems
including dementia.
Dundee has also used dance therapeutically as has the Projekt 11.92 Dance
Company who work with young people who have learning difficulties and were
directly employed by Strathclyde region's social work department - ``determined
to take dance into areas where people don't usually ask for it''.
In the light of which it's no accident either that this particular report will
turn up in the in-tray of executives of the new local authorities whose job it
will be to decide where their budgets, often much more modest than the regional
variety, will be targeted.
SAC director Seona Reid hopes that the cities at least will follow Glasgow's
example and set up a fund to help keep such innovative schemes afloat until the
new bodies have had time to take spending decisions.
Not least because some of the groups have a track record it would be folly to
lose. The Lung Ha Theatre Company started in 1984 in Edinburgh to give new
opportunities on the stage to people with learning difficulties. It's now the
largest company of its kind in Scotland, has 10 productions under its belt, and
meets weekly to give members classes in all kinds of stagecraft.
It has matured into a company which has been welcomed in mainstream venues and
whose work has been televised. It has changed lives. Given a fair financial
wind it will change more.
</TEXT>
