<HEADLINE>`Oscars' for public organisations</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Wendy Jack</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061240</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE Charter Mark award scheme is the equivalent of an Oscar for public
organisations in Britain and today, the winners have been announced, 20 of
which are Scottish.
What, you may ask, is Charter Mark?
It's an award scheme for organisations in the public service such as hospitals
and other NHS services; schools; colleges and universities; Police, fire and
ambulance services; council services; Government services; benefit or
employment offices; water, gas and electricity companies.
The award is given for excellence, and is not easy to obtain; the standards of
those applying is high. Only the best succeed, and a winning organisation has
to show the judges that it provides an excellent service.
It has to demonstrate that it meets those criteria:
l Setting clear and tough performance standards; tells users what those are and
whether they are achieved.
l Tells users in a clear, straightforward way, about all the services and help
available and how to get the most out of them.
l Consults users on what services they need and how these can be made better,
and makes good use of customers' ideas.
l Gives users a choice wherever possible.
l Has courteous, helpful staff and a user-friendly approach to such things as
opening hours and customers' particular needs.
l Makes it easy for users when they are displeased, and acts swiftly to correct
what is wrong.
l Careful budgeting and efficient, effective use of their money.
l Has made real improvements in service quality, and has new ideas, and
improvements ready for the future.
Each Charter Mark award is given for three years, although if standards are not
maintained, it can be taken away. After the three years is up, holders have to
re-apply.
Applications are judged by the Prime Minister's Advisory Panel on the Citizens'
Charter, headed by Sir James Blyth, deputy chairman and chief executive of the
Boots Company plc, and the Citizens' Charter Minister before being finally
approved by the Prime Minister.
Independent consultants supervise the assessment process. Organisations submit
a 10-page application with supporting material, and a team of Charter Mark
assessors who are experienced in diverse areas of public service, considers
this.
At the same time judges get information about applicants' performance from
Government departments, independent regulators, the Audit Commission and other
sources. Whenever possible they are keen to seek evidence from customer panels
or committees.
The best of the applications are short listed, and visited either by members of
the Prime Minister's Advisory Panel, Charter Mark assessors or senior Cabinet
Office staff. Once all the evidence has been thoroughly examined a list of
winners is recommended by the Prime Minister's Advisory Panel.
Winners receive a crystal trophy, a certificate signed by the Prime Minister
and the right to use the Charter Mark logo on stationery and other written
material, on their vehicles, and other equipment for three years. More
important, they get recognition of their first-class service.
The scale of awards has been growing steadily since the scheme was introduced
in 1992. That year up to 50 awards were available with 36 winners of which 35
have re-applied this year. Twenty-five have been successful, while the rest
were not. In the case of the latter, the judges recognised their commitment to
quality and expressed the hope that with the assistance of feedback and advice
from Charter Mark assessors they may be successful next year.
In 1993, 93 winners were announced, while the following year saw 98 receiving
awards, this year a record 223 have won the Charter Mark, with another 193
Highly Commended.
In recognition of the high quality of this year's 740 applications the number
of awards available was increased by the judges. For the first time this year,
the public was able to nominate organisations they considered deserved to win
the award - the route by which some 80 winning organisations scooped their
awards.
The chairman of the judges, Lord Blyth of Rowington, said: ``Charter Marks are
the Oscars of public service. We are very impressed by the quality of this
years' applications. They demonstrate the real commitment to quality of so many
of the people working in public service. I am delighted that there are now a
total of 414 organisations, across the country holding Charter Marks.''
Each Charter Mark award is given for three years, although if standards are not
maintained, it can be taken away
</TEXT>
