<DOCNO>GH951204-000161</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000161</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Partnership  plan pays off</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Advertising Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061241</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
CENTRAL Scotland Police are one of the recipients of this year's Charter Awards.
Following the appointment of chief constable William Wilson in 1990, the
success of his very community-oriented approach to policing has become known
and admired nationally.
Fundamental to the force's ``We can plan out crime'' philosophy is partnership,
and 170 have been formed within the community, with local and regional
councils, schools, businesses and so on.
Invoked in 1991, the strategy seems to be paying off handsomely.
The area's crime figures for 1991 were 25,028, with a crime detection rate of
44.7%; by 1994 the crime figures had fallen to 20,133, and the detection rate
had risen to 56.98%, while the latter figure to date this year has been
successfully eased up once more to about 60%.
The initiative also involves strategies to reduce road traffic accidents.
Throughout their ``patch'' senior officers in each area can make autonomous
decisions on the best policing for their particular locality, based on its
needs and problems.
</TEXT>
