<DOCNO>GH951204-000162</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000162</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Aladdin, Pavilion, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Mary Brennan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061242</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
``THIS has been a panto of two halves,'' declared Ofpants - the official panto
watchdog - ``and don't bother with any wisecracks about intervals.'' A
surreptitious glance at Ofpants's checklist revealed various ticks and crosses.
A kind of squiggly star beside The Krankies - he's the dame, she's
Jimmee-Washee, sorry Wishee-Washee - and various approving scribbles, including
``energetically vulgar''. Further down, a curious doodle . . . a skull and
cross bones maybe? . . . against Linda Nolan's Aladdin and the word ``Yikes!''
underlined three times.
The old watchdog's right, I'm afraid. The Pavilion panto cobbles together
genuine high spots with stuff that arrives centre-stage on automatic pilot and
is likely to stay in complacent low gear throughout the run. Why? Because
good-hearted audiences will simply shrug aside echoes of routine songs ground
out in phoney ``isn't this a good time?'' fashion.
And they'll overlook dialogue that reduces the plot to cues for the songs. And
they'll not even mind the non-performances of Linda Nolan, Mike Hayward, Nicola
Auld - who all seem to feel the costume will say it all for them - and instead
audiences will tell their friends about how absolutely mega Eunice Huthart (of
TV Gladiators fame) was as the kick-boxing genie. She is, because she has an
all-out, enthusiastic personality.
And kids, the lads especially, will gleefully mimic Janette Krankie's wobbly
knees and throaty cry of ``Ah'm a durty wee boay!'' When The Krankies are going
through their astute paces - acting silly, acting saucy, but most of all acting
up for the audience - Aladdin fan-dabi-does work. Otherwise, it
fan-dubious-disnae.
</TEXT>
