<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000163</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000163</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Johnnie Cochran fought racism in the OJ trial and the same fight brings him to the UK Winning hand from a raw deal Anne Simpson</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>anne simpson</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>10</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Features</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061243</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
TO the sound of hosannas and much else besides, Johnnie Cochran moves elegantly
through life, a small, compact figure in topdog clothes, saviour of the rich in
deep trouble, pop icon to the poor.
That strange combination is also what sets many teeth on edge. Ordinarily the
first quality should cancel out the second but there has never been anything
ordinary about Cochran. He is one of those exceptionally perceptive and
swift-talking individuals who, one feels, could have been a conjurer had
showbusiness beckoned. But Cochran was drawn to another form of stagecraft, the
American legal system, and at the bar he has specialised in out-foxing the
establishment at every turn.
Last October 3, at 10.05am, Los Angeles time, the repeated words Not Guilty,
voiced in Courtroom 103, ensured Cochran's most spectacular and profitable
triumph so far.
But if the OJ Simpson circus is over, the various sideshows are not. The other
day, Cochran, the leading defence lawyer in the sportsman's trial, arrived in
Britain to share his knowledge on how best to handle that most primitive of
hatreds, racism. When we met he had been in Brixton earlier in the day. By the
end of the week he would have visited Liverpool's Toxteth. Somewhere in between
the MP, Bernie Grant, had arranged a House of Commons reception for him. There
had been numerous packed and lively meetings where standing ovations were
routine. And then, just before another get-together with Britain's black
community, a strange thing happened.
Someone had wrongly informed Scotland Yard that Johnnie R Cochran jr was armed.
He was questioned and his hotel room searched, a clear case of discrimination
against ethnic peoples, raged his hosts, the Society of Black Lawyers.
For his part, Cochran took the incident philosophically. If nothing else it
proved his point that none of us is free of prejudice. But that rapturous
response he had received from so many Caribbean and Asian audiences also told
us something about contemporary Britain: we have a race crisis here which most
of us are failing to address.
``In the United States one-third of African-American males have been involved
with the legal system, and I'm learning that the situation is not much better
in this country. We're going in the wrong direction if a society believes it is
productive to lock up its minority groups,'' he says.
On that winter's night at the Friends' Meeting House in Euston Road, the sense
of grievance about law and order enforcers in London, Birmingham, Manchester,
Liverpool, Bristol and Leeds, was beyond the comprehension of most whites, and
that, of course, is a large part of the problem. But on this particular
occasion the audience was not just drawn from the usual battlements of urban
deprivation. It also came from residential neighbourhoods up and down the
country.
And when Cochran concluded his address by pledging to return to the States and
raise money for the parents of the slain black teenager, Stephen Lawrence, so
that they can pursue England's first private prosecution for murder, the
applause was thunderous. Afterwards, Cochran spoke about meeting Stephen's
parents and being overwhelmed by their dignity.
``I was enormously impressed by them, and this kind of international solidarity
will let the powers that be know that if victims cannot gain justice in the
normal way, then from across the Atlantic and perhaps with the help of the
continent we will pool resources to finance civil cases. If the Lawrence action
is successful, then the Government will pay attention.''
There is, of course, a sharp irony to such vigorous championing from Johnnie
Cochran on this issue, for civil suits, now filed by the families of Ronald
Goldman and Nicole Brown Simpson might yet prevent his client OJ from having
much of a life. But Cochran doesn't appear to be overly concerned by this
disobliging connection. After all, he prefers to see that whole amazing episode
in his career like this: ``We got that guy off because we did our job. The fact
is the police investigation made so many telling errors we were able to reduce
the prosecution's mountain of evidence to a molehill. I prefer to think we won
because of `reasonable doubt' rather than because some smart lawyer who knew
the tricks beguiled the jury.''
Cochran is 57 but one of those who could easily pass for 40. He admits
delightedly to being a dandy, relishing hand-crafted suits and shoes, and
neckties of high swank. Born and raised in middle-class Los Angeles, he was
already profoundly wealthy before the OJ trial. Early in his career he became
the scourge of the persistently racist LA Police Department, a commitment
which, in fact, made him a hero in the black slums long before they had ever
thought of elevating OJ Simpson to the pantheon of  idols.
But somewhere along life's journey Cochran swung his attention away from
low-dollar cases and towards those which now earn him at least $1m a year,
allowing him all the necessary rich man's trappings - a Rolls-Royce, one
mansion in the Hollywood hills, another by the Pacific Ocean, and the
distinction of having won at least $45m in damages over a period of 20-odd
years. This is the lawyer who brokered the settlement over allegations that the
singer Michael Jackson had sexually abused a teenage boy. And this is the
lawyer who openly says: `I started fighting police assault because it was
wrong. Then thanks to the American Way I made a lot of money while doing it. I
found I could do well and do some good at the same time. But in the States that
isn't always popular.'
BUT had OJ Simpson been poor would Cochran have defended him? At first he
doesn't directly answer but roams around a philosophical tract: ``It's
incumbent on all of us to speak out when people's lives are at stake, whether
these people have financial resources or not.'' And then, as if pressing a
passion button, Cochran's speech becomes even faster and emotional: ``We need
lawyers who care about their clients in the way that lawyers, by tradition,
were meant to do. This isn't about billing out; it's about doing the right
thing.''
To many Americans, however, Johnnie Cochran is the very last person who should
be free and easy with advice. In many minds the OJ Simpson acquittal
demonstrates a trial where money talked, a story where the defence team proved
that if you have enough wealth you can throw it at the American criminal
justice system and tie it up with a thousand strands of procedural tangles. And
for many others it illustrated how a good lawyer can be ``a bad citizen'',
turning a trial into a political caucus where jurors debased their role of
rendering ``a just verdict'' in order to send society a message about corrupt
and racist cops.
But if these are the pervasive views of white Americans, says Cochran, then
that in itself is racism. ``I dare say that if OJ Simpson had been charged with
killing his first wife, Margaret, who is black, there would have been no
interest in this case at all. Do you know that Time magazine took OJ's face and
darkened it for the cover, to make it look sinister? That's part and parcel of
the whole attitude. Having said that, though, the fact that the cameras were in
the courtroom was instructive. If it had been left to print journalists to tell
everyone whether or not those gloves fitted, they would have had every excuse
to claim Simpson was acting when he put them on. But the world could see they
did not fit.''
Now, two months after his freedom from that double murder charge, Cochran's
client is still condemned by someone every day. His lover has dumped him, his
neighbours and friends have retreated, his talent agency of 20 years has struck
him from its books, and the promoters behind all those lucrative deals which
were touted initially have backed off, fearing public revenge should they be
seen to market the OJ initials.
AND among the many bizarre twists in this wretched courtroom tale there is the
one in which Cochran's own defence colleague stripped the shine from their
success immediately after the trial. Still within the shadow of the court,
Robert Shapiro confirmed the general view that Cochran had manipulated the jury
by ``playing the race card from the bottom of the deck''.
The contrast between the two men at that point was almost theatrical: Shapiro's
jowly, Semitic face, a landscape of gloom, and Cochran, the world's most famous
black lawyer, beaming and slapping his client's back in exultation, then moving
out among his people like a god.
The jury's message was, in fact, the old one. America remains one country but
two nations, black and white. ``We have a saying in America,'' says Cochran.
``We arrived in different ships but we're all in the same boat now.'' And he
adds: ``Black and white, we've got to work this thing out together.'' But
though the circus may indeed be over, the verdict sideshows may never end. Yet
was it really the trial of the century? If so, that           puts the
proceedings at Nuremberg in an interesting perspective.
We're going in the wrong direction if society believes it is productive to lock
up its   minority groups
</TEXT>
</DOC>
