<DOCNO>GH951204-000164</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000164</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Everything in the garden is rhody</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Jennifer Cunningham</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>9</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061244</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Jennifer Cunningham reports on a unique venture in which Scotland is helping
China rescue its native rhododendrons
THE tall, unassuming young man might pass for a minor academic, but his large
feet walk regularly in the footsteps of some of this century's greatest
explorers and his hands are helping to save the world.
The exploits of Scotland's great plant hunters are legendary. George Forrest
survived a massacre in Tibet and saw his companions brutally killed in his
quest for the 31,000 species he brought back to Britain. They included 309
species of rhododendron and formed the basis of the greatest collection in the
Royal Botanic Garden in Edinburgh.
Ninety years later, the collection's curator, David Paterson, can cheerfully
refer to Forrest and his fellow-collector Ernest ``Chinese'' Wilson as
plunderers because for the first time the garden has returned living plant
material to its country of origin. Even in China's vast wildernesses its native
species are under threat.
``We sent them Datapost,'' he said of the 220 precious and fragile baby
rhododendrons from Edinburgh he has just helped to plant in the new Hua Xi
Botanical Garden in China's Sichuan Province. Latter-day plant-returners also
have their hairy moments. Datapost turned out to be not as specific as they had
hoped. They delivered the plants hundreds of miles away from the required
destination, causing customs to impound them while the paperwork was untangled.
``Remember, these plants had to be washed of all soil because you cannot
transport soil around the world, so they can only survive for a very short
period and then they need intensive after-care once they get there. So they
were sitting in a customs office while we were frantically trying to get the
paperwork sorted out.''
They survived the ordeal of being in transit for almost a fortnight and
although the success rate will not be 100%, Paterson is confident it will be
over 90%. Like all gardeners, Paterson, a horticulturist rather than a
botanist, believes it is prudent to give away plants.
``Edinburgh has the largest collection of species rhododendron anywhere in the
world. While China has more species in nature, ours are fully-documented and
classified. What we want to do is build up a parallel collection in the Hua Xi
gardens because that prevents us having all our eggs in one basket if, for
example, we had disease in our collection. We have about 454 species in the
botanic garden, about half of which are hardy, but we want to increase our
holding and we also want to increase the biodiversity by bringing in new plants
from China,'' he said.
since the Earth Summit in Rio, biodiversity has been the buzz word. The UK
Government's commitment to it was to set up the Darwin Initiative to fund
projects to conserve endangered species. It has put up #53,400 for the
Edinburgh rhodo return. It also funded a year-long study visit to Edinburgh by
a Chinese horticulturalist, Guiyan Geng. She was involved in growing the
rhododendrons which were sent out to China and returned with David Paterson to
oversee the planting.
``The material we took back came from a number of places that no longer hold
rhododendron populations because the land has changed, usually by clear-felling
and increased grazing by yak,'' said Paterson, who added that they also took
species from the eastern Himalayas, North America and Europe because it is so
difficult for Chinese botanists to go there. The Chinese have been well-warned
to keep the European species under check so that they don't run riot and
destroy the habitat.
The Chinese Academy of Sciences has developed the Hua Xi garden on two sites: a
small garden adjacent to Dujiang City and a big garden which ranges over 1000
hectares of a steep-sided horseshoe-shaped valley. The valley bottom will be
the site of the rhododendron garden.
It will soon be under immense people pressure. Keen to develop eco-tourism, the
Chinese Government is building hotels in the valley because it expects the
garden to become a world tourist attraction. Can it maintain a balance between
development and protecting the flora and fauna?
Paterson cites two natural advantages in keeping the tourists in check.
``Because the terrain is very steep, most of the tourists are going to remain
down at the bottom and so the impact of tourism is going to be contained. It is
also the ideal habitat for leeches and the urban and suburban Chinese hate
leeches, so they are not going to climb up the mountainsides either,'' he said.
Among the native rhododendrons is zhaguense, a real rarity which is found only
on the mountain Zheguo Shan. It is a bit of a coup for Paterson: ``As far as I
am aware it is not in cultivation anywhere in the world and I have brought back
some seeds so that it can be cultivated here as well as in China. Another
species found in association with it, but which is not so rare, is agonnipha,
which is in cultivation and we have some in Edinburgh.
``Part of the work which I was doing there was reintroducing species which we
have in Edinburgh to China. They included belagense which is a small
rhododendron less than one metre high which grows on the snow at 4500 metres,
seeds of which were brought back here for the first time by colleagues in 1991
and we now have half a dozen plants growing in the nursery. We did go on an
expedition to look for it, but the conditions were against us. The snow had
come early, it was very misty and we were driving along steep dirt tracks.
Eventually we had to abandon the vehicle and we walked for the best part of a
day searching these mountains, but failed to find it.
The repatriated plants are, of course, likely to do better than their siblings
in Edinburgh, since they are going into perfect growing conditions. Edinburgh
is drier than is ideal for rhodies.
``I don't think we can regard Hua Xi garden as a satellite but we can certainly
curate the collections together to some extent,'' said David Paterson, who
believes that continued collaboration is vital to the rhodies in both gardens.
The obstacle to that is that the Darwin Initiative funding will be exhausted
after a follow-up visit next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000165</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000165</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>No Headline Present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Murray Ritchie</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>13</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<FLAG>euroview</FLAG>
<RECORDNO>975061245</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THEY say that people who live in Edinburgh never get round to visiting the
castle. There's always tomorrow. Much the same applies to people in Brussels
who rarely stop to look at the remarkable architecture of this city - or what's
left of it.
I am as guilty as the next incomer to Brussels. We rarely see more of the city
than the EU institutions. The EU is not Brussels, of course, any more than
Brussels is Belgium. But there are surprises for those who take the trouble to
look.
Last week I visited the elegant Brussels home of Gerry McGeary and his family
who hail from Hamilton. He mentioned with some satisfaction that a previous
tenant had been one Karl Marx. You never know the minute in this town.
Brussels is famous for its town planning. For years there wasn't any. The
result is delightful chaos - jumbles of distinctive and stylish, mostly stone,
buildings all setting themselves off in haphazard rows along narrow streets.
The downside is traffic. This city was never built for the motor car which now
suffocates it. Tree-lined boulevards have become traffic canyons, death traps
for cyclists and some of the worst-polluted streets in Europe.
To make matters worse the EU has commandeered much of central Brussels, razing
scores of wonderful buildings to put up filing cabinets. This week's talking
point is the appearance of the Berlaymont building. Workmen are completing the
strange task of wrapping it in white canvas, like a big parcel, so that work
can begin on stripping it of asbestos. The job and consequent blight will last
for years. It looks weird in its shroud. Most people think it also looks better
that way.
But away from Euro-land there is another world. I went in search of the McGeary
Gallery, which is a business owned by Francesca McGeary, daughter of Gerry, who
teaches art at the European School in Brussels, and his wife. (Francesca bears
an uncanny resemblance to the Duchess of York and is, apparently, often
mistaken for her by a royalty-conscious Belgian public.)
The McGeary family live in flats above the Gallery in Rue Jean D'Ardenne, not
far from the swanky Avenue Louise with its designer shops where the price tags
come with endless zeros.
Rue Jean d'Ardenne is a typical Brussels back street - the sort you rush past
every day without pausing to look. It has its share of old and elegant
buildings, their splendour somewhat faded now, some others which are more in
the utility end of the market and a stately old school which some official
vandal has painted a sickly sea green.
Belgians do that sort of thing. This, remember, is the city which, despite its
celebrated architecture, is happy to be best known for its ridiculous Manneken
Pis. Only Brussels could make a landmark from a naked urchin urinating.
Admittedly, there's method in that madness: high-spending tourists gravitate to
it all year round.
Francesca McGeary was presenting an exhibition of prints by the celebrated
Scottish painter Elizabeth Blackadder - smashers they are, too - which The
Herald helped with some modest sponsorship. Gerry started telling us the
history of the building which is opposite a house with a plaque commemorating
another resident, the aforesaid Jean d'Ardenne, a Belgian travel writer. After
Jean d'Ardenne moved on, the street - previously called Rue d'Orlean - assumed
his name. It might have been called Hepburn Street. Audrey lived up the road,
too.
The McGearys and their daughter live at number 50 where Karl Marx was the
tenant from 1846 to 1848, according to the plaque on the wall outside. Gerry's
trouble is that students keep pinching the plaques as souvenirs. The present
one is the third.
An American researcher worked out that it was probably in this flat that Marx
wrote the Communist Manifesto before taking it to Paris for publication. He was
knocked up in what is now the McGeary home one morning by the Brussels secret
police - there was revolution in the air at the time - and told to get out of
town because he was persona non grata.
He had been a man-about-town whose favourite howff was the La Maison du Cygne
in Grand Place. It those days it was a working-man's pub; today it is one of
the poshest restaurants in Brussels and only for those on liberal expenses. New
Labour would approve.
Good exhibition, though. My wife decided we liked one of the pictures. I left a
wiser man, and poorer. But spiritually enriched.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000166</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000166</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Rod Stewart at the SECC, Glasgow</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Peter Easton</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Review</ARTICLETYPE>
<RECORDNO>975061246</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE scale of the Big Red Barn is made human by the installation of a central
stage. Above it, video screens supply a succession of introductory images: Rod
punting footballs into an open goal; Rod making amusingly heavy weather out of
changing his infant son's nappy. These pretty well sum up the relationship
between artiste and audience. Thousands of guys and gals have come here to
relive their emotional infancy and a time when more people had work to do and a
reason to believe.
The set lasts for about two-and-a-quarter hours and is mostly chronological.
This entails clumsy narrative, the likes of ``and so we come to 1975 and the
Atlantic Crossing album, when unfortunately I had to leave the UK''.
Unfortunately, Atlantic Crossing comes all too soon, recalling Britt,
superstardom, and the beginning of a tide of mid-Atlantic sludge (Sailing) and
a descending succession of relentless and mostly soulless hits, which are
neither rock nor pop.
To take his mind off this, Rod maintains a cracking pace, kicking footballs,
whirling microphone stands, running circuits of the stage for Young Hearts Run
Free . . .
But the early stuff is still so good. We even hear something from his days with
the Jeff Beck Group, an angry crunching metallic blues which confounds the
dancers now as it did back in '67. Gasoline Alley: what a gem. This show is a
triumph of physical and vocal endurance - and also of laddish charm. But the
later material lets the man down, dislocated in style and strangely
self-important. Good humoured yes, but there's a difference between having a
laugh and having a sense of humour.
</TEXT>
