<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000167</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000167</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>The art of Christmas present</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Clare Henry</BYLINE>
<EDITION>2</EDITION>
<PAGE>14</PAGE>
<ARTICLETYPE>Feature</ARTICLETYPE>
<GRAPHIC>photograph</GRAPHIC>
<RECORDNO>975061247</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
Forget the perfume and whisky.
Clare Henry recommends a visit to the galleries for original festive gifts
CHRISTMAS looms. Gifts? Buy art. That's my advice. It's excellent value - and
lasts much longer than perfume, whisky or clothes! Christmas exhibitions are
ideal for shoppers: a treasure trove of hundreds of smallish pictures spiced
with ceramics, prints, and jewellery at bargain prices.
Bearing in mind the astronomic cost of art materials and framing - plus the 40%
to the gallery - artists practically give their stuff away. And compared to
crowded department stores, calm, spacious galleries are a breeze.
However, this week my sympathies are divided. The postal strike hit Christmas
shows hard. Mailing an average 1500 people (printed invitations plus postage),
costs galleries between #900-#2000, or up to #20,000 annually. Edinburgh's
Scottish Gallery told me it costs them #12 per person a year to keep someone on
their mailing list. A disastrous waste of money if invitations are delayed by a
postal strike.
Yet artists, notoriously bad with deadlines, make Christmas shows a nightmare.
Glasgow Print Studio's opening was marred by lack of prices and lists. Sales
were lost. The fault may lie somewhere between late delivery by artists and
short staffing, but there is no excuse for such unprofessionalism on both
sides. Todd Garner went one better. He had no prices at all at his Contemporary
Ceramics Christmas show.
Happily the granddaddy of them all, Compass Christmas Show, gets it right. For
26 years Cyril and Jill Gerber have scoured art schools and studios for a
tip-top festive collection. Jill designed the Compass logo in 1970 at art
school and shares her father's commitment to keeping the Compass going, despite
a complete cut of Arts Council funding in 1989.
``#25,000 was a lot to lose at a stroke - but we have survived so far.
Christmas is our busiest time. We depend on December sales to help us through
the year,'' says Gerber. How to choose? ``Select what you like. If they don't
like it, at least they'll remember you!''
Over 600 works are crammed into 178 West Regent Street. Artists range from
Picasso, Matisse, Hockney, Freud, Nicholson, Sutherland, Jessie King, and Henry
Moore - who merely feature alphabetically on the printed list (prices vary from
Sutherland's #1400 to Matisse's exquisite #9500 Jeune Femme which I'll buy if I
win the Lottery) - via Blackadder, Cairns, Knox, and Macpherson to new
graduates whose work costs as little as #30.
Bargains abound: jewellery by Dundee's Graeme McColm at #65; delightful
drawings by Bowman and Sue Gerber (#75); fine Shellduck by Jones (#110) and
Mare by Judith Spence (#97), witty #85 linocuts by the virtuoso Robertson;
Bennett's Dancing Horse embroidery (#70); Nardini's acrylic of Tina (#102) or
Michael Fullerton's oil study of a pensive boy (#135).
For serious stuff, look at Lesley Banks's Nanzie, Howard's yellow Reliquary,
Gilbert's charcoal of Ruth, Edgar's Landfall or Gregor Smith's Summmer Squall -
all around #400. Don't miss Scott's superb Garden Orator discoursing on ``Neil
Gunn, the war, poets, birds, sun and love'', Flockart's surreal Banquet,
Cunningham's mad ceramics, Fraser's dogs or Jim Tweedie's bandstand in
Kelvingrove Park.
Tweedie first helped out at Compass in 1971 and has worked there on and off
since the mid-1980s. Like many gallery assistants he's also an artist. A
passion for de Chirico informs his oils, giving his Glasgow cityscapes a fourth
dimension.
Another artist/assistant is Lynn Park at Glasgow's Billcliffe Fine Art. A
jeweller herself, she's made a big impact, selecting elegant silver from
Crimmins, Cherry and Molly Bullick (whose wearable silver also features at the
Scottish Gallery). Park's own brooches and earrings start at #25.
Back at Glasgow Print Studio, the shop sells works at #100 and under. Check out
Korusiewicz's classics, McCormick's New Born, Crum-Ewing's scenarios, Magee's
silhouettes, Pollok's cats, Campbell's clocks - and Chmutin's superb tiny
mezzotints, a mere #70 for something notable created in New York, Glasgow, and
St Petersburg.
Over the road (up to #400), my favourites include Snyder and Ironsides's
colourful monoprints, Malkowska's vigorous woodcuts, Howson's kids, Rae's
windows, Giblin's Arcadia, Robertson's amazing Kingdom of Scotland, and
Simpson's crazy collages.
I also recommend Edinburgh's Open Eye. David Donaldson's Flight into Egypt
features on their invitations, always among the most attractive and best
produced. Incidentally, why is it that artists take out-of-focus photos of
their work, have no idea of what makes a good image, and can rarely supply a
decent slide or black-and-white? Opening a new gallery is always a brave move;
doing it twice requires total commitment. Rena Hunter has just launched her
second effort, the Carthcart Gallery at Clarkson Road in time for Christmas,
with pictures by Orr, Turnbull, Moore, Edgar, Patullo, and Ed Hunter.
For the NS Gallery Cresswell Lane show, Stars and Trees and Fairies, leave your
storybook prejudices at home. These putti, angels, and cherubs by Nagl,
Docherty, Ironside, and Wilson are full of character, with Dorrian's
beautifully drawn daughter the star.
These special pictures are juxtaposed with an Aladdin's cave of affordable
glass, ceramics, and jewellery. There's also a memorial display of flower
paintings by Rita Madhok, famous as Darlinda the astrologer. The Darlinda
Charity, for which she raised a stupendous #300,000 for renal research,
continues and is producing a Celebrity Cookery Book soon.
Another themed show, Angels, Heavenly Visitors and Divine Landscapes at
Kilbarchan's Studio Arts Gallery, encouraged Tom Shanks to turn his hand from
stormy mountains to delicate angels while Birnie shows Venetian cherubs, Carey
a dreamy mandolin player, and Snyder a bold Icarus.
For applied arts Galerie Mirages is definitely the most cosmopolitan. For over
a decade the Dhariwals have scoured the world, bringing exotic jewellery from
India, Indonesia, and Israel, glass from Egypt and Persia, textiles from
Turkey, Afghan-istan and Rajasthan, pots and carvings from Nigeria, Kenya, and
Sarawak and wacky scrap-iron sculpture from Zimbabwe. They specialise in
one-off items which I adore, like the perfect op art poetry of an Indonesian
wicker eel catcher, a Sol Le Witt pattern palm chair or Bernard Leech-like
brown rice bowl. Like the NS Gallery, open on Sundays.
Also look out for Art Exposure at 19 Parnie Street; the Tron Studio;
Edinburgh's Torrance Gallery and East Kilbride's annual drawing show. Happy
shopping.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000168</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000168</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Third suspicion taints Gingrich</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>Patrick Brogan</BYLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061248</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
FOR the first time this weekend, the Democrats have succeeded in getting at
Newt Gingrich's personal honesty.
The Federal Election Commission had indicted Gopac, a committee controlled by
Mr Gingrich from 1986 until early this year, for evading the law.
Gopac is a fund-raising and ginger group that devoted itself to helping
Republican candidates for local office until Mr Gingrich took over. Then he
made it into the intellectual powerhouse of the coming Republican conquest of
the House of Representatives, with a mission to raise funds and to train
Republican candidates.
Unfortunately for him, he neglected to inform the FCC of Gopac's new mission,
which was therefore illegal. In 1991, Democrats complained to the FCC and Gopac
changed its job description, but the FCC now charges that its activities from
1989 to 1991 were illegal.
This is not an impeachable offence, and at the worst, presumably, Gopac will be
fined a sum it can easily afford. However the taint of illegality has now been
attached to the Speaker on three separate issues.
The others were, first, his acceptance of a #3m book advance from Rupert
Murdoch's book-publishing company, HarperCollins.
Mr Gingrich admitted that the deal had at least the appearance of impropriety
and renounced the advance.
He wrote the book and counted of royalties for profit, but the book has sold
far less well than he hoped and he will earn much less than #3m.
This is rather the point his critics made, insinuating that Mr Murdoch was
buying influence with the Speaker, and the Speaker was selling it. Mr
Gingrich's extreme rancour against the press is partly because of the fact that
all the publicity the newspapers gave to the book deal in December last year
has led to losing him a great deal of money.
The third ethical problem also concerned Gopac. It turned out that the
committee was paying Mr Gingrich to give lectures at a small university in
Georgia. He says that this was all a matter of teaching history, but the
Democrats claim that it was a covert way of subsidising his congressional
salary.
The Democratic Whip in the House, David Bonnior, a relentless critic of the
Speaker's, says that the FCC indictment is the ``smoking gun'' that proves Mr
Gingrich's criminality. The Speaker says the whole issue is phoney. No doubt
the truth will be found to lie in-between, but the dispute is bound to hurt the
Speaker.
Gopac is a cute acronym: the Republican Party likes to be known as the Grand
Old Party (GOP) and most of the covert funding of American politics is done
through Political Action Committees (PACs). Hence Gopac.
The FCC has released thousands of pages of memos and letters from Gopac's
files, showing how thoroughly and systematically Mr Gingrich and his friends
planned to take over the party and then to win control of Congress. Whatever
the legality of the operation, the papers the FCC has issued make fascinating
reading.
For the first time, they reveal a real political campaign in action.
One of the revelations, for instance, is that from the start, Mr Gingrich and
his friends concentrated on strategy, not substance. They intended to proclaim
themselves conservatives, and then use private polls and ``focus groups'' to
discover what that meant, and to tailor their programme to the findings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000169</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000169</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Law failing workers, says TUC</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>5</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061249</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
THE legal system is failing many workers because it is ``slow, costly and
complicated'', the TUC says in a report published today.
Workers would have more chance of getting legal redress in workplace disputes
if unions were given a more important role, it says.
The TUC says union involvement should be extended from the traditional areas of
occupational injury and ill health, discrimination and employment rights. TUC
general secretary John Monks said: ``The present legal system fails too many
people.
``Trade unions have expertise in dealing with workplace issues and should be
given a greater role. We believe that unions can do a lot to help non-union
members too.''
The report says the costs and complications involved in taking a grievance to
court were often prohibitive for all but the rich or those who qualified for
legal aid.
The TUC call for the legal system to be restructured and for more disputes to
be settled out of court.
Legal aid should be made available for representation at industrial tribunals,
says the report, Justice For Working People, which was published in advance of
a TUC conference on discrimination law in London today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>GH951204-000170</DOCNO>
<DOCID>GH951204-000170</DOCID>
<DATE>951204</DATE>
<HEADLINE>Tutu demands Nigeria sanctions</HEADLINE>
<EDITION>1</EDITION>
<PAGE>6</PAGE>
<RECORDNO>975061250</RECORDNO>
<TEXT>
ARCHBISHOP Desmond Tutu yesterday urged sanctions against Nigeria in the wake
of the execution of Ken Saro-Wiwa.
Speaking in London before the official memorial tribute to the writer and human
rights campaigner, hanged with eight other Ogoni activists last month,
Archbishop Tutu called for an oil embargo against Nigeria and for the accounts
of the military rulers to be closed.
``Apartheid was brought to its knees by the support for sanctions,'' he said,
``therefore we would call on the international community to continue that good
work.''
The Nobel Prize winner also gave support to an international boycott of Shell
Oil if the company refused to bring pressure on General Sani Abacha's
government by pulling out of gas projects there.
Archbishop Tutu, a close friend of Nelson Mandela, said the South African
president's initial ``softly softly'' approach towards Nigeria was hardening.
``He has got the bit between his teeth,'' he said.
And he was hopeful that the British government would eventually impose
sanctions. He said: ``I hope that Mr Major will take a moral stand.''
He was supported by former peace envoy Terry Waite, who said he had seen the
efficacy of sanctions in South Africa and insisted ordinary people would be
behind them.
Mr Waite also spoke movingly about the fate of Mr Saro-Wiwa. ``I myself have
lived under a death sentence and I know there are many people in Nigeria now
who are living under that threat,'' he said.
Mr Saro-Wiwa's brother, Dr Owen Wiwa, 39, who demonstrated last week outside
Shell's London offices, also spoke at the memorial performance at the Theatre
Royal, Haymarket.
He and his wife, Diane, 23, who escaped from Nigeria 10 days ago, spoke of the
``insensitivity'' of Shell and the worsening conditions for the Ogoni people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
